</p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=7:android-inventor&amp;catid=2:structuredevaluations&amp;Itemid=4\"> Android Inventor</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Structured Evaluation | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/26/2010 | <strong>Platform:</strong> Mobile | <strong>Version:</strong> Prelim</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Create Android Applications Easily</p>\r\n<p>One of the challenges in creating mobile applications for public health  consumers is learning the specific programming languages and conventions  associated with each platform. For example, in order to develop for the iPhone a  developer needs to learn <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.apple.com/library/mac/#documentation/Cocoa/Conceptual/ObjectiveC/Introduction/introObjectiveC.html\" target=\"_blank\">Objective-C</a> and install the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.apple.com/technologies/tools/whats-new.html\" target=\"_blank\">XCode</a> integrated  development environment on a Mac OS X computer.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />Google has created a tool called <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://appinventor.googlelabs.com/about/\" target=\"_blank\">Android App Inventor</a> that is targeted towards non-programmers and uses a visual approach to creating mobile platforms for smartphones and other Android devices. App Inventor allows non-programmers to drag and drop lego-block style components and compose them into a useful application that is targeted for mobile devices.</p>\r\n<p><br />We will evaluate this tool to determine how helpful it may be to public health programs and organizations to allow for routine and emergency response mobile applications to be developed for such purposes as in the field surveillance, information dissemination, ad hoc communication and other potential uses.</p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\"> (view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5px\" height=\"1px\" /> <a href=\"images/structured_evaluations/android1.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Android Inventor Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/structured_evaluations/android1_thumb.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Android Inventor  Screenshot\" title=\"Android Inventor Screenshot\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"12px\" height=\"1px\" /> <a href=\"images/structured_evaluations/android2.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Android Inventor Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/structured_evaluations/android2_thumb.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Android Inventor Screenshot\" title=\"Android Inventor Screenshot\" align=\"top\" /></a></p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Resources icon\" title=\"Resources icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> Resources\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8ADwPLSFeY8&amp;feature=player_embedded\" target=\"_blank\">Google\'s App Inventor Demo YouTube Video</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:07:20',62,'','2011-05-23 15:35:06',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:07:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',24,0,11,'','',0,137,'robots=\nauthor='),(8,'  Open Source Data Mining Tools  ','-open-source-data-mining-tools-','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/data_mining_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"data mining icon\" title=\"data mining icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=8:-open-source-data-mining-tools-&amp;catid=2:structuredevaluations&amp;Itemid=4\"> Open Source Data Mining Tools</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Structured Evaluation | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 6/01/2010 | <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version:</strong> Final</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Data Mining Tools for the Public Health Community</p>\r\n<p>This evaluation focused on the evaluation of general purpose open source data  mining software product for the public health community. Data mining tools  which were developed for a specific domain (e.g. text mining, image mining,  microarray data mining, etc.) were not included in this evaluation.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />The data mining software products in this evaluation include: RapidMiner, Weka, Orange, Rattle, and Knime.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Weka</strong> has been selected to undergo agency approval process.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: This evaluation was performed, prior to the development of the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=67:-epi-collect-&amp;catid=2:structuredevaluations&amp;Itemid=4\">Structured Evaluation Tool</a>.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Resources icon\" title=\"Resources icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> Resources\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/OpenSourceDataMining.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Evaluation Report</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,2,'2010-12-08 15:11:30',62,'','2011-05-23 15:44:04',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:11:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',21,0,3,'','',0,180,'robots=\nauthor='),(9,'UUorld','uuorld','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/uuorld_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"UUorld icon\" title=\"Uuorld icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=9:uuorld&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> UUorld</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/05/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/05/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">A Set of 3D Geovisualization and Mapping Tools</p>\r\n<p>The UUorld are 3D geovisualization and mapping tools that include a Pro-version and a free version. The non-commercial version is not intended for commercial use and includes the UUorld logo on all non-commercial version maps.  The software has core functionality to easily build 3D extruded map visualizations in a relatively simple manner.  The UUorld website also includes a data portal with access to thousands of datasets with minimal metadata documentation that can be used with the system.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />The free-version of the software only allows 25 downloads at a time from the Data Portal site.  The software allows some integration with Google maps and Google Earth and the company offers services that would include more robust development for specific use cases for a fee (not specified).</p>\r\n<p><br />The UUorld is somewhat limited in out-of-the-box functionality but does provide some interesting 3D perspectives and 3D views of geospatial data.  This software might have some limited potential use for public health, but would be even better with expanded functionality to meet specific use-cases of public health.  The UUorld data portal does contain some disease datasets from Kaiser Permanente and WHO that they have published for use with the system.</p>\r\n<h2>Background:</h2>\r\n<p>UUorld is not open-source software but does offer a non-commercial software version (free) as well as a commercial version of the software. The UUorld was formed by a core group of geospatial defense developers in DC that have since relocated their offices to San Francisco have have incorporated as UUorld.com.</p>\r\n<h2>Results:</h2>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: general information,  system features, and functionality.</p>\r\n<h4>General Information:</h4>\r\n<p>The UUorld website includes a gallery of user create maps that gives an idea of the types of map products produced (Source: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/gallery/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/gallery</a>).</p>\r\n<h4>System Features:</h4>\r\n<p>The UUorld website includes a Download section with links to purchase the commercial version of the product and a link for a free (non-commercial version).  There are versions of UUorld for Windows, Linux, and Mac OS X operating systems.</p>\r\n<p><br />The website also includes gallery of maps (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/gallery\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/gallery</a>), and a Data Portal (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/portal/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/portal</a>) with thousands of datasets that can be utilized within the system. This data portal also contains some minimal metadata to describe the data source(s), geographic unit of analysis, and year in which the data were produced.</p>\r\n<p><br />The website includes a help section: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/help\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/help</a></p>\r\n<p><br />Four tutorials are included on the website:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Tutorial on custom stats: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=7\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=7</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Tutorial on custom borders: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=6\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=6</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Tutorial on Naming Conventions: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=5\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=5</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Tutorial on Region Lists:  <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=11\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/help?page_id=11</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Functionality:</h4>\r\n<p>Services: (Source: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/services\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/services</a> )</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Advanced mapping</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Google Maps integration</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">KML and Google Earth platform</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Web traffic visualization</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Custom data operations</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Version Comparison:</h2>\r\n<p>(Source: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com/download/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.uuorld.com/download</a>)</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/uuworld_table.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"UUorld version comparison table\" title=\"UUorld version comparison table\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Alternatives:</h2>\r\n<p>The 3D extrusion maps that are created by UUorld may also be constructed with other commercial GIS software such as ArcGIS 10 with the ArcGIS 3D Analyst extension.</p>\r\n<h2>Recommendation:</h2>\r\n<p>The UUorld software may have some potential for 3D visualization of public health data. The pricing of the software and licensing structure for an enterprise organization is not clear. The non-commercial use version of the software will not suffice for public health use and it is likely that agencies would need to purchase the commercial version to have success with the software. CDC and other agencies can build similar 3D Visualizations with existing ArcGIS 10 / 3D Analyst extensions that they may have already purchased for other GIS tasks. This software does include access to a data portal with Kaiser Permanente public health datasets but has limited track record with public health.</p>\r\n<h2>Conclusion:</h2>\r\n<p>The UUorld software has potential for public health use but has limited functionality in terms of the out-of-the-box functionality. The software does provide some compelling 3D extrusion maps but the limited functionality does not allow the public health user to fully customize for their specific use-cases.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"References icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> References <br /><br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.uuorld.com\" target=\"_blank\">UUorld Website</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://datavisualization.ch/showcase/uuorld\" target=\"_blank\">Data Visualization Channel, Dynamically Mapping Your Data with UUorld</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.researchpipeline.com/mediawiki/index.php?title=Main_Page\" target=\"_blank\">Research Pipleline Wiki Pages</a> </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>',1,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-05-10 14:43:18',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',12,0,28,'','',0,97,'robots=\nauthor='),(10,'Appcelerator Titanium','appcelerator-titanium','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/appcelerator_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Appcelerator Titanium icon\" title=\"Appcelerator Titanium icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=10:appcelerator-titanium&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> Appcelerator Titanium</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/19/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 7/22/2010 <br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Cross Platform | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Accelerates Development of Multi-Platform Native Mobile Applications</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.appcelerator.com/\" title=\"Appcelerator\">Appcelerator</a> is a four-year-old company that launched the Titanium suite of products in March 2010. Titamiun accelerates the development of native applications on mobile and desktop platforms. Titanium Mobile, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://github.com/appcelerator\" title=\"Appcelerator open source project\">open-sourced</a> under the Apache Public License v2.0, currently supports development on iPad, iPhone, and Android devices with an April beta version supporting Blackberry.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br /> Appcelerator reports over 50,000 developers using its products to create applications and over 22 Titanium developed apps in the iTunes App Store and/or Android Marketplace. Titanium Community is their free edition, while paying $199-499/month/developer for the Professional and Enterprise editions gives you professional support, app analytics and online training. Appcelerator provides a JavaScript API that is used to develop rich-feature applications that are then built into native applications that deploy and run on both iPhone and Android devices. This is an important distinction as the actual application will be compiled from Objective-C for iPhone/iPad and Java for Android. Producing native applications means that Appcelerator-developed apps will be more responsive and have greater access to device functions than similar application development frameworks that produce only HTML5 / web applications.</p>\r\n<p><br />I installed Titanium Developer 1.2.1 within the lab to test functionality and features. The documentation for Titanium is extensive and includes a community site, video tutorials and robust example projects. Within an hour I was able to compile, build and run a simple project within a emulator for iPhone. With additional time, I was able to get the same Titanium project to compile, build and run within the Android emulator. A single code base in JavaScript results in similar-functioning apps on both iPhone and Android. I did have a small snag with Android in that Titanium requires the 1.6 Android SDK installed even if you are only developing Android 2.2 apps. Initially I only had the 2.2 Android SDK installed and Titanium errored out with cryptic messages until I googled and found that Titanium looks for directories that only exist with the 1.6 Android SDK.</p>\r\n<p><br />Titanium uses a simple directory and file structure to manage JavaScript (.js) files that are used by the Titanium Developer product to generate the native projects for Objective C and Java. In theory this means that a developer using Titanium will never have to see or know Objective-C nor Java. However, in practice knowledge of these languages is useful for configuration and debugging.</p>\r\n<p><br />The positive aspects of this tool are: programming language simplicity, cross-platform, and simplified deployment.  Developers using Titanium need only know JavaScript and the Titanium API to develop rich, full-featured applications on the iPhone, iPad, Android and- eventually- Blackberry. This dependence on JavaScript enables the key value of cross-platform compatibility of coding once (in JavaScript) and deploying onto multiple mobile platforms using their native languages and APIs. Appcelerator\'s committment to additional platforms is shown by their Blackberry beta. The Titanium Developer tool simplifies application compilation, build and deployment to individual devices, the iTunes app store or the Android Marketplace. In fact, the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.appcelerator.com/showcase/applications-showcase/\" title=\"Appcelerator Showcase\">Appcelerator Showcase</a> includes multiple applications developed using Titanium but only released on a single platform, I believe this is due to JavaScript development and simplified deployment tools.</p>\r\n<p><br />The upside of Titanium are overshadowed by significant downsides: lack of IDE, lack of full debugging support, legal and policy issues. Since developers use JavaScript to create apps with Titanium, any IDE that supports JavaScript can be used. But this means there is no direct support within the IDE for graphical layout tools, build and deployment from within the IDE, project management within the IDE and all of the modern amenities developers expect while creating software. When comparing Titanium\'s bring-your-own-IDE philosophy to to Google\'s AndroidSDK+Eclipse or Apple\'s XCode, it is very apparent how having a fully integrated IDE benefits the developer. Titanium does not currently support debugging iPhone apps, although Android debugging is supported. This means that if you need to debug your iPhone apps using Titanium, you need to use the Titanium API\'s logging and messaging functions to write out debug statements. While this is better than nothing, it does not replace actual integrated debugging with its break points and watches. Perhaps the largest negative is the potential conflict with section 3.3.1 of the iOS SDK software licence agreement. Section 3.3.1 includes the language:</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px; \"><br />\"3.3.1 — Applications may only use Documented APIs in the manner prescribed by Apple and must not use or call any private APIs. Applications must be originally written in Objective-C, C, C++, or JavaScript as executed by the iPhone OS WebKit engine, and only code written in C, C++, and Objective-C may compile and directly link against the Documented APIs (e.g., Applications that link to Documented APIs through an intermediary translation or compatibility layer or tool are prohibited).\"</p>\r\n<p><br />Since applications developed with Titanium are originally written in JavaScipt this could be ominous for Titanium developed apps. However Jeff Haynie, Appcelerator\'s CEO, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.appcelerator.com/blog/2010/04/iphone-os-4-0-announcement-and-our-commitment-to-you.html\" title=\"Appcelerator CEO Statement\">thinks that Appcelerator is safe</a> and no Titanium developed apps have been removed from the app store. Appcelerator isn\'t alone as Unity3D, Ansca, MonoTouch, Adobe and others are potentially affected, but this level of fear, uncertainty and doubt should weigh heavily on the decision to use Titanium.</p>\r\n<h2>Overall Insights:</h2>\r\n<p class=\"belowh2\">While Titanium is a great tool for JavaScript developers who don\'t wish to learn Objective-C or Java and prevents teams from having to develop separate code-bases for different mobile platforms, it still seems like a very specific niche for developers. JavaScript is a simpler language than Java and Objective-C, but it still presents a learning curve for app developers. Given the rapid pace of releases for multiple platforms, the newest features can only be accessed using direct APIs from Apple, Google, RIM and others. Until this tool matures and resolves its potential legal issues, new developers should focus on the first-party tools released by mobile platforms for their primary development tools. However, for developers who are already extremely proficient in JavaScript, Appcelerator is something that should be closely examined to see if it fits.</p>\r\n<h2>Quick Facts:</h2>\r\n<ul class=\"sum4\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">License:</span></em> Open Source (paid support and training)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Platform:</span></em> Java (client)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Cost:</span></em> Community edition $0; Profesional and Enterprise pricing varies (previously was $200-500/month/developer)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Potential Public Health Use Cases:</span></em> Conduct Investigation; Process, Store, and Analyze Data; Conduct Epidemiological Research</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>UPDATE 2010.09.09: Apple released a <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.apple.com/pr/library/2010/09/09statement.html\" title=\"Apple app store review guidelines update\">statement updating the app store review guidelines</a> that eases the concerns mentioned above around section 3.3.1 of the iOS SDK license agreement. This removes the possibility that Titanium developed apps would be rejected by the app store.</p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\"> (view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5px\" height=\"1px\" /><a href=\"images/brief_reviews/titaniumdeveloper.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Appcelerator Screenshot - Titanium Developer - Learning\"> <img src=\"images/brief_reviews/titaniumdeveloper_thumb.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Appcelerator Screenshot - Titanium Developer - Learning\" title=\"Appcelerator Screenshot - Titanium Developer - Learning\" /></a><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"12px\" height=\"1px\" /> <a href=\"images/brief_reviews/titaniumscreenshot2.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Appcelerator Screenshot - Titanium Developer - Deployment\"> <img src=\"images/brief_reviews/titaniumscreenshot2_thumb.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Appcelerator Screenshot - Titanium Developer - Deployment\" title=\"Appcelerator Screenshot - Titanium Developer - Deployment\" /></a></p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum5\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Project References icon\" title=\"Project Resources icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.appcelerator.com\" target=\"_blank\">Appcelerator Website</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:25:22',62,'','2011-05-10 14:41:34',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:25:22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',17,0,27,'','',0,108,'robots=\nauthor='),(11,'GeoDa and OpenGeoDa','geoda','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/geo_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"GeoDa icon\" title=\"GeoDa icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=11:geoda&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> GeoDa and OpenGeoDa</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/11/2010 |   <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Prelim</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Exploratory Spatial Data Analysis Tool</p>\r\n<p>The GeoDa and OpenGeoDa tools were built to provide a mechanism to explore spatial data and to examine these data for spatial autocorrelation and spatial dependence.</p>\r\n<p><br />The tools within GeoDa are useful for public health as disease data and populations are often clustered with positive spatial autocorrelation. The OLS regressions assume spatial independence and so it becomes necessary to consider spatial regressions under conditions of spatial  autocorrelation. The GeoDa tools allow researchers to explore their data  spatially and to examine spatial autocorrelation as well as conduct OLS  regressions and spatial regressions and map residuals and examine  clustering of residuals (for example). The parallel coordinate plot (PCP) with linked brushing allows epidemiologists to explore risk factors and outcome variables simultaneously within the same geographic study space. This is a powerful way to examine disease and potential clustering of disease and/or risk factors for disease outcomes.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h2>Background:</h2>\r\n<p><br />GeoDa is an exploratory spatial data analysis (ESDA) and GIS tool that was developed by Dr. Luc Anselin (Arizona State University). Dr. Anselin has formed an entire GeoDa Center to provide support and further research with the GeoDa (legacy tool) and new alpha version of OpenGeoDa (the open-source version of GeoDa).</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />\"The GeoDa Center for Geospatial Analysis and Computation develops state-of-the-art methods for geospatial analysis, geovisualization, geosimulation, and spatial process modeling, implements them through software tools, applies them to policy-relevant research in the social and environmental sciences, and disseminates them through training and support to a growing worldwide community.\"<br /><br />Dr. Luc Anselin, source: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://geodacenter.asu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">http://geodacenter.asu.edu</a></p>\r\n<p><br />GeoDa is a legacy application at this point and new efforts have been directed toward the open-source version, OpenGeoDa, which is currently in alpha version.</p>\r\n<h2>Results:</h2>\r\n<p><br />This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: general information, system features, and functionality.</p>\r\n<h4>General Information:</h4>\r\n<p>The GeoDa Center homepage <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://geodacenter.asu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">(http://geodacenter.asu.edu)</a> includes links on the left navigation bar for many resources including: Tutorials, Support, E-talks, Training, Publications, Presentations, Working Papers, Data, Projects, Downloads, News Headlines related to GeoDa, and external links to other spatial research centers.</p>\r\n<h4>System Features:</h4>\r\n<p><br /><em>GEODA: New Features</em></p>\r\n<p><br />Data Manipulation:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The creation of polygon shapefiles for regular lattices or grids from basic user input on the structure of the lattice.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The construction of polygon shapefiles from boundary information contained in an ascii input file.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />Mapping:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">A circular cartogram, implementing Dorling\'s cellular automata algorithm  (Dorling, 1996), fully linked and brushable.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Conditional maps.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />Exploratory Data Analysis:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Parallel coordinate plot (PCP) for multivariate data exploration, with linking  and brushing.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Three-dimensional scatter plot, with linking and brushing.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Conditional plots, using two conditioning variables to explore the distribution of  a third variable.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Conditional map, box plot, histogram, and scatter plot.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />Spatial Regression:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Ordinary Least Squares regression with full diagnostics for spatial effects  (Moran\'s I, Lagrange Multiplier statistics), as well as the usual tests against heteroskedasticity and non-normality.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Maximum Likelihood estimation of the spatial lag and the spatial error models,  with asymptotic inference.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><br /><em>GEODA: Refinements and Improvements of Existing Features</em></p>\r\n<p><br />User Interface:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The standard menu structure has been slightly reorganized.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">New items for Table, Space, and Regress.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The spatial autocorrelation analysis was moved from the earlier Explore menu to Space.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">An item for Methods has been added to the opening menu to allow  regression analysis without starting a project (i.e.,  without loading a new shapefile into the project).</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The toolbar buttons have been slightly reorganized.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">New toolbar buttons have been added for the Cartogram, PCP, Conditional Plot, and the 3-D Scatter Plot.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">A new dockable toolbar is included with buttons to activate the various  map functions (quantile map, box map, standard deviational map,  percentile map, cartogram, and map movie).</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The spatial autocorrelation toolbar buttons were separated from the EDA toolbar.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> The toolbar buttons for opening a new map and duplicating a map have new look.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> The default map window now shows the legend.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />Spatial Data Manipulation:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">A custom bounding box can be specified in the creation of Thiessen polygons;  previously, only the bounding box for the points themselves was used.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">A higher order contiguity calculation now contains an option for the inclusion of  all lower order neighbors (the previous default) or the computation of a \"pure\" higher order contiguity.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Distance weights files and k-nearest neighbor weights now contain the \"correct\" distance between the points as the third column of the GWT file; previously this value was rescaled and not useful for interpretation.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The \"threshold\" typo has been fixed.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The weights characteristics histogram has a new look and more flexible  classifications, with islands properly included as having zero neighbors.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />Mapping:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The default selection tool for point shapefiles is now the circle  (previously, it was a rectangle).</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The Map Movie was thoroughly revised, with a new interface, allowing Interactive starting and stopping (pause) as well as rewind and step through.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />Exploratory Data Analysis:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The Histogram sports a new look and uses a continuous color ramp.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">The Box Plot has been slightly redesigned and shows the median more distinctly.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />Table:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Table functions can now be invoked from the main menu; previously, this was only by right-clicking in the table.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Alternatives:</h2>\r\n<p>There are commercial software alternatives such as the ArcGIS Geostatistical Analyst Extension and Spatial Analyst Extensions which, through the ArcGIS Toolbox, can provide similar functionality (and much more) to GeoDa but with much more cost. GeoDa is free, and OpenGeoDa is free and open-source. Other commercial products such as TerraSeer / Space-Time Intelligence System  would also compete in terms of similar functions.  The open-source community might have alternatives in the form of R, Python GDAL, or GeoDa Center\'s PySAL.</p>\r\n<h2>Recommendation:</h2>\r\n<p>Dr. Luc Anselin has provided an excellent tool for exploratory spatial data analysis (ESDA), choropleth mapping, and descriptive statistical visualizations with linked brushing. This tool has been widely utilized by public health geographers and epidemiologists (Lai, et. al, 2009).</p>\r\n<p><br />The importance of tools such as GeoDa to examine spatial autocorrelation, perform basic OLS regression, and spatial regressions are critical to public health analyses which are often subject to spatial autocorrelation of disease cases (numerators) and underlying populations (denominators).</p>\r\n<p><br /> The GeoDa includes many tutorials and resources and literature publications to provide public health epidemiologists and geographers with examples of how to apply this very important tool for public health spatial analyses.</p>\r\n<h2>Conclusion:</h2>\r\n<p>GeoDa and OpenGeoDa are right-on-time for public health and the need for tools with spatial and temporal capabilities. The open-source version of GeoDa may be of particular value in the transparence of methodology and potential capacity for modification and customization that may be required within the specialized use-cases of public health spatial epidemiology and spatial analyses.</p>\r\n<p><br />Dr. Luc Anselin shows a lot of leadership in not only providing such a robust tool but also providing lots of documentation and tutorials to encourage public health epidemiologists to incorporate spatial thinking and spatial analytics into their analyses. The robust exploratory spatial data analyses (ESDA) that are possible with the GeoDa tool make it a great addition to the public health toolbox.</p>\r\n<p><br />The linked brushing and linked analytics of histograms, scatter plots and parallel coordinate plots (PCPs) can be helpful for public health epidemiologists to examine risk factors (multiple variables) and outcome variables within the same geographic context, space, and study areas. This multivariate approach can allow the astute epidemiologist or geographer to examine disease and risk factors for disease simultaneously within the same frame of reference along with other factors such as underlying population, poverty, or other factors that may be influencing negative health outcomes.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum5\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Project References icon\" title=\"Project Resources icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> References <br />\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Anselin, L. and Rey, S.J. 2010. Perspectives on Spatial Data Analysis.<br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.springer.com/economics/regional+science/book/978-3-642-01975-3\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.springer.com/economics/regional+science/book/978-3-642-01975-3</a> </li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Anselin, L. 2003. GeoDa 0.9 User\'s Guide. Spatial Analysis Laboratory (SAL).  Department of Agricultural and Consumer Economics, Univ. of Illinois, Urbana Champaign. <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.geodacenter.org/downloads/pdfs/geoda093.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.geodacenter.org/downloads/pdfs/geoda093.pdf</a></li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Dorling, D. 1996. Area Cartograms: Their Use and Creation. CATMOG 59, Institute of British Geographers. </li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Franklin, Janet. 2010. Mapping Species Distributions. Spatial Inference and Prediction.  <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://geodacenter.asu.edu/talks/franklin/\" target=\"_blank\">http://geodacenter.asu.edu/talks/franklin/</a> </li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Lai, P.C., So,F-M., Chan, K-W. 2009. Spatial Epidemiological Approaches in Disease Mapping and Analysis. CRC Press, Taylor&amp;Francis Group. 174 pages.<br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.crcpress.com/product/isbn/9781420045468\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.crcpress.com/product/isbn/9781420045468</a> </li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Murray, A.T. 2009. Geographic space and choropleth display. Book Chapter within  Advances in GIS Research, Springer-Verlag, Berlin (2009).<br /> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/512/\" target=\"_blank\">http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/512/</a></li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">McCann, M. and Anselin, L. 2010. OpenGeoDa, an Open Source Tool for Geovisualization and Exploration.<br /> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/1323/\" target=\"_blank\">http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/1323/</a> </li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Rey, S. and Anselin L. 2010. PySAL: A Python Library for Spatial Analysis and Geocomputation.<br /> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/1324/\" target=\"_blank\">http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/1324</a> </li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Schmidt, C.R. 2010. A web-based, open-source ESDA prototype in a cloud computing environment. <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/1325/\" target=\"_blank\">http://geodacenter.asu.edu/node/1325/</a> </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>',1,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:33:24',62,'','2011-05-23 15:34:49',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:33:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',51,0,26,'','',0,155,'robots=\nauthor='),(12,'  Using Secure Web Services to Visualize Poison Center Data for Nationwide Biosurveillance: A Case Study  ','-using-secure-web-services-to-visualize-poison-center-data-for-nationwide-biosurveillance-a-case-study-','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/graph_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Graph icon\" title=\"Graph icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=12:-using-secure-web-services-to-visualize-poison-center-data-for-nationwide-biosurveillance-a-case-study-&amp;catid=5:publications&amp;Itemid=7\">Using Secure Web Services to Visualize Poison Center Data for Nationwide Biosurveillance: A Case Study</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Visualizing Poison Center Data through Secure Web Services</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\"><br />Thomas G. Savel, Alvin Bronstein, William Duck, M. Barry Rhodes, Brian Lee, John Stinn, Katherine Worthen</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\">Online Journal of Public Health Informatics, Vol 2, No 1 (2010)</p>\r\n<p><br />OBJECTIVES:</p>\r\n<p>Real-time surveillance systems are valuable for timely response to public health emergencies. It has been challenging to leverage existing surveillance systems in state and local communities, and, using a centralized architecture, add new data sources and analytical capacity. Because this centralized model has proven to be difficult to maintain and enhance, the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has been examining the ability to use a federated model based on a secure web services architecture, with data stewardship remaining with the data provider.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />METHODS:</p>\r\n<p>As a case study for this approach, the American Association of Poison Control Centers and the CDC extended an existing data warehouse via a secure web service, and shared aggregate clinical effects and case counts data by geographic region and time period. To visualize these data, CDC developed a web browser-based interface, Quicksilver, which leveraged the Google Maps API and Flot, a javascript plotting library.</p>\r\n<p><br />RESULTS:</p>\r\n<p>Two iterations of the NPDS web service were completed in 12 weeks. The visualization client, Quicksilver, was developed in four months.</p>\r\n<p><br />DISCUSSION:</p>\r\n<p>This implementation of web services combined with a visualization client represents incremental positive progress in transitioning national data sources like BioSense and NPDS to a federated data exchange model.</p>\r\n<p><br />CONCLUSION:</p>\r\n<p>Quicksilver effectively demonstrates how the use of secure web services in conjunction with a lightweight, rapidly deployed visualization client can easily integrate isolated data sources for biosurveillance.</p>\r\n<p><br /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://firstmonday.org/htbin/cgiwrap/bin/ojs/index.php/ojphi/article/view/2920/2505\" target=\"_blank\">View full text in PDF format.</a></p>',1,3,0,5,'2010-12-08 15:36:11',62,'','2011-01-21 15:45:05',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:36:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',15,0,4,'','',0,64,'robots=\nauthor='),(13,'  A Public Health Grid (PHGrid): Architecture and Value Proposition for 21st Century Public Health  ','-a-public-health-grid-phgrid-architecture-and-value-proposition-for-21st-century-public-health-','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/grid_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Public\" title=\"Public Health Grid icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=13:-a-public-health-grid-phgrid-architecture-and-value-proposition-for-21st-century-public-health-&amp;catid=5:publications&amp;Itemid=7\"> A Public Health Grid (PHGrid): Architecture and Value Proposition for 21st Century Public Health</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Grid Computing</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\"><br />Savel T, Hall K, Lee B, McMullin V, Miles M, Stinn J, White P, Washington D,  Boyd T, Lenert L.</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\">National Center for Public Health Informatics, CDC, Atlanta, GA 30333, USA.</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\">Int J Med Inform. 2010 Jul;79(7):523-9. Epub 2010 May 15.</p>\r\n<p><br />PURPOSE:</p>\r\n<p>This manuscript describes the value of and proposal for a  high-level architectural framework for a Public Health Grid (PHGrid), which the authors feel has the capability to afford the public health community a robust technology infrastructure for secure and timely data, information, and knowledge exchange, not only within the public health domain, but between public health and the overall health care system.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />METHODS:</p>\r\n<p>The CDC facilitated multiple Proof-of-Concept (PoC) projects, leveraging an open-source-based software development methodology, to test four hypotheses with regard to this high-level framework. The outcomes of the four PoCs in combination with the use of the Federal Enterprise Architecture Framework (FEAF) and the newly emerging Federal Segment Architecture Methodology (FSAM) was used to develop and refine a high-level architectural framework for a Public Health Grid infrastructure.</p>\r\n<p><br />RESULTS:</p>\r\n<p>The authors were successful in documenting a robust high-level architectural framework for a PHGrid. The documentation generated provided a level of granularity needed to validate the proposal, and included examples of both information standards and services to be implemented. Both the results of the PoCs as well as feedback from selected public health partners were used to develop the granular documentation.</p>\r\n<p><br />CONCLUSIONS:</p>\r\n<p>A robust high-level cohesive architectural framework for a Public Health Grid (PHGrid) has been successfully articulated, with its feasibility demonstrated via multiple PoCs. In order to successfully implement this framework for a Public Health Grid, the authors recommend moving forward with a three-pronged approach focusing on interoperability and standards, streamlining the PHGrid infrastructure, and developing robust and high-impact public health services.</p>',1,3,0,5,'2010-12-08 15:38:03',62,'','2011-02-28 15:35:16',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:38:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',24,0,3,'','',0,145,'robots=\nauthor='),(15,'Brief Reviews','brief-reviews','','<p><img src=\"images/stories/brief_reviews_small.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Brief Reviews icon\" title=\"Brief Reviews icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=category&amp;layout=blog&amp;id=3&amp;Itemid=5\">Brief Reviews</a></p>\r\n<p><br />Short, informal posts reviewing a specific technology, software or p