ts of articles','lots-of-articles','','<p>dsadasda</p>','',-2,1,0,3,'2011-02-15 18:56:00',62,'','0000-00-00 00:00:00',0,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-02-15 18:56:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',1,0,0,'','',0,0,'robots=\nauthor='),(42,'Article Title','test3','','<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php/prototypes/42-test3\">Article Title</a></p>\r\n<p><br />Article content...</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>vontente ngkrlengkdlmngkfdngkfdngkfngfkldngfdngkflgnkflda;glfknglkfd;alfkngkald;flkngkl;lkeweiworjijijio and then she said and then i saide so shw saw me and i was a tree and everything was allrigth really and i don\'tl onow what time ir is why you always asking me that?</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n','\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>so we thought about itt a lto and decided not to do it.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://firstmonday.org/htbin/cgiwrap/bin/ojs/index.php/ojphi/article/view/2920/2505\" target=\"_blank\">View full text in PDF format.</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>',-2,1,0,1,'2011-02-16 15:58:12',62,'','2011-02-16 21:17:41',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-02-16 15:58:12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',7,0,0,'','',0,4,'robots=\nauthor='),(43,'Palantir Technologies Government Platform','palantir-technologies-government-platform','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/palantir_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Palantir logo\" title=\"Palantir logo\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=43:palantir-technologies-government-platform&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Palantir Technologies Government Platform</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 2/11/2011 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 2/14/2011 <br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Cross Platform | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">Complex Information Analysis</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\">Palantir Government</a> is a platform for information analysis. Palantir was designed for environments where the fragments of data that an analyst combines to tell the larger story are spread across a vast set of starting material. Palantir provides flexible tools to import and model data, intuitive constructs to search against this data, and powerful techniques to iteratively define and test hypotheses. With Palantir, an analyst can go all the way from an initial tasking to a final product in hours or days, rather than weeks.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />Palantir Technologies was founded in 2004 by Paypal alumni and Standard computer scientists who wanted to create a platform for integrating, visualizing, and analyzing the world\'s information. Palantir supports many kinds of data including structured, unstructured, relational, temporal, and geospatial. Their products are built for real analysis with a focus on security, scalability, ease of use, and collaboration. Palantir is headquartered in Palo Alto, CA, but has a large presence in the DC area at Tyson\'s Corner, VA.</p>\r\n<p><br />After HHS CTO Todd Park\'s presentation to CDC on December 6th, the lab installed Palantir to access the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"https://analyzethe.us/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://analyzethe.us/\">AnalyzeThe.US</a> public domain data source collected by Palantir Technologies. This data source collects key data sets from data.gov and other public data sources and links them using Palantir\'s platform. The stated goal of the analyzethe.us project is, \"Ultimately, by allowing citizens to analyze our democracy, AnalyzeThe.US democratizes analysis.\"</p>\r\n<p><br />Palantir has solutions for Intelligence, Defense, Financial, Cyber Security and Healthcare; but no specific, dedicated solution for public health.</p>\r\n<p><br />Palantir Government consists of three components:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Data Platform (hosted),</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Application Platform (client-based),</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2 \">Compute Platform (hosted).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />The lab installed the Application Platform which is a Java-based client program that runs on most modern desktop/workstation operating systems.</p>\r\n<p><br />To conduct our investigation we connected to the existing analyzethe.us Data and Compute Platforms so we did not install the server-based Palantir components. Using the Palantir client application, lab researchers ran through saved example investigations to create, analyze and display information assets, links, and connected information. This tool provides four main functions on an analyzed-curated data set based on articles and data items entered or carefully imported:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Seamlessly integrates structured and unstructured data sources</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Provides advanced search &amp; discovery capabilities</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Enables enterprise-wide knowledge management</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Facilitates collaboration across users, groups, and agencies</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Overall Insights:</h2>\r\n<p class=\"belowh2\">The strength of this tool is linkage creation, and would be particularly useful for complex case-based (e.g., outbreak) investigations. It is not a classic (predictive modeling) data mining tool, such as SAS Enterprise Miner, which leverages multiple data sets (training, validation, and test). This tool is not necessarily built for event detection, sense making or emergent intelligence so it may be challenging to deploy in public health scenarios that involve large amounts of timely clinical data (e.g., syndromic surveillance). Although the tool has a strong learning curve, it is excellent for creating linkages and discovering additional relationships. Palantir also has a useful developer\'s SDK and growing list of partner consulting and system integrator firms. Cost does not appear to be trivial, but could not be ascertained, as that information was not visible on their web site, and it appears that financial arrangements are made on a case-by-case basis. Palantir did not respond to requests with cost information.</p>\r\n<p><br />An additional investigation based on a public health specific data set (rather than the data.gov data from analyzethe.us) would help us to better determine the impact for public health.</p>\r\n<h2>Quick Facts:</h2>\r\n<ul class=\"sum4\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">License:</span></em> Commercial</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Platform:</span></em> Hosted/Cloud (server), Java (client)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Cost:</span></em> Varies</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Potential Public Health Use Cases:</span></em> Conduct Investigation; Data Management; Process, Store, and Analyze Data; Conduct Epidemiological Research</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\"> (view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5px\" height=\"1px\" /><a href=\"images/brief_reviews/palantirscreenshot1analyzetheus.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Palantir Screenshot - Analyzethe.us Investigation\"> <img src=\"images/brief_reviews/palantir_thumb.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Palantir Screenshot - Analyzethe.us Investigation\" title=\"Palantir Screenshot - Analyzethe.us Investigation\" /></a></p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum5\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Project References icon\" title=\"Project Resources icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"> Palantir Government Product Page: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\">http://www.palantirtech.com/government</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Investment Profile on Palantir Technologies: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies\">http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Sample Data Set: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"https://analyzethe.us/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://analyzethe.us/\">https://analyzethe.us/</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Demo video for Palantir Government: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government/videos/fullct\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government/videos/fullct\">http://www.palantirtech.com/government/videos/fullct</a> </li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,3,'2011-02-17 14:51:36',63,'BAL','2011-05-10 14:38:14',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-02-17 14:51:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',28,0,25,'','',0,119,'robots=\nauthor='),(44,'palantir_test','palantirtest','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/palantir_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Palantir logo\" title=\"Palantir logo\" align=\"left\" style=\"border: 0px initial initial;\" /><a href=\"index.php/brief-reviews/43-palantir-technologies-government-platform\">Palantir Technologies Government Platform</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 2/14/2011 | <strong>Platform:</strong> Cross Platform | <strong>Version: </strong>Prelim</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Complex Information Analysis</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\">Palantir Government</a> is a platform for information analysis. Palantir was designed for environments where the fragments of data that an analyst combines to tell the larger story are spread across a vast set of starting material. Palantir provides flexible tools to import and model data, intuitive constructs to search against this data, and powerful techniques to iteratively define and test hypotheses. With Palantir, an analyst can go all the way from an initial tasking to a final product in hours or days, rather than weeks.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />Palantir Technologies was founded in 2004 by Paypal alumni and Standard computer scientists who wanted to create a platform for integrating, visualizing, and analyzing the world‚Äôs information. Palantir supports many kinds of data including structured, unstructured, relational, temporal, and geospatial. Their products are built for real analysis with a focus on security, scalability, ease of use, and collaboration.Palantir is headquartered in Palo Alto, CA but has a large presence in the DC area at Tyson\'s Corner, VA.</p>\r\n<p><br />After HHS CTO Todd Park\'s presentation to CDC on December 6th, the lab installed Palantir to access the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"https://analyzethe.us/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://analyzethe.us/\">AnalyzeThe.US</a> public domain data source collected by Palantir Technologies. This data source collects key data sets from data.gov and other public data sources and links them using Palantir\'s platform. The stated goal of the analyzethe.us project is, \"Ultimately, by allowing citizens to analyze our democracy, AnalyzeThe.US democratizes analysis.\"</p>\r\n<p><br />Palantir has solutions for Intelligence, Defense, Financial, Cyber Security and Healthcare; but no specific, dedicated solution for public health.</p>\r\n<p><br />Palantir Government consists of three components:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Data Platform (hosted),</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Application Platform (client-based),</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2 \">Compute Platform (hosted).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />The lab installed the Application Platform which is a Java-based client program that runs on most modern desktop/workstation operating systems.</p>\r\n<p><br />To conduct our investigation we connected to the existing analyzethe.us Data and Compute Platforms so we did not install the server-based Palantir components. Using the Palantir client application, lab researchers ran through saved example investigations to create, analyze and display information assets, links, and connected information. This tool provides four main functions on an analyzed-curated data set based on articles and data items entered or carefully imported:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Seamlessly integrates structured and unstructured data sources</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Provides advanced search &amp; discovery capabilities</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Enables enterprise-wide knowledge management</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Facilitates collaboration across users, groups, and agencies</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Overall Insights:</h2>\r\n<p><br />The strength of this tool is linkage creation, and would be particularly useful for complex case-based (e.g., outbreak) investigations. It is not a classic (predictive modeling) data mining tool, such as SAS Enterprise Miner, which leverages multiple data sets (training, validation, and test).This tool is not necessarily built for event detection, sense making or emergent intelligence so it may be challenging to deploy in public health scenarios that involve large amounts of timely clinical data (e.g., syndromic surveillance). Although the tool has a strong learning curve, it is excellent for creating linkages and discovering additional relationships. Palantir also has a useful developer\'s SDK and growing list of partner consulting and system integrator firms. Cost does not appear to be trivial, but could not be ascertained, as that information was not visible on their web site, and it appears that financial arrangements are made on a case-by-case basis. Palantir did not respond to requests with cost information.</p>\r\n<p><br />An additional investigation based on a public health specific data set (rather than the data.gov data from analyzethe.us) would help us to better determine the impact for public health.</p>\r\n<h2>Quick Facts:</h2>\r\n<ul class=\"sum4\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">License:</span></em> Commercial</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Platform:</span></em> Hosted/Cloud (server), Java (client)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Cost:</span></em> Varies</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"><em><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Potential Public Health Use Cases:</span></em> Conduct Investigation; Data Management; Process, Store, and Analyze Data; Conduct Epidemiological Research</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Project References icon\" title=\"Project Resources icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"> Palantir Government Product Page: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government\">http://www.palantirtech.com/government</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Investment Profile on Palantir Technologies: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies\">http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Sample Data Set: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"https://analyzethe.us/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://analyzethe.us/\">https://analyzethe.us/</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Demo video for Palantir Government: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government/videos/fullct\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.palantirtech.com/government/videos/fullct\">http://www.palantirtech.com/government/videos/fullct</a> </li>\r\n</ul>',0,1,0,3,'2011-02-28 17:01:29',62,'','2011-02-28 19:45:05',62,62,'2011-03-07 20:18:55','2011-02-28 17:01:29','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',32,0,24,'','',0,60,'robots=\nauthor='),(45,'Wiki Content','wiki-content','','<p>This is the wiki content.</p>','',-2,5,0,7,'2011-03-10 18:54:08',62,'','2011-03-10 20:28:50',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-03-10 18:54:08','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',2,0,0,'','',0,23,'robots=\nauthor='),(46,'Wiki Summary','wiki','','<p>Our wiki is powered by<em><strong> </strong>MediaWiki</em> software and will open in a <strong>new window</strong>.</p>\r\n<p><br />MediaWiki uses a simplified markup language for formatting. To learn more about the markup used in MediaWiki, please see <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Formatting\" target=\"_blank\">Help: Formatting</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><br /><img src=\"images/stories/new_window.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"link opens in a new window\" title=\"link opens in a new window\" /> <a class=\"smallish\" href=\"mediawiki/index.php/Main_Page\" target=\"_blank\">Go to the Wiki</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>','',1,5,0,7,'2010-12-29 14:19:54',62,'','2011-03-29 15:21:07',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-29 14:19:54','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=0\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',13,0,1,'','',0,16,'robots=\nauthor='),(48,'OpenMRS:  An Open Source Electronic Medical Record System','openmrs-an-open-source-electronic-medical-record-system','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OPENMRS icon\" title=\"OPENMRS icon\" width=\"80\" height=\"53\" align=\"left\" style=\"float: left; border: 0;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=48:openmrs-an-open-source-electronic-medical-record-system&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> OpenMRS:  An Open Source Electronic Medical Record System</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong> Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 3/28/2011 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 3/28/2011 <br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Cross Platform | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">Access to an Example EHR System</p>\r\n<p>Given all the national activity around Electronic Health Records  (EHR), the R&amp;D team felt it was of value to provide the public  health community access to an example EHR system, and gain a practical  understanding of what healthcare providers are now experiencing on a  daily basis. The log-in credentials and links to the example EHR system are below:</p>\r\n<p><br /><span style=\"padding-left: 25px; position: relative; bottom: 5px;\"><strong>Username:</strong> guest                <strong>Password:</strong> Passw0rd</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><span style=\"padding-left: 25px; position: relative; bottom: 10px;\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://207.138.115.204/openmrs-standalone\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>External</strong></a> lab link <span style=\"padding-left:2px; padding-right:2px;\">|</span> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://172.16.100.250/openmrs-standalone\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Internal</strong></a> lab link</span></p>\r\n','\r\n<h2>Per Wikipedia:</h2>\r\n<p><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://openmrs.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">OpenMRS</a> is a collaborative <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_source\" target=\"_blank\">open source</a> project to develop excellent software to support the delivery of health care in developing countries.<sup id=\"cite_ref-0\" class=\"reference\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenMRS#cite_note-0\" target=\"_blank\"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> It grew out of the critical need to scale up the treatment of <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIV\" target=\"_blank\">HIV</a> in <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Africa\" target=\"_blank\">Africa</a> but from the start was conceived as a general purpose electronic medical record system that could support the full range of medical treatments.</p>\r\n<p><br />OpenMRS is founded on the principles of openness and sharing of  ideas,  software and strategies for deployment and use. The system is  designed  to be usable in very resource poor environments and can be  modified with  the addition of new data items, forms and reports without  programming.  It is intended as a platform that many organizations can  adopt and  modify avoiding the need to develop a system from scratch.</p>\r\n<h2>Design:</h2>\r\n<p>OpenMRS is based on a \"concept dictionary\" that describes all the   data items that can be stored in the system such as clinical findings, laboratory test results or socio-economic data. This approach avoids the   need to modify the database structure to add new diseases for example, and facilitates sharing of data dictionaries between projects and sites. An important features of OpenMRS is its modular construction  which  allows the programming of new functions without modifying the  core code. OpenMRS is web based but can be deployed on a single laptop or on a large server and runs on <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux\" target=\"_blank\">Linux</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Windows\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Microsoft Windows\">Windows</a> or <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mac_OS_X\" target=\"_blank\">Mac OS X</a>.</p>\r\n<p><br />Other key features of OpenMRS:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Built on the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MySQL\" target=\"_blank\">MySQL</a> database (but uses <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hibernate_%28Java%29\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Hibernate (Java)\">Hibernate</a> allowing it to be ported to other databases)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Programmed in <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_%28programming_language%29\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Java (programming language)\">Java</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Includes tools for data export and reporting</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Versions currently exist for <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AIDS\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"AIDS\">HIV/AIDS</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-drug-resistant_tuberculosis\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Multi-drug-resistant tuberculosis\">drug resistant TB</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primary_care\" target=\"_blank\">primary care</a> and <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oncology\" target=\"_blank\">oncology</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Supports open standards for medical data exchange including <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HL7\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"HL7\">HL7</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LOINC\" target=\"_blank\">LOINC</a> and IXF</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>',1,1,0,3,'2011-03-29 18:11:18',62,'','2012-01-17 18:42:23',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-03-29 18:11:18','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',15,0,23,'','',0,76,'robots=\nauthor='),(47,'Tags','tags','','<!--Making space for tag cloud module to display-->\r\n<p><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></p>','',1,4,0,6,'2011-03-24 14:13:43',62,'','2011-03-24 19:19:41',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-03-24 14:13:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=0\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',17,0,1,'','',0,11,'robots=\nauthor='),(49,'Share an Idea E-mail','share-an-idea-content','','<p><img src=\"images/stories/email_us.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"E-mail Us icon\" title=\"E-mail Us icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"larger\">E-mail Us</p>\r\n<p><br />Submitted ideas are read and reviewed by the R&amp;D Lab team. Please be sure to include your e-mail address and name. We may follow up for additional information regarding your idea, if necessary. Please e-mail <a class=\"reg\" href=\"mailto:InformaticsLab@cdc.gov\"><img src=\"images/irdu_mail.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"IRDU e-mail\" title=\"IRDU e-mail\" align=\"absbottom\" /></a> or use the form below to contact us.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>{jcomments off}</p>','',1,5,0,9,'2010-12-29 19:01:55',62,'','2011-05-24 18:55:11',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-29 19:01:55','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=0\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',27,0,1,'','',0,23,'robots=\nauthor='),(50,'MapWindow GIS','mapwindow','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/mapwindow_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"MapWindow icon\" title=\"MapWindow icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=50:mapwindow&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> MapWindow GIS</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/05/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/05/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">An Open-Source Geographic Information System (GIS)</p>\r\n<p>The MapWindow application is a ready-to-use spatial data viewer, and a tool that can be modified into a new custom application. (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.mapwindow.org</a>).</p>\r\n<p><br />The MapWindow consists of the main MapWindow application, Core Components, and plug-ins. The main MapWindow application is the central interface and is a stand-alone GIS application.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h2>Background:</h2>\r\n<p>The core components are MapWinGIS (an ActiveX control that may be placed into any project in any programming language that supports ActiveX).  This ActiveX component is the main map component of the software.  Another core component is the MapWinInterfaces (also called the plugin interface).</p>\r\n<p><br />The MapWinInterfaces is a DLL file which will allow developers to write their own plugins to the main MapWindow application. These plug-ins can be authored with any programming language that supports the creation and use of Windows Dynamic Linked Libraries (DLLs). The final portion of MapWinow are the plug-ins (user-authored extensions to MapWindow). Four main plug-ins are included in the main MapWindow application: Table Editor, Shapefile Editor, GIS Tools, and Feature Identifier/Labeler.</p>\r\n<p><br />The MapWindow software is accompanied by a large user community, user guides, developer guides, wikis, discussion forums, mailing lists, an issue tracking system, internationalization, overall project management, an open-source team, soure code repositories, sample code for developers, script directories, user-authored plug-ins, and tutorials.  A distinguishing characteristic of this software is that it is free to use and redistribute to your clients and other end users.  The whole point of MapWindow is to provide an core application that can be customized and redistributed for specific use-cases.</p>\r\n<p><br />Much work has been done with MapWindow for the purpose of hydrology and hydrological research.  The University of Bristol is using MapWindow GIS software within their coursework on GIS for Health Research and Public Health (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.epi.bris.ac.uk/shortc/gis.htm\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.epi.bris.ac.uk/shortc/gis.htm</a>).</p>\r\n<h2>Results:</h2>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: general information, system features, and functionality.</p>\r\n<h4>General Information:</h4>\r\n<p>The MapWindow software development is lead by Dr. Daniel Ames (Idaho State University), but it should be noted that there are hundreds or thousands of MapWindow developers that are part of the project. Dr. Ames is working with the members of the MapWindow Open Source Team to continue to develop and deploy MapWindows under the Mozilla Public License 1.1.  <br />(Source:  <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/why.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/why.php</a> )</p>\r\n<h4>System Features:</h4>\r\n<p>(Source: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/mapwinapp.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/mapwinapp.php</a>)</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Standard Toolbars</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Additional plug-in menus</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Functionality:</h4>\r\n<p>(Source: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/mapwinapp.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/mapwinapp.php</a>)</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Turning plug-ins on and off</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Creating and editing MapWindow projects</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Adding map data to projects</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Using the legend to control layers</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Changing layer display properties</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Adding a label to a layer</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Adding a color scheme to layers</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Display and modify map scale bar</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Map navigation</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Finding map information (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Measuring shapes (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Printing and exporting maps</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Using projections</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Editing/creating data or layers (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Editing layers (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Using table editor to edit attribute table (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Create or update length, area, or perimeter attributes (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Table editor field calculator functions (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Using document launcher to add hotlinks (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Buffer shapes (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Snapping new features to other shapefiles (vector)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">GISTools Plug-in User\'s Guide</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Support for vector, raster, imagery including ESRI grids, ASCII grids, GeoTiff grids, and USU Binary grids</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Shape2Earth plug-in to export shapefiles to KML for Google Earth</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Alternatives:</h2>\r\n<p>While there are other open-source GIS Desktop applications with extensibility such as uDig, gvSIG, and GRASS, MapWindow is somewhat unique in the fact that it is free, modifiable, and redistributable in modified form.</p>\r\n<h2>Recommendation:</h2>\r\n<p>The MapWindow software has a track record of success with federal agencies such as NOAA and for use within hydrology and hydrologic research. A commonly used plug-in for MapWindows is the BASINS 4 plug-in developed by EPA (BASINS, 2007) as well as with humanitarian aid mapping (MapAction, 2009).  MapWindow also has some limited track record for disease surveillance for public health (Changsang et al, 2009).</p>\r\n<p><br />The MapWindow software could have great potential utility for environmental public health issues surrounding toxic spills, runoff, and hydrology related transport of toxic substances that might have negative health effects.</p>\r\n<h2>Conclusion:</h2>\r\n<p>MapWindow is a useful, free, customizable, and freely re-distributable software with potential utility for public health.  The software has a track record of success with NOAA and EPA. HHS and CDC should consider use of MapWindow software to supplement their GIS toolbox and complement their existing commercial software investments. MapWindow will not be a replacement for commercial GIS software but could complement the commercial software and would provide a mechanism to freely re-distribute GIS software with basic functionality to resource challenged environments that may not be able to afford commercial GIS tools.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"References icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> References <br /><br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Ames, D.P., Gover, D. and MapWindow Open Source Team  2007.<br /> <em>MapWinGIS Reference Manual — A function guide for the free MapWindow GIS Active X map component.</em></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Ames, D.P. 2006. <em>Getting Started with the MapWinGIS ActiveX Control</em>.   <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org/downloads/documentation/UsingMapWinGIS.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.mapwindow.org/downloads/documentation/UsingMapWinGIS.pdf</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"> Anselmo, A. 2005. <em>MapWindow Plug-in Development — Sample Project: Simple Path Analyzer Plug-in, A step-by-step guide to creating a custom MapWindow Plug-in using the IPlugin interface.</em> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/documentation.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/documentation.php</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">BASINS, 2007. URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.epa.gov/waterscience/basins/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.epa.gov/waterscience/basins</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Chansang, C., Nakhapakorn, K., Chansang, U., and Sawanpanyalert, P. 2009.<br /> <em>Disease Mapping for Surveillance and Control at House Level Using Geoinformation Freeware.</em><br />Journal of Health Science, 2009; 18:883-93. </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Michaelis, C.  2005. <em>MapWindow GIS ActiveX Control.</em> <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/documentation.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.mapwindow.org/pages/documentation.php</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Akkala, A., Devabhaktuni, V., and Kumar, A.  2010.  <em>Software Review:  Interpolation techniques and associated software for environmental data.</em><br /> Environmental Progress &amp; Sustainable Energy. Vol 29(2).  Pages 134-141. </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Ford, R.E. 2009. <em>Integrating GIS into eHealth initiatives in Africa.</em> Ver 8.  Nov. 2009.  <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://idrc-gisworkshop.pbworks.com/f/FINAL_eHealth_GIS_Report8rev.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://idrc-gisworkshop.pbworks.com/f/FINAL_eHealth_GIS_Report8rev.pdf</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Hintze, P. and Lakes, T.  2009. <em>Geographically Referenced Data for Social Science.</em> <br />German Council for Social and Economic Data (RatSWD).  <br /> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.ratswd.de/download/RatSWD_WP_2009/RatSWD_WP_125.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ratswd.de/download/RatSWD_WP_2009/RatSWD_WP_125.pdf</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Kamadjeu, R. and Tollentino, H.  2008. <em>Web-based public health geographic information systems for resources-constrained environment using scalable vector graphics technology: a proof of concept applied to the expanded program on immunization data.</em><br />International Journal of Health Geographics.  Vol 5:24.    <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/24/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/24</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Madzudzo, P.F.  2007. <em>Exploratory Visualization of Temporal Events in Epidemiological Research:  Case Study of Black Death.</em> <br />Thesis (PhD).  The Netherlands: ITC.    <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.itc.nl/library/papers_2007/msc/gfm/madzudzo.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.itc.nl/library/papers_2007/msc/gfm/madzudzo.pdf</a> </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>',1,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-05-10 14:44:45',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',4,0,22,'','',0,29,'robots=\nauthor='),(51,'OpenJUMP GIS','openjump','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/openjump_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=51:openjump&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> OpenJUMP GIS</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/13/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/13/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">An Open-Source Geographic Information System (GIS) Written in Java</p>\r\n<p>OpenJUMP GIS software appears to seek a middle-ground between basic and fundamental open-source GIS and more advanced GIS. The middle-ground also provides some extension through Python programming and plugins. The tool does support basic overlay, vector editing, and spatial queries with some topological tools as well. The overall look and feel of OpenJUMP is not complicated and seems to provide a friendly user-interface that may appeal to both new and seasoned GIS users.</p>\r\n<p><br />The advanced and very advanced GIS users may not be satisfied with OpenJUMP but it may strike a perfect match for new users or intermediate users that require basic GIS without a complicated interface. There are very few examples of public health/epidemiology use of this tool within the literature but this could be due to the relatively young age of the OpenJUMP (2009).</p>\r\n','\r\n<h2>Background:</h2>\r\n<p>OpenJUMP is an open source Geographic Information System (GIS) written  in the Java programming language. It is developed and maintained by a  group of volunteers from around the globe. OpenJUMP started as JUMP  designed by Vivid Solutions. OpenJUMP can read and write shapefiles and  simple GML files.</p>\r\n<p><br />There is limited support for WMS and WFS web services. The primary  strength is within the editing capabilities for geometry and attribute  data. The user can style maps and export to SVG format. There are a  growing number of vector analysis tools for topologic analysis and  overlay. OpenJUMP 1.3 release has new functionality that can be added by  advanced users with the Python language and Raster GIS capability with  SEXTANTE GIS extension. OpenJUMP has limits in reading very large  datasets and limited support for cartographic projections.There is  limited support for WMS and WFS web services. The primary strength is  within the editing capabilities for geometry and attribute data. The  user can style maps and export to SVG format. There are a growing number  of vector analysis tools for topologic analysis and overlay. OpenJUMP  1.3 release has new functionality that can be added by advanced users  with the Python language and Raster GIS capability with SEXTANTE GIS  extension. OpenJUMP has limits in reading very large datasets and  limited support for cartographic projections.</p>\r\n<h2>Results:</h2>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: general information, system features, and functionality.</p>\r\n<p><br />There are many resources for OpenJUMP including tutorials, user docs, developer docs, articles, user map, user forum, email lists, wiki, openjump support, a bug tracking system, a feature request system, a pilot project, external links, and contact information. There are also additional OpenJUMP plugins.</p>\r\n<h4>System Features:</h4>\r\n<p>(Steiniger, 2009)</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Vector GIS that can read rasters as well.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Not just a demo viewer, but you can edit, save, analyze, conflate, and display data.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Operates on Windows, Linux, and Mac OSX platforms as it is JAVA-based.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">An excellent framework for rapid prototyping.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Freely distributed under the GNU GPL license.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Data Formats:</h4>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Reads GML, SHP, DXF, JM, MIF, TIFF, JPG, MrSID, ECW, as well as from PostGIS, ArcSDE, Oracle, and MySQL.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Writes: GML, SHP, DXF, PostGIS, JML &amp; JPG</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Supports: OGC WMS &amp; WFS (-T), GML 2 SLD</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Editing &amp; Conflation:</h4>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Drawing points, lines, polygons, circles</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Adding, moving, deleting vertices</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Rotating, scaling, auto-complete polygon</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Cut, merge, simplify polygons and lines</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Warping, quality assurance tools</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Vector Analysis &amp; Query:</h4>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Spatial and attribute query functions</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Calculating length, area, centroid, buffer, convex hull</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Topology tools: line noder, polygonizer, planar graph</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Attribute transfer tools (1:1 transfer, or n:1 transfer)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Raster analysis via SEXTANTE connector</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Customization:</h4>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Provides an API, scripting via BeanShell and Java Python</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">(Java) plugin-system</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Alternatives:</h2>\r\n<p>There are other open-source desktop GIS options including: uDig, Quantum GIS, MapWindow, gvSIG, and GRASS GIS.</p>\r\n<p><br />The OpenJUMP software provides some basic GIS capabilities and potential to expand with Python programming for advanced geoprocessing. The OpenJUMP GIS software provides a simple graphic user interface without an overwhelming number of controls and this can make the initial user experience less intimidating than other GIS software. The tool provides some nice vector layer editing capabilities and has some limited support for Web Mapping Services (WMS) and Web Feature Services (WFS) through plugins. The support for WMS and WFS is not native to the main application as it is within uDig (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://udig.refractions.net\" target=\"_blank\">http://udig.refractions.net</a> ).</p>\r\n<h2>Recommendation:</h2>\r\n<p>OpenJUMP is a Java-based application is cross-platform and can run on  Windows, Linux, or Mac and this is nice. The OpenJUMP does support some  nice geoprocessing capabilities such as buffering, Thiessen polygon  creation, convex hull creation, multiple ring buffering, as well as some  capability for generalization, spatial queries, unions, intersects, and  overlay as well as some topological quality assurance tools to compare  geometries between layers. The OpenJUMP tool seems to have a nice blend  of some very basic and intermediate GIS capability but does not have  more advanced spatial interpolation or kriging tools that one might find  in other more complicated commercial GIS or within tools such as GRASS  GIS or R. There does not seem to be a lot of adoption of OpenJUMP by the  medical/epidemiological community, but the tool itself is relatively  new.</p>\r\n<h2>Conclusion:</h2>\r\n<p>OpenJUMP appears to see a GIS middle-ground and strike a balance between  basic GIS functionality and a friendly user interface with advanced  plugin and Python support for advanced GIS users. The Java-based  OpenJUMP is cross-platform and this can be very useful within  environments with multiple operating systems. The OpenJUMP tool provides  enough basic GIS functionality that beginner and intermediate GIS users  may find this tool very useful.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"References icon\" align=\"absmiddle\" /> References <br /><br />\r\n<li class=\"sum2\"> Narayanan, M., Mohan, A., and Gayatri, R. 2007. <em>Web GIS for Tamil Nadu Using FOSS.</em><br /> Map World Forum. Hyderbad, India, Proceedings — Web GIS 2007. <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.gisdevelopment.net/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.gisdevelopment.net/</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Steiniger, S. and E. Bocher (2009): <em>An overview on current free and open source desktop GIS developments.</em><br /> International Journal of Geographical Information Sciences 29 (10): 1345-1370.  <br /> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://terragis.net/docs/presentations/sstein_foss_desktop_gis_overview.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://terragis.net/docs/presentations/sstein_foss_desktop_gis_overview.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"> Steiniger, S. 2009. <em>OpenJUMP: Jump Unified Mapping Platform.</em> Descriptive Flyer.   <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.jump-pilot.sourceforge.net/download/ojlogo/openjumpflyer_v3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.jump-pilot.sourceforge.net/download/ojlogo/openjumpflyer_v3.pdf</a> </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>',1,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-05-10 14:50:52',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',6,0,21,'','',0,431,'robots=\nauthor='),(52,'uDig GIS','udig','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=52:udig&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> uDig GIS</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/05/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/05/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">An Open-Source Geographic Information System (GIS)</p>\r\n<p>UDig:     User-Friendly Desktop Internet GIS Version 1.1.0  http://udig.refractions.net/</p>\r\n<p>Executive Summary:</p>\r\n<p>UDig is an open-source Geographic Information System (GIS) desktop software (http://udig.refractions.net).   The software contains many features that may have potential utility for public health.   The software includes a welcome tutorial to get started using the software as well as a comprehensive HELP section of the software.</p>\r\n<p>The software includes wizards and dialogue boxes that help guide new users to perform basic functions such as adding data to maps, exporting maps, importing projects, and style editing.   The ADD DATA capacity includes the ability to add ArcSDE layers, database tables, graphic files, MySQL tables, Oracle Spatial tables, PostGIS tables, Web Feature Services (WFS), and Web Mapping Services (WMS).</p>\r\n<p>The software has a certain familiar look and feel for those public health users that already have GIS experience with commercial mapping software such as ArcGIS.</p>\r\n<p>The graphic user interface for UDig is robust without being overly complicated.</p>\r\n<p>The window panes are organized in a manner consistent with typical software development within the Eclipse framework and so many computer scientists will feel very comfortable with the look and feel as well as the overall operation of the software.</p>\r\n<p>The software also includes a Tip of the Day and a full section on ‚ÄúTips and Tricks‚Äù.</p>\r\n<p>UDig includes a style editor that appears to incorporate color standards from ColorBrewer (http://colorbrewer2.org/ ) and these are important features for map readers with color blindness.</p>\r\n<p>The process of adding shapefiles as data layers within a UDig map is not as intuitive as the process for adding WMS or WFS services.   It is unclear why the designers have a separate process to add shapefiles but this could be confusing for new users.</p>\r\n<p>Background:</p>\r\n<p>There are many open-source GIS tools that are available and many of these are available through an Open-Source Geospatial Foundation (OSGeo):  http://www.osgeo.org/ The goal of the OSGeo foundation is to build the highest quality  Open-source geospatial software.</p>\r\n<p>The OSGeo contributed geospatial libraries (GeoTools) (http://www.geotools.org/) that are utilized within UDig.   GeoTools are an open source Java GIS Toolkit that conforms to Open Geospatial Consortium specifications (http://www.opengeospatial.org/).   UDig is built upon a foundation of Eclipse (http://www.eclipse.org/).  Eclipse is a multi-language, open source, software development environment and open-source community created by IBM to foster open-source software development.  One may use various open-source languages with Eclipse including:  Java, Python,  C, C++, COBOL, Perl, PHP, Scala, and Ruby.  UDig is built upon the Eclipse framework and is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL).   The UDig product includes software developed by the Eclipse Foundation, GeoTools, and the Apache Software Foundation (http://www.apache.org/).    Canadian geographers have also contributed financially through the GeoConnections (http://cgdi.gc.ca/CGDI.cfm).</p>\r\n<p>Results</p>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: general information,  system features, and functionality.</p>\r\n<p>General Information:  The overall look and feel and operation of the UDig software is very good and operates in a very similar manner to commercial GIS software.  The interface will appeal to both new users of GIS as well as software developers and engineers within the public health organizations as this is based upon the Eclipse workbench.</p>\r\n<p>System Features:  -       Tutorials and Comprehensive Help Documentation  -       Shapefile support.  -       Web Mapping Service (WMS) and Web Feature Service (WFS) support.  -       Web cataloging of WMS and WFS service connections  -       ColorBrewer color standards  -       Projection / Re-Projection capability using standard or custom projections  -       On-the-fly reprojection  -       Community Plug-in extensibility  -       A UDig 1.1 Discovery Site  -       LGPL licensing  -       Cartographic elements:  scalebars, legends, map titles, etc  -       Thematic map classification with  Quantile or Equal Interval methods  -       Rollback of changes and Undo features</p>\r\n<p>Functionality:  -       Bookmarking of spatial extents within the map  -       Multiple map projects with multiple tables of contents containing layers  -       Ability to add graphics to the maps  -       Ability to view feature attribute tables of shapefiles  -       Display of map coordinates and coordinate system and ability to change.  -       Geometry validation of vector features.  -       Feature Selection and counting of selected features  -       Feature editing, creation of new features, vector / vertices editing  -       Identification tool, Selection tool, Pan, Zoom, traditional navigation  -       uDig update manager  -       Eclipse plug-in support  -       Buffer, Intersection, Clip, Split  -       Coming soon:  Merge, Trim Line, Arc, Parallel, Dissolve, Spatial Join Geometries  -       Extensions developed during Google Summer of Code including feature transformation, rubbersheeting, inverse distance weighted interpolation, spline interpolation.</p>\r\n<p>Alternatives:  The Open Source Geospatial Foundation (OSGeo) lists several alternative open-source GIS desktop mapping applications including GRASS, Quantum GIS, OSSIM, and gvSIG that are projects of OSGeo.   MapWindow is another open-source desktop GIS application that has been used by NOAA and other federal agencies.</p>\r\n<p>Recommendation:  UDig also has a small track record of success with public health GIS and epidemiology.  Open-source GIS software has a place within public health research and has been used for HIV/AIDS management and other studies (Vanmeulebrouk et. al, 2008).  This software is free, open-source, easy to use, and contains many of the same functions of commercial desktop GIS software.  Open-source GIS tools could be used as a low cost alternative for public health departments in resource challenged areas that may not be able to afford commercial GIS software (Kamadjeu and Tolentino, 2008).</p>\r\n<p>Conclusion:  The UDig open-source is truly a User-friendly Desktop Internet GIS (UDig).  UDig provides tutorials and a comprehensive help section which is very helpful for new users.   This open source software provides many of the functions that are found within commercial desktop GIS software.   The operation of the software is straight forward and simple to follow with the possible exception of the process to add shapefiles to the map.   The public health community still relies on shapefiles to some extent and so this is one area that could be improved.  The UDig software follows standards for projections, colors, classification, and provides limited cartographic elements for maps.  This open-source desktop GIS could be a very useful addition to the public health toolbox.   This tool has been used extensively by the Canadian government through their GeoConnections national portal : http://www.geoconnections.org/en/aboutGeo/projects/id=416</p>\r\n<p>References:  Kamadjeu, R. and Tollentino, H.  2008.  Web-based public health geographic information systems for resources-constrained environment using scalable vector graphics technology: a proof of concept applied to the expanded program on immunization data.  International Journal of Health Geographics.  Vol 5:24.  URL:   http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/24/</p>\r\n<p>Madzudzo, P.F.  2007.  Exploratory Visualization of Temporal Events in Epidemiological Research:  Case Study of Black Death.   Thesis (PhD).  The Netherlands: ITC.  URL:  http://www.itc.nl/library/papers_2007/msc/gfm/madzudzo.pdf</p>\r\n<p>Ramsey, P.  2004.  User Friendly Desktop Internet GIS (uDig) for OpenGIS Spatial Data Infrastructures.    URL:  http://udig.refractions.net/files/docs/udig-summary.pdf</p>\r\n<p>UDig Case Studies:   URL: http://udig.refractions.net/files/docs/uDigCaseStudies.pdf/</p>\r\n<p>UDig Fact Sheet:  URL:  http://udig.refractions.net/confluence/display/UDIG/More</p>\r\n<p>Vanmeulebrouk, B., Rivett, U., Ricketts, A., Loudon, M.   2008.  Open source GIS for HIV / AIDS Management.  International Journal of Health Geographics.  Vol 7:53.  URL:  http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/7/1/53/</p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-21 15:10:44',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',1,0,20,'','',0,1,'robots=\nauthor='),(53,'Quantum GIS','quantum','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=53:quantum&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> Quantum GIS</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/05/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/05/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">An Open-Source Geographic Information System (GIS)</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.qgis.org/\">http://www.qgis.org/</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Quantum GIS is an open-source desktop GIS that has a user-friendly  interface and includes many of the same functions of commercial desktop  GIS software.  Quantum GIS has potential use within public health and  may be appropriate in resource challenged environments or within areas  that require open-source GIS software.</p>\r\n<p>The software is licensed under the GNU General Public License.  QGIS  supports vector, raster, and various database formats and functions.   The core functions of QGIS are continually expanding and QGIS also  supports plug-in development to allow users to extend the core  software.  (Source:  <a href=\"http://www.qgis.org/\">http://www.qgis.org/</a>).  The Quantum GIS software has versions that will run on Linux, Unix, Mac OSX and MS Windows.</p>\r\n<p>The Quantum GIS software coding began in 2002 and was originally a  project on SourceForge and was Q GIS because it used the Qt Toolkit from  Nokia (Source:  <a href=\"http://qgis.osgeo.org/en/about-qgis.html\">http://qgis.osgeo.org/en/about-qgis.html</a> ).</p>\r\n<p>The Quantum GIS community is beginning to assemble Case Studies which  illustrate how government agencies are using their software (<a href=\"http://qgis.org/en/community/qgis-case-studies.html\">http://qgis.org/en/community/qgis-case-studies.html</a> ).  The first case-study has been published and relates to work for  Solothurn, Switzerland regarding the requirements for an easy-to-use  desktop GIS running on Linux to accommodate the migration of GIS data  and software to Linux operating systems.   This is not the first time  that researchers have suggested that Quantum GIS could be very useful  within public health (Chang et. al 2009).</p>\r\n<p>Quantum GIS also played a role within health data analyses within  India (Oberai and Ram Mohan Rao, 2010) and with Amazonia snakebite  injuries (Stuppy, 2010).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many open-source GIS tools that are available and many of  these are available through an Open-Source Geospatial Foundation  (OSGeo):  <a href=\"http://www.osgeo.org/\">http://www.osgeo.org/</a> The goal of the OSGeo foundation is to build the highest quality</p>\r\n<p>Open-source geospatial software.   Quantum GIS (or QGIS) includes an  open-source community with wikis, blogs, forums, mailing lists, bug  tracking, overall project management,  user manuals, workshop materials,  workbooks, brochures, a QGIS community team, developer meetings, user  meetings, and tutorials.   Quantum GIS also includes some commercial  support from support contractors (Source: <a href=\"http://www.qgis.org/en/commercial-support.html\">http://www.qgis.org/en/commercial-support.html</a> ).</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Results</strong><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: <em>general information,</em></p>\r\n<p><em>system features, and functionality.</em></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>General Information:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Quantum GIS is currently operating on version 1.5.0 ‚ÄúTethys‚Äù.</p>\r\n<p>One can download both the sourecode and binary packages here: <a href=\"http://www.qgis.org/wiki/Download/\">http://www.qgis.org/wiki/Download/</a></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>System Features</strong>:  (Source:  <a href=\"http://www.qgis.org/about-gis/features.html\">http://www.qgis.org/about-gis/features.html</a> and <a href=\"http://qgis.osgeo.org/en/about-qgis/qgis-releases.html\">http://qgis.osgeo.org/en/about-qgis/qgis-releases.html</a>) .</p>\r\n<p>-       View and overlay vector and raster data in different formats  and projections without conversion to an internal or common format.</p>\r\n<p>-       Create maps and interactively explore spatial data with a friendly graphic user interface.</p>\r\n<p>-       Create, edit, and export spatial data</p>\r\n<p>-       Perform spatial analysis using the fTools plugin for Shapefiles or the GRASS plugin</p>\r\n<p>-       Publish your own map on the internet using export to Mapfile with MapServer.</p>\r\n<p>-       Adapt Quantum GIS to your business needs through extensible plugin architecture.</p>\r\n<p>-       New Symbology Infrastructure</p>\r\n<p>-       Field Calculator</p>\r\n<p>-       Print Composer</p>\r\n<p>-       User interface improvements</p>\r\n<p>-       Render caching</p>\r\n<p>-       Custom SVG Search paths</p>\r\n<p>-       Specify CRS when creating new shapefile</p>\r\n<p>-       Customizable attribute forms</p>\r\n<p>-       Changelog</p>\r\n<p>-       Measure angles on the map</p>\r\n<p>-       Map Composer</p>\r\n<p>-       Python Console</p>\r\n<p>-       WMS Search Server</p>\r\n<p>-       Symbology updates</p>\r\n<p>-       Save vectors as many file types‚Ä¶.</p>\r\n<p>-       Map annotations</p>\r\n<p>-       Spatial Selection plugin</p>\r\n<p>-       Spatialite Support improvements</p>\r\n<p>-</p>\r\n<p><strong>Functionality: </strong>(Source: <a href=\"http://qgis.osgeo.org/en/about-gis/qgis-releases.html\">http://qgis.osgeo.org/en/about-gis/qgis-releases.html</a>)</p>\r\n<p>-       Web Mapping Service (WMS) support.</p>\r\n<p>-       WMS-C scale slide gui added and more selection improvements</p>\r\n<p>-       Live GPS tracking tool</p>\r\n<p>-       New angle measuring tool</p>\r\n<p>-       User configurable WMS Search server</p>\r\n<p>-       Editing of invalid geometry in node tool</p>\r\n<p>-       SVG fill symbol layer</p>\r\n<p>-       Font marker symbol layer</p>\r\n<p>-       Noplugins command line options</p>\r\n<p>-       Allow hiding of deprecated CRSes</p>\r\n<p>-       Point displacement plugin</p>\r\n<p>-       Saving vector layers as ogr vector files</p>\r\n<p>-       Raster provider:  reduce debugging noise</p>\r\n<p>-       Allow adding parts to multi points and lines</p>\r\n<p>-       Text and form annotation</p>\r\n<p>-       Default composer templates</p>\r\n<p>-       Gradient color ramps</p>\r\n<p>-       Map centers where user clicks on the map</p>\r\n<p>-       Spatial selection plugin</p>\r\n<p>-       Data-defined size and rotation for symbols / symbolization</p>\r\n<p>-       IdentifyAsHTML for Rasters with Identify tool</p>\r\n<p>-       Export legend groups and layers with legendinterface</p>\r\n<p>-       Show selected feature count in status bar</p>\r\n<p>-       Query option added to layer menu to subset vector layers</p>\r\n<p>-       Option to label only selected features</p>\r\n<p>-       Load/save queries created in query builder</p>\r\n<p>-       Manual addition of categories in symbolization</p>\r\n<p>-       Georeferencer: possible to configure if residuals should be in pixels or map units</p>\r\n<p>-       Delimited text provider:  allow empty values in numeric columns</p>\r\n<p>-       Added rule based renderer for symbology</p>\r\n<p>-       Can create spatial lite databases within QGIS</p>\r\n<p>-       Inclusion of GDAL Raster tools plugin into QGIS core</p>\r\n<p>-       New python console (with history)</p>\r\n<p>-       Add validation to capture tool</p>\r\n<p>-       Allow postgres layers without saved username and password</p>\r\n<p>-       Support NULL values in search strings</p>\r\n<p>-       Optionally add new layers to the selected group</p>\r\n<p>-       Map composer can add attribute tables in layouts</p>\r\n<p>-       Identify tool attribute form now non-modal in view</p>\r\n<p>-       Identified feature highlights disappear when window is  deactivated or closed and reappears when the window is reactivated.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are several alternative open-source GIS desktop software including uDig, MapWindow, gvSIG, and GRASS GIS.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Quantum GIS software has a small track record of success for  public health data and epidemiological analyses.  This open-source  desktop GIS software has a user-friendly interface and a community of  open-source developers that are continually improving the interface and  adding functionality.   Many basic GIS functions are present that are  common to commercial GIS desktop systems.   The Quantum GIS software has  potential utility for public health within resource challenged  environments that cannot afford commercial desktop GIS software.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Quantum GIS  open-source software has potential utility for public health.</p>\r\n<p>The software comes with a community of users and developers and is  relatively easy to use.  The free cost and easy to use interface can  make Quantum GIS a potential mechanism to increase the adoption of GIS  within resource challenged environments that may lack funds for  commercial GIS software and trained GIS professionals.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>REFERENCES:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>Chang, A.Y., Parrales, M.E., Jimenez, J., Sobieszczyk, M.E., Hammer,  S.M., Copenhaver, D.J., and Kulkarni, R.P.  2009.  Combining Google  Earth and GIS mapping technologies in a dengue surveillance system for  developing countries.  International Journal of Health Geographics   2009, 8:49</p>\r\n<p>URL:  <a href=\"http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/8/1/49/\">http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/8/1/49/</a></p>\r\n<p>Neteler, M. and Furlanello, C.  2007.  Predictive modeling of spatio-temporal patterns:  GRASS GIS and OSGeo.</p>\r\n<p>URL:  <a href=\"http://mpa.fbk.eu/markus/kof2007/kof2007_osgeo_netelr.pdf\">http://mpa.fbk.eu/markus/kof2007/kof2007_osgeo_netelr.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Oberai, K. and Ram Mohan Rao, K.  2010.  Real Time Distributed  Geographical Information System (DGIS) Tool for Recording, Updating, and  Analysing the Health Related Data Using Open Source Technologies.</p>\r\n<p>URL:  <a href=\"http://mapindia.org/2010/proceedings/pdf/139.pdf\">http://mapindia.org/2010/proceedings/pdf/139.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Quantum GIS Brochure:  <a href=\"http://download.osgeo.org/qgis/doc/brochure/qgis-1.5.0_2-sided_brochure_en.pdf\">http://download.osgeo.org/qgis/doc/brochure/qgis-1.5.0_2-sided_brochure_en.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Rossi, L., Fraquelli, C., Vesco, U., Permunian, R., Sommavilla, G.M.,  Carmignola, G., Pozzo, R.D. and Menenguz, P.G.  2007.  Descriptive  epidemiology of a scabies epidemic in chamois in the Dolomite Alps,  Italy.  European Journal of Wildlife Research.  Volume 53, Number 2, May  2007 131-141.</p>\r\n<p>URL:  <a href=\"http://www.springerlink.com/content/g2l55v6x6gmw2223/\">http://www.springerlink.com/content/g2l55v6x6gmw2223/</a></p>\r\n<p>Solymosi, N., Reiczigel, J., Harnos, A., Meszaros, J., Molnar, L.D. and Rubel, F.  2010.</p>\r\n<p>Finding Spatial Barriers by Monmonier‚Äôs Algorithm.  (Poster).</p>\r\n<p>URL:  <a href=\"http://www.sociomed.hu/includes/ISCBposterv01.pdf/\">http://www.sociomed.hu/includes/ISCBposterv01.pdf/</a></p>\r\n<p>Stuppy, Sarah.  2010.  The Epidemiology of Snakebite Injury in the  Amazonian Regions of Ecuador.  MPH Research Project, Virginia  Commonwealth University.</p>\r\n<p>URL:  <a href=\"http://digarchive.library.vcu.edu/dspace/bitstream/10156/2995/5/Stuppy_Sarah_MPH.pdf\">http://digarchive.library.vcu.edu/dspace/bitstream/10156/2995/5/Stuppy_Sarah_MPH.pdf</a></p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-21 15:21:20',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',1,0,19,'','',0,1,'robots=\nauthor='),(54,'EpiCollect ','epi-collect','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/structured_evaluations/epicollect_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"EpiCollect icon\" title=\"EpiCollect icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=54:-epi-collect-&amp;catid=2:structuredevaluations&amp;Itemid=4\">EpiCollect</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Structured Evaluation | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 3/01/2011 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 3/31/2011 <br /><strong>Platform:</strong> iOS/Android/Web | <strong>Version: </strong>Review</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">A Generic Data Collect Tool for the Mobile Epidemiologist <img src=\"images/structured_evaluations/epicollect_rating.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"EpiCollect Rating: ~56%\" title=\"EpiCollect Rating: ~56%\" /> <img src=\"images/structured_evaluations/epicollect_adoption_curve.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"EpiCollect Adoption Curve Estimate: Embryonic\" title=\"EpiCollect Adoption Curve Estimate: Embryonic\" /></p>\r\n<p>This evaluation focused on EpiCollect, a data collection tool designed for iOS (iPhone, iPad) and Android devices to allow epidemiologists to rapidly design forms, share forms with a small group and use the forms to collect data directly using their mobile device.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />EpiCollect is an open source, mobile app for collecting generic form data. While this initial release suffers from significant limitations, the app shows promise as a way to rapidly design forms, collect data in the field and share data within a project. It should be considered by informaticians in low resource environments interested in collecting public health related data using forms.</p>\r\n<p><br />This evaluation was created using the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/irdu-guide-to-public-health-informatics-structured-evaluation-release.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">CDC Informatics Research and Development Unit (IRDU) Guide to Public Health Informatics Structured Technology Evaluations</a>.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Resources icon\" title=\"Resources icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> Resources\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/epicollect-structured-evaluation.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Evaluation Report</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,2,'2011-04-21 21:40:00',63,'','2011-12-01 17:21:04',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-04-20 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',22,0,2,'','',0,108,'robots=\nauthor='),(55,'Open Source Desktop GIS','desktop','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=54:desktop&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> Open Source Desktop GIS</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/25/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/25/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\"><strong>GIS and Geovisualization Tools for Health Informatics</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Geographic Information Systems (GIS) have a place within the many domains of Health Informatics.</p>\r\n<p>The use of commercial GIS software such as ArcGIS has been  established within all 50 state health departments and within over 70  ministries of health around the globe.   There is a need for the use of  open source GIS within resource challenged environments (Kamadjeu and  Tolentino, 2007).   There are hundreds of open source GIS software  products available and a wide range of features, functions, and  potential utility for public health.   The open source GIS software  cover a spectrum of fairly simple to very complex and the resources  supporting the software vary as well.</p>\r\n<p>The optimal choice(s) of open source GIS software for health  informatics may be guided by certain fundamental requirements which  include free cost and gentle learning curve with capacity for both very  simple as well as more complex geospatial analyses.   This paper  examines the spectrum of available open source GIS software and makes  some side-by-side comparisons to provide some guidance to health  researchers for choosing the optimal open source GIS software.</p>\r\n<p>This paper seeks to compare and contrast the 6 most commonly used  open source desktop GIS software through installation of the software, a  benchmark testing methodology, and a series of functionality comparison  tables.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Health informatics may include the domains of healthcare, medicine,  and public health.  Geographic Information Systems (GIS) technology  (Tomlinson, 2007) has evolved along with personal computers and  databases (Codd, 1970).   Health informatics is not completely na√Øve to  these developments and they have leveraged commercial GIS products such  as ArcGIS and these products are present within nearly all state health  departments and within over 70 Ministries of health across the globe.    GIS adoption has some challenges including software expense, learning  curve, GIS training, access to GIS data, and retention of trained GIS  staff.</p>\r\n<p>Resource challenged environments may require open source GIS tools  that are available at no cost (Kamadjeu and Tolentino, 2006).   While  the use of open source GIS tools may lower the startup cost for  acquiring GIS software, there are many considerations to determine which  of the hundreds of open source GIS tools might best fit the needs and  requirements of health informatics.</p>\r\n<p>It is important to note that this is not the first time that open  source desktop GIS software have been reviewed, compared, and evaluated  (Steiniger and Bocher, 2009, Ford, 2009, and Ramsey, 2007).  This review  of the open source GIS desktop software will be through the lens of the  public health informatics, GIS, and epidemiology perspective and will  examine these tools for their potential utility for public health.   It  is also worth noting that the CDC has produced their own GIS software  (although not completely open source) called EPI-Info and this was built  in conjunction with ESRI / MapObjects and has been downloaded millions  of times and is utilized by researchers around the globe.   EPI Info is  free but not open source and so this falls into another category and  will not be reviewed in this paper.   EPI info has many specific  epidemiology and statistical strengths but also has much more limited  visualization and mapping capabilities to the software reviewed within  this paper.  EPI-Info does have some significant weaknesses and is an  aging software package that is within need of an updated version that  would allow users to take advantage of web services and other geospatial  capabilities now available.</p>\r\n<p>The FreeGIS.org website (<a href=\"http://freegis.org/\">http://freegis.org/</a>) lists over 351 free GIS software tools and the Open Source GIS site (<a href=\"http://opensourcegis.org/\">http://opensourcegis.org/</a> )  lists over 259 open source GIS software tools.   There are also  several commonly used commercial GIS software tools used within public  health and other domains.  It would be impossible to compare and  contrast the hundreds of tools available and produce a document with  pragmatic value and utility.   This document compares a small subset of  the most commonly used GIS tools.   The domain of the most commonly used  GIS software is still large and may include both commercial GIS  products as well as open-source tools.    The Wikipedia list of  Geographic Information System (GIS) software includes a relatively short  list of the most popular commercial and open source GIS software:  <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_geographic_information_systems_software\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_geographic_information_systems_software</a> .</p>\r\n<p>Table A.  The most commonly used open-source GIS software include 6 products:</p>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\"><strong>SOFTWARE</strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"486\" valign=\"top\"><strong>URL</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\">GRASS GIS</td>\r\n<td width=\"486\" valign=\"top\"><a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/\">http://grass.itc.it</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\">uDig</td>\r\n<td width=\"486\" valign=\"top\"><a href=\"http://udig.refractions.net/\">http://udig.refractions.net/</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\">Quantum GIS</td>\r\n<td width=\"486\" valign=\"top\"><a href=\"http://www.qgis.org/\">http://www.qgis.org/</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\">MapWindows</td>\r\n<td width=\"486\" valign=\"top\"><a href=\"http://www.mapwindow.org/\">http://www.mapwindow.org</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\">OpenJUMP</td>\r\n<td width=\"486\" valign=\"top\"><a href=\"http://www.openjump.org/\">http://www.openjump.org</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\">gvSIG</td>\r\n<td width=\"486\" valign=\"top\"><a href=\"http://www.gvsig.org/\">http://www.gvsig.org/</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>SOFTWARE INSTALLATION:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The most common open source desktop GIS software have websites with  download links to installers for the various operating systems (Windows,  Linux, or Mac OSX) but these tools can sometimes be challenging to  install and may require some technical skill in terms of unzipping,  extracting install files, readme file documentation, and knowing how to  respond to software install path locations and other parameters.   The  burden of installation of open source or commercial GIS is similar and  this burden is not unique to one or the other but does represent a  challenge for non-IT savvy personnel.</p>\r\n<p>There are some efforts to provide a single download in the form of a Virtual Machine (VM) through websites such as GIS VM.com (<a href=\"http://www.gisvm.com/\">http://www.gisvm.com/</a> ).    These types of websites will allow users to download a VM base  and then download and install a pre-configured GIS Virtual Machine that  includes installation of the most commonly used open source GIS software  packages.   This represents a lot of time savings and has the potential  to standardize the installation process to assure that all public  health personnel are operating from the same base installation.    This  also has the potential to simplify tech support for open source GIS  installations by standardizing the install process and giving all users  the exact same setup, files, and configuration.</p>\r\n<p><strong>METHODS:    Benchmark Testing of Open Source Desktop GIS Software</strong></p>\r\n<p>Benchmark testing of software involves the use of standard datasets  and measuring the performance speed and quality of outputs generated  from these standard datasets.   The concept of benchmark testing for web  GIS is promoted by both commercial vendors and the open source GIS  communities.   There are relatively little documentation in the  literature that examine benchmark testing for open source desktop GIS  software.</p>\r\n<p>There are some efforts to benchmark test open source web mapping GIS software in the form of the ‚ÄúWMS Shootout‚Äù:  (<a href=\"http://2009.fossg4.org/presentations/#presentation_109\">http://2009.fossg4.org/presentations/#presentation_109</a> ) and there seem to be additional plans for benchmark testing with open source desktop GIS software (<a href=\"http://wiki.osgeo.org/wiki/Benchmarking_2010\">http://wiki.osgeo.org/wiki/Benchmarking_2010</a> ).</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Traditional Benchmark Testing of Open Source GIS Desktop Software</strong></p>\r\n<p>-       Standard dataset</p>\r\n<p>-       Large dataset (millions of points)</p>\r\n<p>-       WMS service</p>\r\n<p>-       WFS service</p>\r\n<p>-       Spatial Query</p>\r\n<p>-       Spatial Interpolation</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>The traditional benchmark testing may only answer part of the requirements of testing for public health purposes.</p>\r\n<p>It is nice to have software that will read large files quickly and  will not crash with large datasets or appear to hang or otherwise lockup  but it is also necessary to construct some type of public health  benchmarking that would test these software packages for their alignment  to public health GIS needs.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Public Health GIS needs / wish list for open source desktop GIS: </strong></p>\r\n<p>-       Easy to obtain / download / install</p>\r\n<p>-       Easy to learn / use ‚Äì cannot have steep learning curve</p>\r\n<p>-       Free or very inexpensive ‚Äì must have low cost</p>\r\n<p>-       Create Base map</p>\r\n<p>-       Add Case data to base map  (creating a spot map).</p>\r\n<p>-       Join Case data to base map admin boundaries</p>\r\n<p>-       Create Choropleth map</p>\r\n<p>-       Data Classification</p>\r\n<p>-       Geocoding</p>\r\n<p>-       Cluster detection ?</p>\r\n<p>-       Time-series mapping ?</p>\r\n<p>-       Proximity Analyses  (distance of patients to providers)</p>\r\n<p>-       Location-Allocation analyses  (find best location of new clinic ‚Ä¶.or find underserved populations)</p>\r\n<p>-       Standards (color standards, typology, classification, spatial interpolation, other methods)</p>\r\n<p>-       Metadata ‚Äì how current are all datasets, source of all datasets, resolution of all datasets</p>\r\n<p>-       Projections ‚Äì ability to handle data within different projections or to reproject data‚Ä¶?</p>\r\n<p>-       Cartography ‚Äì ability to add titles, legends, scalebars, north arrows, metadata, other elements.</p>\r\n<p>-       Performance ‚Äì does it take forever to do the most basic operations ?</p>\r\n<p>Perhaps the best way to evaluate the open source desktop GIS Software  is from the perspective and lens of the public health wish list for GIS  software.   The basic idea is to examine the software in terms of their  ease of use, low burden of expense, and non-steep learning curves with  the ability to extend to support complex use-cases and requirements for  public health spatial analyses.  This paper attempts to do this by  finding resources and links for each software package that can show  evidence that the software attempts to align to public health GIS needs  and requirements.   It is possible that more robust public health  benchmark testing could be developed in the future by teams of  epidemiologists and geographers but this remains undone at the time of  this writing.</p>\r\n<p><strong>RESULTS:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The six most commonly used open source GIS software were compared  within a series of tables to examine functionality, resources, technical  support, usability, ease of use, and capacity to serve the needs of  public health informatics.</p>\r\n<p>The tables provide links to various resources that will allow readers  to copy and paste the URLs into their web browsers and go directly to  the various resources.  The comparisons are objective and the resources  are not evaluated in depth for quality of the resource nor are they  subjectively judged in any manner.  This structured evaluation will  provide the reader with an objective set of tables that describe the  existence of resources or lack of resources.  Users of commercial GIS  software will immediately recognize that the cartographic quality of the  map output from open source GIS tools is not at the same quality  level.   Although the open source desktop GIS software tools do have  some limited ability to add scalebars, legends, north arrows, and other  common map elements, these tools are not robust and not nearly as  flexible as similar offerings within commercial GIS software.   There  are certain ‚Äúheadaches‚Äù associated with many aspects of Geographic  Information Systems (GIS) and these are not unique to open source GIS  software.   While testing these open source GIS tools several errors  would occur with database field names that were longer than 10  characters, and other ‚Äúcurve balls‚Äù that might throw exception errors  with geoprocessing scripts and other common tests of the applications.</p>\r\n<p>Some of these exceptions are relatively minor setbacks for an  experienced GIS professional but may represent significant obstacles to  those public health professionals that may have less experience  troubleshooting minor GIS problems.</p>\r\n<p><strong>DISCUSSION:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The universe of open source desktop GIS is very broad and there are literally hundreds of possible software choices.</p>\r\n<p>The most utilized and popular open source desktop GIS software are  reviewed in this paper for public health utility and value.  The five  most common open source desktop GIS software are compared and benchmark  tested for potential use within the public health domain.   The software  are tested within the perspective of potential public health users and  the utility of the software are judged against the needs and  requirements of public health professionals that may be non-GIS experts.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Random notes:</strong></p>\r\n<p>uDig is very easy to add WMS Layers and one simply puts in the URL  with GetCapabilities request and it works on the first attempt.    Quantum GIS does not seem to work so easily‚Ä¶.not sure about GRASS and  others ‚Ä¶..</p>\r\n<p>MapWindow can add WMS Services by installing the Online Data  plugin.    OpenJUMP also can add WMS layers but it is not very  intuitive;   It seems like uDig has the most intuitive interface for  adding WMS layers‚Ä¶.</p>\r\n<p>So far, Quantum GIS does the worst job of bringing in WMS Services‚Ä¶even crashed once‚Ä¶</p>\r\n<p>GRASS is also a pain to do this‚Ä¶.looks like you need to run r.in.wms from the command line‚Ä¶.jeez.</p>\r\n<p>One really strange aspect of GRASS is the fact that one must build a GRASS database ‚ÄúGISDBASE‚Äù.</p>\r\n<p>The GRASS database contains ‚Äúlocations‚Äù and ‚Äúmapsets‚Äù and these need to be set up prior to using GRASS.</p>\r\n<p>This is not that difficult but is yet another step to get started and also forces public health to conform to this outdated mode</p>\r\n<p>of geospatial data management and project management.  Most modern  GIS software create some sort of map document (.mxd in the case of ESRI)  or other type of open-source project file that contains pointers to  database or WMS layer url locations within that document.   GRASS seems a  little behind the technological times in terms of database management  and flexibility with file management.</p>\r\n<p>GRASS GIS has some very advanced capabilities including command line  operations but it also requires a lot of setup and installation in  advanced as well as some knowledge about Python and graphic user  interfaces.</p>\r\n<p>Quantum GIS has a couple of nice advantages in that it is an easy to  use interface that has an extension to GRASS GIS that allows it to  leverage the more advanced features of GRASS through a nicer interface.</p>\r\n<p>A lot of the open source GIS software seem to emphasize their editing  capabilities and the ability to move vertices and perform many types of  feature editing, geometry and topology checks and validations.   While  these are important functions and especially important to the GIS  professional, it is likely that public health epidemiologists will have  less understanding and need to edit street networks, fix dangles,  snapping of links to nodes, and or understanding of the underlying  spatial geometry and computational geometry.</p>\r\n<p>There seems to be an important GAP within both the software and the  literature in terms of the public health application of open source GIS  and the applied examples and use cases for each of the open source tools  within the domain of public health.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>RECOMMENDATIONS:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\"><strong>User Characteristics</strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Recommendation</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">Easy to Learn,  Easy to Use ‚Äì Advanced Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">Tools in this category have highest probability of adoption</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">Easy to Learn, Easy to Use -  Basic Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">Tools in this category have higher probability of adoption</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">Easy to Learn, Easy to Use -  Very Little Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">Tools in this category may still have high adoption</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">More challenging to Learn / Use ‚Äì Advanced Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">Tools in this category may still be adopted</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">More challenging to Learn / Use  ‚Äì Basic Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">Tools in this category are less likely to be adopted</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">More challenging to Learn / Use -  Very Little Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">Tools in this category are unlikely to be adopted</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\"><strong>User Characteristics</strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Preliminary Evaluation of Open Source Desktop Tools</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">Easy to Learn,  Easy to Use ‚Äì Advanced Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">Quantum GIS, gvSIG,</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">Easy to Learn, Easy to Use -  Basic Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">OpenJUMP , uDig</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">Easy to Learn, Easy to Use -  Very Little Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">MapWindows</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">More challenging to Learn / Use ‚Äì Advanced Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\">GRASS ‚Äì great functionality ‚Äì challenging to learn / use</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">More challenging to Learn / Use  ‚Äì Basic Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"439\" valign=\"top\">More challenging to Learn / Use -  Very Little Functionality</td>\r\n<td width=\"438\" valign=\"top\"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The choice of open-source GIS desktop software may be dependent upon the business needs and requirements of</p>\r\n<p>end-users or project specific-requirements.   There are certain tools  such as MapWindow that have a history of use with hydrology projects  and have tools specific to hydrological analyses.   BASINS is a tool  that was developed by EPA based upon the core of MapWindow and has even  more specific hydrology tools that make it an exception tool for this  use.</p>\r\n<p>Public health as a domain is very broad and there may be  task-specific requirements that focus your choice of open source desktop  GIS software.   The litmus tests for general  software recommendations /  adoption are:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li> Easy to download and install</li>\r\n<li> Instruction manuals / help / tutorials</li>\r\n<li>Easy to launch software and begin using software</li>\r\n<li>Learning curve is not steep and this is guided by tutorials and documentation</li>\r\n<li>Basic to Advanced functionality with capacity to extend with plugins and scripting languages</li>\r\n<li>Track record of success within the public health and epidemiology published literature</li>\r\n<li>Community of users</li>\r\n<li>Technical support and forums</li>\r\n<li>Ability to collaborate with other researchers / share maps / models</li>\r\n<li> Ability to document and provide metadata for maps and other products</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>It is likely that these general requirements are common to the domain  of public health but may not address specific requirements of an  individual program.   It is also possible that some of these general  needs are not completely necessary for certain programs.</p>\r\n<p>GRASS GIS installs on Windows but did not previously have support for this operating system.</p>\r\n<p>The Windows version of GRASS GIS has some missing modules, including the module for the 3D GIS functionality.</p>\r\n<p>It is possible to replace these missing modules with other modules but this burden is upon the user and they must have</p>\r\n<p>knowledge of the missing module, the required replacement, and then how to find and install the replacement modules.</p>\r\n<p>While these issues are documented and some help provided it is these  types of issues that make GRASS a bit harder to deal with than other  open source GIS software in terms of the non-GIS public health  professional.</p>\r\n<p>GIS users are used to a certain amount of ‚Äútinkering‚Äù with software,  code, models, etc and reading software whitepapers and code snippets to  get things to run;   It is likely that the non-GIS public health  professional will have less patience and less experience in dealing with  these types of issues.    Software documentation is a good thing and it  always helps to have software documentation but if the end-users must  read hundreds of pages of whitepapers or documents to simply install and  use the software than this becomes a less adoptable solution.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>CONCLUSION:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The choice of open source desktop GIS software may be guided by  specific requirements and the matching of system needs with the  appropriate available software package.   The software evaluated within  this paper covered a spectrum from fairly simple (MapWindows) to  extremely complex (GRASS GIS).  There are several other tools that fall  within the moderate middle ground of the spectrum and these tools may  have the highest potential for general adoption within public health.    It is also possible that none of these tools will be readily adopted by  public health as commercial GIS products are common within health  departments and it is unclear how many personnel would be trained to use  such open source GIS software.   It is possible that  resource-challenged environments may be good candidates for potential  use of open source desktop GIS software (Kamadjeu and Tolentino,  2007).   There may be specific uses for MapWindows in terms of  hydrological analyses and other strengths of that particular software.    GRASS GIS may be of great utility for public health graduate students  that may be working on very complex spatial analyses for dissertations  and other research publications.   It is possible that the pragmatic  middle ground between specific simplicity and broad complexity will make  tools such as Quantum GIS, OpenJUMP, and gvSIG popular with a large  number of epidemiologists that require basic to intermediate level  GIS.   The software developers and IT staff may find that some of the  eclipse based tools such as uDig, and OpenJUMP.   Python developers may  prefer the Quantum GIS and GRASS GIS combination with the GRASS  extension for Quantum GIS.    The .NET developers may also have  appreciation for the MapWindows ActiveX control and the ability to  freely distribute the customized MapWindow applications.</p>\r\n<p><strong>COMPARISON TABLES FOR OPEN SOURCE DESKTOP GIS SOFTWARE:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Table 1.  General information of selected GIS and Geovisualization software products</strong></p>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"></td>\r\n<td width=\"78\" valign=\"top\"><strong>GRASS</strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"114\" valign=\"top\"><strong>uDig</strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"126\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Quantum GIS </strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"174\" valign=\"top\"><strong>MapWindow</strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"168\" valign=\"top\"><strong>OpenJUMP</strong></td>\r\n<td width=\"127\" valign=\"top\"><strong>gvSIG</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">Version</td>\r\n<td width=\"78\" valign=\"top\">6.4.0</td>\r\n<td width=\"114\" valign=\"top\">1.2</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\" valign=\"top\">1.5.0</td>\r\n<td width=\"174\" valign=\"top\">4.8</td>\r\n<td width=\"168\" valign=\"top\">1.3</td>\r\n<td width=\"127\" valign=\"top\">1.9</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">Organization</td>\r\n<td width=\"78\" valign=\"top\">OSGeo</td>\r\n<td width=\"114\" valign=\"top\">Refractions.net</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\" valign=\"top\">OSGeo</td>\r\n<td width=\"174\" valign=\"top\">Idaho State Univ.</td>\r\n<td width=\"168\" valign=\"top\">Vivid Solutions</td>\r\n<td width=\"127\" valign=\"top\">gvSIG Association</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\">License</td>\r\n<td width=\"78\" valign=\"top\">GPL</td>\r\n<td width=\"114\" valign=\"top