p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=57:processing&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> Processing</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/11/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/11/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">A Sketch Language</p>\r\n<p><strong>Processing.org : </strong>Source:¬† (<a href=\"http://processing.org/\">http://processing.org/</a> )</p>\r\n<p><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Processing is a sketch language that was developed by Ben Fry and  Casey Reas at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) to marry  the love of art and the love of code within open source programming.¬†¬†  The tool is free and allows programmers to build sketches  programmatically and to modify that code very easily to make interactive  sketches and graphic user interfaces with event handling.¬†¬† This tool  might seem very basic but it has been used by physicists and other  scientists around the world for many types of visualization tasks.¬†¬† One  such impressive example is the NPZ Visualizer which uses Processing to  visualize the Nutrients, Phytoplankton, and Zooplankton life cycle along  the Pacific Northwest Coast (Banas, N., 2008).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Processing is an open source programming language and environment for  people who want to create images, animations, an interactions.¬†¬†  Initially developed as a software sketchbook and to teach fundamentals  of computer programming within a visual context, Processing also has  evolved into a tool for generating professional work.¬† Today, tens of  thousands of students, artists, designers, researchers, and hobbyists  use</p>\r\n<p>Processing for learning, prototyping, and production. (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://processing.org/\">http://processing.org/</a> ).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Results</strong><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: <em>general information,</em></p>\r\n<p><em>system features, and functionality.</em></p>\r\n<p><em> </em></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>General Information:¬†¬† (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://procesing.org/\">http://procesing.org/</a>) </strong></p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Free to download and open source</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Interactive programs using 2D or 3D or PDF output</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† OpenGL integration for accelerated 3D</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Operates on GNU/Linux, Mac OS X, and Windows</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Projects run online or as double-clickable applications</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Over 100 libraries extend the software into sound, video, computer vision, more.</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Getting Started Guide:¬† <a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/gettingstarted/\">http://processing.org/learning/gettingstarted/</a></p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Overview and Hello World:¬†¬† <a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/overview/\">http://processing.org/learning/overview/</a></p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Sketch Window with drop down menus for sketch examples</p>\r\n<p><strong>System Features</strong>:¬† (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/overview\">http://processing.org/learning/overview</a> ).</p>\r\n<p>Processing consists of:</p>\r\n<p>-The Processing Development Environment (PDE).¬† This is the software that runs when</p>\r\n<p>you double-click the Processing icon.¬† The PDE is an Integrated Development</p>\r\n<p>Environment (IDE) with a minimalist set of features designed as a simple introduction to</p>\r\n<p>programming or for testing one-off ideas.</p>\r\n<p>-A collection of functions (also referred to as commands or methods)  that make up the ‚Äúcore‚Äù programming language interface, or API, as well  as several libraries that support more advanced features such as drawing  with OpenGL, reading XML files, and saving complex imagery in PDF  format.</p>\r\n<p>-A language syntax, identical to Java but with a few modifications.</p>\r\n<p>-An active online community, hosted at <a href=\"http://processing.org/\">http://processing.org/</a> .</p>\r\n<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Digital Artists‚Äô Handbook discusses potential tools within the  digital art toolbox that are potential alternatives / complementary  tools for Processing including</p>\r\n<p>tools such as GIMP and Soda Play and others.¬†¬† A fuller listing of  URLs for potential alternatives is found in the Notes section of the  Game Art section of the Digital Artists‚Äô Handbook:¬† <a href=\"http://www.digitalartistshandbook.org/node/11\">http://www.digitalartistshandbook.org/node/11</a></p>\r\n<p>Although some of these alternatives support a lot of sketching , many  are not so much of a coding environment and it seems like Processing  does an excellent job of marrying the artists sketch with programmatic  code.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Processing has potential for use within public health.¬†¬† The NPZ  Visualizer 1.5 (Banas, N., 2008) shows the potential to build very  robust graphic user interfaces with Processing that can incorporate  regression models with slider bars for model parameters so that  scientists can run ‚Äúwhat-if‚Äù scenarios.¬†¬† The National Science  Foundation funded some of the work of the NPZ Visualizer project and  much of the source code for this application are made available by Dr.  Neil Banas through his website.¬†¬† Public health could utilize these  types of tools and source codes to build regression models and  visualizations of disease outcomes with explanatory variables and risk  factor slider bars to allow public health officials to visualize  potential effects of interventions on specific variables.¬†¬† Processing  should be seriously examined as a visualization tool for science within  the domain of public health.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Processing has not been widely used within public health but projects  supported by the National Science Foundation have utilized Processing  for very complex scientific visualizations (Banas, N., 2008).¬†¬† This  tool has many strengths including the open source code, free software,  and strong visualization capacity with capacity for graphic user  interface design and event-driven programming to allow user-interaction.</p>\r\n<p>Processing could be utilized by public health to build visualization  models that are interactive and would allow epidemiologists to examine  the effects of risk factor changes on potential disease outcomes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>REFERENCES: </strong></p>\r\n<p>Anderson, K.,¬† Barknecht, F., Betts, T., Cramer, F., Chandler, P.,  Goriunova, O., Lambert, K., Larulle, O., Magnusson, T., Maleve, N.,  Mansoux, A., Messeri, V.,</p>\r\n<p>Moradi, I., Oreggia, E., Philips, J., Sarkar, S., Schouten, T., de  Valk, M.¬† Westenberg, P., and Yuill, S.¬†¬† 2009.¬†¬†¬† The Digital Artists‚Äô  Handbook.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.digitalartistshandbook.org/node/17/pdf\">http://www.digitalartistshandbook.org/node/17/pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Banas, N.¬† 2008.¬† NPZ Visualizer 1.5¬† ¬†University of Washington, Applied Physics Lab.¬†¬† URL: <a href=\"http://coast.ocean.washington.edu/%7Eneil/NPZvisualizer/\">http://coast.ocean.washington.edu/~neil/NPZvisualizer/</a></p>\r\n<p>Banas, N.¬† 2007.¬† Designing ecosystem models to tell biological  stories.¬†¬† University of Washington,  Oceanography.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†  URL:¬† <a href=\"http://coast.ocean.washington.edu/%7Eneil/papers/grc07slides.pdf\">http://coast.ocean.washington.edu/~neil/papers/grc07slides.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Franks, P.J.S.¬† 2002.¬† NPZ Models of Plankton Dynamics:¬† Their  Construction, Coupling to Physics, and Application.¬†¬† Journal of  Oceanography.¬† Vol 58, No 2, 379-387.¬†¬†¬†¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.springerlink.com/content/6xnqgd4hx1lmq6n1/\">http://www.springerlink.com/content/6xnqgd4hx1lmq6n1/</a></p>\r\n<p>Reas, C.¬† and Fry, B.¬† 2007.¬† Processing:¬† A Programming Handbook for  Visual Designers and Artists.¬† The MIT Press.¬† 710  pages.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/books/#reasfry\">http://processing.org/learning/books/#reasfry</a></p>\r\n<p>Reas, C. and Fry, B.¬† 2010.¬† Getting Started with Processing.¬†¬† O‚ÄôReilly Media.¬† 208pgs.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† URL: <a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/books/\">http://processing.org/learning/books/</a></p>\r\n<p>Shiffman, D. 2008.¬† Learning Processing:¬† A Beginner‚Äôs Guide to  Programming Images, Animation, and Interaction.¬† Morgan Kaufmann. 450  pages.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/books/\">http://processing.org/learning/books/</a></p>\r\n<p>Shiffman, D.¬† 2010.¬† Processing in Eclipse.¬† URL: <a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/eclipse/\">http://processing.org/learning/eclipse/</a></p>\r\n<p>Thorp, Jer.¬† 2010.¬† Open Science, H1N1, Processing, and the Google  Spreadsheet  API.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†  URL:¬† <a href=\"http://blog.blprnt.com/blog/blprnt/open-science-h1n1-processing-and-the-google-spreadsheet-api\">http://blog.blprnt.com/blog/blprnt/open-science-h1n1-processing-and-the-google-spreadsheet-api</a></p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 18:49:34',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',4,0,17,'','',0,3,'robots=\nauthor='),(58,'gvSIG GIS','gvsig','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=58:gvsig&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> gvSIG GIS</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/05/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/05/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">An Open-Source Geographic Information System (GIS)</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig\">http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The gvSIG open-source suite (multiple software packages) of GIS  software that is very robust in features and functionality and has great  potential for use as a tool for public health GIS.¬† This open-source  software has an additional strength of multi-language support which  includes 10 different languages.¬† Perhaps even more enticing is the  platform independence of the software and that it can run on MS Windows,  Mac OS, or Linux operating systems.¬† This flexibility in terms of  platform and language support could create greater potential adoption by  international public health agencies that might be seeking alternative /  open-source GIS solutions in resource challenged environments.<strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many open-source GIS tools that are available and many of  these are available through an Open-Source Geospatial Foundation  (OSGeo):¬† <a href=\"http://www.osgeo.org/\">http://www.osgeo.org/</a> The goal of the OSGeo foundation is to build the highest quality</p>\r\n<p>Open-source geospatial software.¬† gvSIG is one of the open-source  desktop GIS tools that is a project of OSGeo and is known for  integration of local and remote data through standards, extensibility,  continual application enhancement, customization, free use,  distribution, study and improvement, as well as Multilanguage support  (Spanish, English, French, German, Italian) and multiplatform support  (Windows, Linux, Mac OS) (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig/\">http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig/</a>).</p>\r\n<p>The gvSIG software suite includes a mobile version that is optimized  for mobile data collection platforms.¬† The gvSIG is a mobile GIS and  also a mobile Spatial Data Infrastructure and as such is the first such  client licensed under open source.</p>\r\n<p>(Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.gvsig.org/web/home/projects/gvsig-mobile/\">http://www.gvsig.org/web/home/projects/gvsig-mobile/</a>).¬† There is also a gvSIG mini application for Android (<a href=\"http://blog.gvsig.org/2010/06/01/gvsig-mini-as-one-of-the-30-best-free-apps-for-android/\">http://blog.gvsig.org/2010/06/01/gvsig-mini-as-one-of-the-30-best-free-apps-for-android/</a> ).</p>\r\n<p>The gvSIG Commons is a space to collaborate and share code and  projects that is similar to google code or other collaborative  open-source spaces.</p>\r\n<p>The gvSIG also includes user documentation, developer documentation,  tester documentation, a learning section which includes full user  courses, developer courses, and community courses (developed by the  gvSIG community).</p>\r\n<p>These courses are available in English or in Spanish and some in French.</p>\r\n<p>Finally, gvSIG has a user blog (<a href=\"http://blog.gvsig.org/\">http://blog.gvsig.org/</a>), association (<a href=\"http://www.gvsig.com/\">http://www.gvsig.com/</a>) and hosts annual user conferences (<a href=\"http://www.gvsig.com/news/6th-gvsig-conference-knowledge-for-change\">http://www.gvsig.com/news/6th-gvsig-conference-knowledge-for-change</a>)</p>\r\n<h1>Results</h1>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: <em>general information,</em></p>\r\n<p><em>system features, and functionality.</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>General Information:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The gvSIG software was originally developed for the Ministry of  Infrastructure and Transport of Valencia, Spain.¬†¬† The vision and  mission of the gvSIG project included some core concepts in their  interpretation of the free software model and values.</p>\r\n<p>These core concepts are:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Sharing knowledge should not be an end in itself but a means to an end.</li>\r\n<li>Conviction that advancement and technological progress will be more  efficient with shared discovery and documentation of R&amp;D projects  (not hidden results).</li>\r\n<li>Build R&amp;D projects in alignment with social needs</li>\r\n<li>Collaboration, shared knowledge, solidarity, trust, democratic  function and loyalty are essential values that are core to the success  of the gvSIG project / mission.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>The gvSIG includes a user community as well as a Technical Steering  Committee of developers that guide the direction(s) of the project.¬†¬†  There is a formalized process to join the technical steering committee  and participate within their meetings.<br /> The gvSIG also includes a Board of Directors and there is a formalized  process to become a board member and nominate board members.</p>\r\n<p>(Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.gvsig.org/web/home/organization/mission-vision-and-values/\">http://www.gvsig.org/web/home/organization/mission-vision-and-values/</a>)</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>System Features:¬† (</strong>Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig/\">http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig/</a>)<strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Fully rich GIS desktop client</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Multilanguage support</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Platform independent</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Modular</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† OGC Standards compliant</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Developed based upon INSPIRE principles:¬† (<a href=\"http://inspire.jrc.ec.europa.eu/index.cfm/pageid/48/\">http://inspire.jrc.ec.europa.eu/index.cfm/pageid/48/</a>)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Interoperability with data formats (ENVI, ERDAS, GRASS, GeoTIFF, etc).</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Web Mapping Service (WMS) support</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Web Feature Service (WFS) support</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Web Coverage Service (WCS) support</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Discovery services to find data / services within a spatial data infrastructure</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Functionality:¬† (</strong>Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig/\">http://www.osgeo.org/gvsig/</a>)<strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Geoprocessing tools</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Proximity ‚Äì buffer, spatial joins</li>\r\n<li>Overlay¬† -¬† clip, difference, intersections, unions</li>\r\n<li>More ‚Äì supports convex hull creation and reprojection of layers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Computer Aided Design (CAD) Tools and Integration</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Integrated advanced raster tools</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Georeferencing images</li>\r\n<li>Image transparency</li>\r\n<li>Brightness and contrast</li>\r\n<li>Highlight</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Extensions, including SEXTANTE which extends for morphology and hydrology fields.</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Scripting support</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Powerful reprojection engine</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† 3D Visualization</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Network Analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Raster analyses¬† ‚Äì classification, rectification,</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Mobile device / gvSIG for mobile devices</p>\r\n<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Open Source Geospatial Foundation (OSGeo) lists several  alternative open-source GIS desktop mapping applications that are  projects of OSGeo including:¬† uDig, GRASS, Quantum GIS, and OSSIM.¬†¬†  MapWindow is another open-source desktop GIS application that has been  used by NOAA and other federal agencies.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The gvSIG software has a limited track record of success with  epidemiology studies in Europe and it is not surprising that adoption  has been greatest in Spain (origin of the gvSIG project).¬†¬† The gvSIG  software has much functionality that would be of potential use for  public health and epidemiology and supports many similar functions to  commercial desktop GIS software.¬†¬† The gvSIG software includes support  for vector, raster, and web services as well.¬†¬† This software could have  value for public health within resource challenged environments that  cannot afford commercial GIS software.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The gvSIG software has capacity for fundamental GIS functions and services.</p>\r\n<p>The tool is a free download and includes a user-community as well as  the potential to contribute to software development through the  technical steering committee.</p>\r\n<p>This tool has potential for public heatlh and epidemiology work and  has a limited track record of success with these areas within Europe.</p>\r\n<p><strong>REFERENCES:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Akkala, A., Devabhaktuni, V., and Kumar, A.¬† 2010.¬† Software Review:¬†  Interpolation techniques and associated software for environmental  data.¬† <em>Environmental Progress &amp; Sustainable Energy.</em> Vol 29(2).¬† Pages 134-141.</p>\r\n<p>Anguix, A., Diaz, L., Carrera, M.¬† 2008.¬† gvSIG a GIS Desktop Solution for and Open SDI.¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://gvsig-desktop.forge.osor.eu/downloads/pub/documents/articles/gvSIG-GIS_desktop_solution_for_open_SDI.pdf\">http://gvsig-desktop.forge.osor.eu/downloads/pub/documents/articles/gvSIG-GIS_desktop_solution_for_open_SDI.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Del Rey, A., Montesinos, M., Carrasco, J., and Carrion, G.¬† 2009.¬† gvSIG Mobile as a Mobile Client of SDI.¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://gvsig-desktop.forge.osor.eu/downloads/pub/documents/articles/gvSIG-Mobile_client_SDI_OSGIS_Nottingham.pdf\">http://gvsig-desktop.forge.osor.eu/downloads/pub/documents/articles/gvSIG-Mobile_client_SDI_OSGIS_Nottingham.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Ford, R.E.¬†¬† 2009.¬† Integrating GIS into eHealth initiatives in Africa.¬†¬† Ver 8.¬† Nov. 2009. URL:¬† <a href=\"http://idrc-gisworkshop.pbworks.com/f/FINAL_eHealth_GIS_Report8rev.pdf\">http://idrc-gisworkshop.pbworks.com/f/FINAL_eHealth_GIS_Report8rev.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Hintze, P. and Lakes, T.¬† 2009.¬† Geographically Referenced Data for  Social Science.¬†¬† German Council for Social and Economic Data (RatSWD).  URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ratswd.de/download/RatSWD_WP_2009/RatSWD_WP_125.pdf\">http://www.ratswd.de/download/RatSWD_WP_2009/RatSWD_WP_125.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Kamadjeu, R. and Tollentino, H.¬† 2008.¬† Web-based public health  geographic information systems for resources-constrained environment  using scalable vector graphics technology: a proof of concept applied to  the expanded program on immunization data.¬† <em>International Journal of Health Geographics</em>.¬† Vol 5:24.¬†¬† URL:¬†¬† <a href=\"http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/24/\">http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/24/</a></p>\r\n<p>Madzudzo, P.F.¬† 2007.¬† Exploratory Visualization of Temporal Events  in Epidemiological Research:¬† Case Study of Black Death.¬†¬† Thesis  (PhD).¬† The Netherlands: ITC.¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.itc.nl/library/papers_2007/msc/gfm/madzudzo.pdf\">http://www.itc.nl/library/papers_2007/msc/gfm/madzudzo.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Vanmeulebrouk, B., Rivett, U., Ricketts, A., Loudon, M.¬†¬† 2008.¬† Open source GIS for HIV / AIDS Management.¬† <em>International Journal of Health Geographics</em>.¬† Vol 7:53.¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/7/1/53/\">http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/7/1/53/</a></p>\r\n<p>O‚ÄôBrien. O. and Singleton, A.¬† 2009.¬† OpenStreetMap Data and  Choropleth Maps.¬† Department of Geography.¬† University College of  London.¬†¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=dgm4jnjp_11gnp7wkcn\">http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=dgm4jnjp_11gnp7wkcn</a></p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 18:54:57',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',5,0,16,'','',0,5,'robots=\nauthor='),(59,'Google Web Toolkit (GWT)','gwt','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"GeoDa icon\" title=\"GeoDa icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=59:gwt&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> Google Web Toolkit (GWT)</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/12/2010 |   <strong>Platform:</strong> Web | <strong>Version: </strong>Prelim</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Development Toolkit for Complex Browser-Based Applications</p>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://code.google.com/webtoolkit/\">Google Web Toolkit (GWT)</a> is a development toolkit for building and optimizing complex  browser-based applications. GWT is used by many products at Google,  including Google Wave and Google AdWords. It‚Äôs open source, completely  free, and used by thousands of developers around the world.</p>\r\n<p>This project will evaluate¬†how useful a tool this¬†may be¬†for  developing rich internet applications¬†that perform well on multiple  HTML5 enabled platforms (e.g., iOS, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Chrome,  Android, etc.).¬† Discovering ways to leverage existing skill sets such  as Java by the public health informatics community will be key to  helping the workforce to be productive without needing to learn new  languages (such as Objective-C) and stay current on updates and releases  of mobile and desktop development platforms.</p>\r\n<p>This may be an alternative to tools such as Appcelerator for  cross-platform development while recognizing the key differences between  native functionality and HTML5 functionality.</p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:33:24',62,'','2011-04-25 19:11:05',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:33:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',6,0,15,'','',0,4,'robots=\nauthor='),(60,'GRASS GIS','grass','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=60:grass&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> GRASS GIS</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/05/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/05/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">An Open-Source Geographic Information System (GIS)</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/\">http://grass.itc.it/</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The GRASS GIS open-source software is perhaps the oldest of all  open-source GIS software packages and has the longest track record of  use and perhaps the most world-wide users (Source: <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/\">http://grass.itc.it/</a>).¬†  This software has a reputation within the scientific community and has a  track record of success within those communities.¬† The software has not  been known for easy installation and use, however, and this is  something that has been improving over the 27 year history of the  software and they have added a new section to help first time users to  get started with GRASS GIS (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/intro/firsttime.php/\">http://grass.itc.it/intro/firsttime.php/</a>).¬†  The GRASS software is no longer alone within the open-source GIS  software genre and the community is competing with other technologies  that have similar functions with a more user-friendly interface.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are many open-source GIS tools that are available and many of  these are available through an Open-Source Geospatial Foundation  (OSGeo):¬† <a href=\"http://www.osgeo.org/\">http://www.osgeo.org/</a> The goal of the OSGeo foundation is to build the highest quality</p>\r\n<p>Open-source geospatial software.¬†¬† The Geographic Resources Analysis  Support System (GRASS) is arguably the oldest open-source GIS software  (celebrating 27 years!) and most widely used open-source GIS software  and is part of the OSGeo suite of open-source GIS software. ¬†¬†The GRASS  GIS software was originally developed by the US Army Corps of  Engineers.¬† The GRASS software comes with installation guides,  tutorials, courses, migration hints, wiki documentation, user community,  world-wide developer community, mailing lists, user groups, bug/issue  tracking system, programmer‚Äôs manual, development roadmap, and source  code repository¬† (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/devel/index.php\">http://grass.itc.it/devel/index.php</a>).¬†¬†  The GRASS GIS software has been used in many scientific disciplines  including public health and a GRASS application called EpiGRASS has been  developed for visualizing, analyzing, and simulation of epidemic  processes.</p>\r\n<p>(Source:¬† <a href=\"http://grass.osgeo.org/wiki/GRASS_and_its_siblings;_a_guide_for_the_novice#EpiGrass\">http://grass.osgeo.org/wiki/GRASS_and_its_siblings;_a_guide_for_the_novice#EpiGrass</a>).</p>\r\n<p>GRASS GIS is currently used by many federal government agencies and  academic institutions including:¬† NOAA,¬† NASA, USDA, Natl Park Service,  US Census Bureua, Oak Ridge National Lab, Duke University, McGill  University, European Commission, North Carolina State University,  Arizona State University, UC Davis.</p>\r\n<p>(Source:¬† <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/intro/general.php\">http://grass.itc.it/intro/general.php</a> and <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/intro/index.php\">http://grass.itc.it/intro/index.php</a> ).</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Results</strong><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: <em>general information,</em></p>\r\n<p><em>system features, and functionality.</em></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>General Information:</strong></p>\r\n<p>GRASS GIS has a lot of history and credibility with federal  government agencies and academic institutions.¬†¬† There are a large body  of tutorials in many different languages located here:¬† <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/gdp/tutorials.php/\">http://grass.itc.it/gdp/tutorials.php/</a></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>System Features</strong>:¬† (Source: <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/intro/general.php\">http://grass.itc.it/intro/general.php</a>)</p>\r\n<p>GRASS is a raster/vector GIS, image processing system, and graphics  production system.¬† GRASS contains over 350 programs and tools to render  maps and images on monitor and paper;; manipulate raster, vector, and  sites data; process multi spectral image data; and create, manage, and  store spatial data. ¬†GRASS uses both an intuitive windows interface as  well as command line syntax for ease of operations.¬† GRASS can interface  with commercial printers, plotters, digitizers, and databases to  develop new data as well as manage existing data.¬†¬† GRASS supports  network file sharing through its LOCATION/MAPSET concept and allows  teams to keep LOCATIONs with their underlying MAPSETS on a central  server and allows¬† for simultaneous work on the same project database.¬†¬†  GRASS also supports WMS and WFS web services !</p>\r\n<p><strong>Functionality: </strong>(Source: <a href=\"http://grass.itc.it/intro/capabilities.html\">http://grass.itc.it/intro/capabilities.html</a>)</p>\r\n<p>Raster Analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Automatic rasterline and area to vector conversion</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Buffering of line structures</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Cell and profile data query</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Colortable modifications</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Conversion to vector and point data format</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Correlation / covariance analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Expert system analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Map algebra (map calculator)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Interpolation for missing values</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Neighborhood matrix analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Raster overlay with or without weight</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Reclassification of cell labels</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Resampling (resolution)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Rescaling of cell values</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Statistical cell analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Surface generation from vector lines</p>\r\n<p>3D-Raster analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† 3D data import (intuitive ASCII: x y z Format)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† 3D masks</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† 3D interpolation (IDW, Regularized Splines with Tension)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† 3D Visualization (isofurfaces)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Interface to Vis5D visualization tool</p>\r\n<p>Vector analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Contour generation from raster surfaces (IDW, Spline algorithm)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Conversion to raster and point data format</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Digitizing with board on screen (scanned raster image) with mouse</p>\r\n<p>Point data analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Delaunay triangulation</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Surface interpolation from spot heights</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Thiessen polygons</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Topographic analysis (curvature, slope, aspect)</p>\r\n<p>Image processing</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Canonical component analysis (CCA)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Color composite generation</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Edge detection</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Frequency filtering (Fourier, convolution matrices)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Fourier and inverse fourier transformation</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Histogram stretching</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† IHS transformation to RGB</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Image rectification (affine polynomial transformations on raster and vectors)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Ortho photo rectification</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Principal component analysis (PCA)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Radiometric corrections (Fourier)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Resampling</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Resoultion enhancement (with RGB/IHS)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† RGB to IHS transformation</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Texture oriented classification (sequential maximum a posteriori)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Shape detection</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Supervised classification (training areas, maximum likelihood classification)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Unsupervised classification (min distance clustering, max likelihood classification)</p>\r\n<p>DTM Analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Contour generation</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Cost / path analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Slope / aspect analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Surface generation from spot heights or contours</p>\r\n<p>Visualization</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† 3D surfaces with 3D query (NVIZ)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Color assignments</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Histogram presentation</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Map overlay</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Point data maps</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Raster maps</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Vector maps</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Zoom / unzoom ‚Äì function</p>\r\n<p>Map creation</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† PPM-image maps</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Postscript maps, HTML maps</p>\r\n<p>SQL-support</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Database interfaces (ODBC, PostgreSQL)</p>\r\n<p>Other modules</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Erosion modeling (AGNPS 5, ANSWERS, TOPMODEL)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Landscape structure analysis</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Solution transport</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Watershed analysis</p>\r\n<p>Geostatistics</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Interface to ‚ÄúR‚Äù GNU S (a statistical analysis environment)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are several alternative open-source GIS¬†desktop software including:¬† MapWindow,¬†uDig, gvSIG,¬†and QuantumGIS.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>GRASS GIS has the longest track record of success with federal  government agencies and academic institutions of all of the open-source  GIS software packages.¬† The GRASS GIS software is in some senses very  mature and yet new competition within the genre of open-source GIS  software is challenging old ideas about user interface design and  useability of the GIS software.¬†¬† Many federal agencies are already  using GRASS GIS and so it makes sense that this software has potential  for use within public health, HHS, CDC, and within resource challenged  environments that may not have funds for commercial GIS software.<strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>GRASS GIS continues to improve and evolve over the 27 year history of  this open-source software.¬†¬† GRASS GIS has the largest adoption of  open-source GIS software as well as an established track record of  success with federal government agencies and academic institutions.¬† The  GRASS GIS software can be an effective part of the public health  toolset.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>REFERENCES:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>Isorna, C. et. al.¬† 2004.¬† GRASSlicer:¬† A Medical Image Analysis and Visualization Tool.</p>\r\n<p>Proceedings of the FOSS/GRASS Users Conference 2004.</p>\r\n<p>Bangkok, Thailand:¬† September 12-14 (2004).</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://gisws.media.osaka-cu.ac.jp/grass04/papers.php?first_letter=all\">http://gisws.media.osaka-cu.ac.jp/grass04/papers.php?first_letter=all</a>.</p>\r\n<p>GRASS Development Team, 2010.¬† Geographic Resources Analysis Support  System (GRASS) Software, Version 6.4.0.¬† Open Source Geospatial  Foudation.¬† <a href=\"http://grass.osgeo.org/\">http://grass.osgeo.org/</a></p>\r\n<p>GRASS Development Team, 2010.¬† Geographic Resources Analysis Support  System (GRASS) Programmer‚Äôs Manual.¬† Open Source Geospatial Foundation.¬†  Electronic document:¬† <a href=\"http://grass.osgeo.org/programming6/\">http://grass.osgeo.org/programming6/</a></p>\r\n<p>Lombardo, J.S.¬† and Buckeridge, D.L.¬† 2007.¬† Disease Surveillance:¬† A  Public Health Informatics Approach.¬† Wiley-Interscience, 2007.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0470068124.html\">http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0470068124.html</a></p>\r\n<p>Neteler, M.¬† and Mitasova, H.¬† 2004.¬† Open Source GIS:¬† A GRASS GIS Approach.</p>\r\n<p>The International Series in Engineering and Computer Science.¬† Springer, 2004.</p>\r\n<p>URL: <a href=\"http://www.springerlink.com/content/j21632/\">http://www.springerlink.com/content/j21632/</a></p>\r\n<p>Neteler, M. and Furlanello, C.¬† 2007.¬† Predictive modeling of spatio-temporal patterns:¬† GRASS GIS and OSGeo.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://mpa.fbk.eu/markus/kof2007/kof2007_osgeo_netelr.pdf\">http://mpa.fbk.eu/markus/kof2007/kof2007_osgeo_netelr.pdf</a></p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 19:19:12',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',4,0,14,'','',0,3,'robots=\nauthor='),(61,'IBM Spatiotemporal Epidemiological Modeler (STEM)','stem','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=61:stem&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">IBM Spatiotemporal Epidemiological Modeler (STEM)</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/05/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/05/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">A Space-Time SEIR Modeler for Disease Outbreaks and Epidemics</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.eclipse.org/ohf/components/stem/\">http://www.eclipse.org/ohf/components/stem/</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>IBM has built a spatiotemporal epidemiology modeler framework with the STEM system.</p>\r\n<p>This framework is free and open-source and supports generic  Susceptibility-Exposure-Infected-Recovered (SEIR) models that  compartmentalize populations at-risk into these categories.¬†¬† The tool  allows for ‚ÄúWhat-If Scenarios‚Äù whereby the epidemiologist may change  attack rates and other parameters and run / re-run the models to examine  how the populations at-risk are affected by the new scenario in space  and time.</p>\r\n<p>The IBM tool is not the final word in terms of spatiotemporal  modeling for disease outbreaks, but rather, is the beginning of the  process, by which scientists can utilize this free framework and generic  set of models to customize and build more accurate models of disease  outbreaks.¬†¬† The free and open-source nature of the tool provides a  potential mechanism for the Scientific Method by which one can build  transparent methodologies and models that can be executed, tested, and  compared to empirical data to determine residual levels and weaknesses  of the models.¬†¬† The IBM STEM tool could be a powerful mechanism for  disease modeling if embraced by public health scientists and  epidemiologists.¬†¬† The central question of adoption might surround the  computer science expertise required to customize the models and the  ability of public health researchers to adapt to spatiotemporal modeling  as opposed to more traditional temporal modeling (only).¬†¬† Public  health has long embraced temporal models and the use of epidemiological  curves and histograms of cases per day over time and over the course of  outbreaks but has lagged behind in terms of adopting spatial and  spatiotemporal modeling of the same outbreaks.¬† The IBM STEM tool can  help to bring space and time thinking together within a testable  framework and re-ignite an interest in spatial epidemiology and to end  what Dr. Tom Koch has called the ‚ÄúGreat Divorce‚Äù of space and time  within the field of epidemiology (Koch, 2005).</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Spatiotemporal Epidemiological Modeler (STEM) is a free software  available through the Eclipse Foundation.¬†¬† Originally developed by IBM  Research, STEM is a framework and development tool designed to help  scientists and public health officials create and use spatial and  temporal models of emerging infectious diseases.</p>\r\n<p>STEM currently includes a large number of plug-ins for the 244  countries and dependent areas defined by the Geographic Coding Standard  maintained by the International Organization for Standardization.¬† These  plug-ins contain global data including geographic data, population  data, demographics, and basic models of disease.¬†¬† The disease models  distributed with STEM include epidemiological compartment models.¬†¬†  Other plug-ins describe relationships between regions including  nearest-neighbor or adjacency relationships as well as information about  transportation, such as connections by roads and a model of air  transportation.</p>\r\n<p>Relationships between regions can then be included in models of how a  disease spreads from place to place.¬†¬† To accomplish this, STEM  represents the world as a ‚Äúgraph‚Äù.¬† The nodes in the graph correspond to  places or regions, and the edges in the graph describe relationships or  connections between regions.</p>\r\n<p>(Source:¬† <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spatiotemporal_Epidemiological_Modeler/\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spatiotemporal_Epidemiological_Modeler/</a> ).</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Results</strong><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: <em>general information,</em></p>\r\n<p><em>system features, and functionality.</em></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>General Information:</strong></p>\r\n<p>IBM STEM is built upon the Eclipse (<a href=\"http://www.eclipse.org/\">http://www.eclipse.org/</a>) workbench and operates in a way that will be familiar to programmers and developers that utilize the Eclipse workbench.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>System Features</strong>:¬† (Source: ¬†¬†<a href=\"http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/STEM#What.27s_New\">http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/STEM#What.27s_New</a>)</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† A full implementation of the STEM graph based simulation engine for spatiotemporal modeling</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Geographic visualization of the spread of disease using internally implemented graphics</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Geographic visualization of the spread of disease using Google Earth</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† ‚ÄúWizards‚Äù to create Projects, Graphs, Models, Scenarios, Sequencers, and Diseases</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Visual editors to edit Graphs, Models, Scenarios, Sequencers, and Diseases</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† A complete sett that defines all of the countries specified  by the ISO-3166 standard includes area, land mass, and recent human  population data</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† A complete Lat/Long data set in Geographic Markup Language  (GML) format for all countries defined by the ISO-1366 standard</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† An extensive set of predefined ‚ÄúGraph‚Äù fragments that can be reused in user Models</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† An extensive set of predefined ‚ÄúModels‚Äù, one for each country, that can be reused in user Models and Scenarios</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† A set of predefined ‚ÄúScenarios‚Äù that illustrate disease spread models around the Earth</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† A wide variety of mathematical models of infectious disease.</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Lots more.¬† IBM is adding features all the time.</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† New Graph Wizard</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† New Infectors, Inoculators, and Population Initializers</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† New External files implemented for creating new infectors and inoculators</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Tutorials provided in English, Spanish, Hebrew, and Japanese.</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Installation Guides, Manuals, Wikis, IBM STEM source code, bug tracking system</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Newsgroups, user feedback, request new features, user conference calls</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong></p>\r\n<p>CDC uses several temporal (only) modeling tools including FLUSURGE and FLUAID.</p>\r\n<p>The CDC tools do not have a spatial component and do not include  mapping of flu cases in space but do produce epidemiological curves and  histograms of the number of flu cases over units of time.<strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The IBM STEM tool is a free and open-source framework for space and  time modeling of potential epidemics and outbreaks.¬† The field of  epidemiology is strongly rooted in facets of Person, Time, and Place.¬†¬†  Temporal models of disease outbreaks are not good enough because they do  not take into account the spatial clustering of populations at-risk and  the spatial component of disease outbreaks.¬† There is a need for new  tools that will integrate space and time thinking within a single  modeling framework.</p>\r\n<p>The IBM STEM tool is one such tool and may be a useful starting point  for spatiotemporal epidemiological models for public health.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The IBM STEM tool has great potential utility for public health and  the integration of space-time thinking and modeling of disease outbreaks  and epidemics.</p>\r\n<p>The generic models provided by IBM are simply a starting point for  more robust and accurate models that might be developed by public health  scientists and epidemiologists.¬†¬† The IBM STEM tool can become a  mechanism for the Scientific Method as it would allow transparent and  testable modeling and methodology that could be tested and vetted with  the scientific community.</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>REFERENCES: </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>Ford, DA, Kaufman JH, Eiron I.¬† 2006.¬† An extensible spatial and  temporal epidemiological modeling system.¬† International Journal of  Health Geographics</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/4\">http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/4</a></p>\r\n<p>IBM STEM:¬† <a href=\"http://wiki.eclipse.org/STEM#Publications_and_Presentions_on_STEM\">http://wiki.eclipse.org/STEM#Publications_and_Presentions_on_STEM</a></p>\r\n<p>Koch, T.¬† 2005.¬† Cartographies of Disease:¬† Maps, Mapping, and Medicine.</p>\r\n<p>ESRI Press.¬†¬† ISBN 9781589481206.¬† 412 pages.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://esripress.esri.com/display/index.cfm?fuseaction=display&amp;websiteID=90&amp;moduleID=0\">http://esripress.esri.com/display/index.cfm?fuseaction=display&amp;websiteID=90&amp;moduleID=0</a></p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 19:29:14',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',3,0,13,'','',0,5,'robots=\nauthor='),(62,'Antaeus','antaeus','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=62:antaeus&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Antaeus</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/11/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/11/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Data From the Ground Up</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong> </strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">Source: (</span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/</span></span></a></span></span><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"> )</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Antaeus  is an exploratory data analysis (EDA) tool that makes great use of  scatter plots, 3D scatter plots, Scatter Plot arrays and matrices, and  Sunflower scatter plots to help the individual researcher to explore and  understand potential relationships and potential correlations within  their existing data. The tool emphasizes the ‚Äúreal‚Äù and suggests not to  build ‚Äúabstractions‚Äù of the data. This tool seems to examine the world  of data in a similar manner to the famous text on Exploratory Data  Analysis and also seems to share some of the philosophy that exploratory  data analyses are at least as important if not more important than  confirmatory analyses (Tukey, 1977). The Antaeus tool provides excellent  scatterplot visualization without requiring coding/programming but  provides this in a non-customizable manner. The Antaeus tool is free for  academic and non-commercial use.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Background:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Antaeus  is a system for finding patterns in multivariate data. It is intended  to be used by a single investigator working from individual data tables.  It provides tools for looking at your data when you don‚Äôt yet know what  you‚Äôre looking for, led by your intuition and knowledge about the  emergent phenomena represented. </span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">(Source: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/about.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/about.html</span></span></a></span></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"> ).</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Antaeus  relies almost exclusively on scatter plots to visualize data. The tool  also makes use of a more information dense scatter plot, the ‚Äúsunflower  plot‚Äù and approaches data visualization from a ‚Äúreification‚Äù or ‚Äúmaking  the real data‚Äù approach as opposed to creating ‚Äúabstractions‚Äù of the  data or abstract representations. The software approaches data  visualization with scatter plots and relates this to the mathematical  notion of a function that can be the foundation of mathematics and also  of understanding potential relationships and correlations within your  data.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">(Source: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/seeing.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/seeing.html</span></span></a></span></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"> ).</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">One  benefit of the sunflower scatter plot is the ability to build a  scatterplot with millions of observations and still have an  interpretable scatter plot. </span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">(Source: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/sunflowerplot.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/sunflowerplot.html</span></span></a></span></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">) </span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The following links are fascinating and provide more background information:</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Learn More About Antaeus:</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">About Antaeus: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/about.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/about.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">A Second Opinion: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/secondopinion.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/secondopinion.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Seeing Your data: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/seeing.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/seeing.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The Sunflower plot: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/sunflowerplot.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/sunflowerplot.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Functions: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/functions.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/functions.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Dimensions: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/dimensions.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/dimensions.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Partitions: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/partitions.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/partitions.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Cubes: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/navigating.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/concepts/navigating.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Introductions to Antaeus:</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Introduction: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/intros/simple.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/intros/simple.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Clarity: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/intros/clear.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/intros/clear.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Portability: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaeus-data.com/intros/portable.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaeus-data.com/intros/portable.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Publishability: </span></span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.antaus-data.com/intros/publishability.html\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.antaus-data.com/intros/publishability.html</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial-BoldMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Results</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: </span></span><span style=\"font-family: Arial-ItalicMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><em>general information,</em></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: Arial-ItalicMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><em>system features, and functionality.</em></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>General Information:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The  Antaeus tool is based upon scatter plot visualizations. The tool is  somewhat lacking in terms of instructions for how to import your data  into the Antaeus software.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The  basic idea is to create delimited text files with dimensions (perhaps  age, race, sex, time, place, ethnicity) and measures (perhaps counts,  rates, smr, etc) and then import these text files and create data cubes.  The data cubes can stay locally or Antaeus has an option to publish  data cubes to their server. The Antaeus website mentions that to this  date, no group has decided to publish their data cube to their site and  public health could not do this with any protected health information.  The Antaeus software does come with several example data cubes to  explore with the software tools.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>System Features</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">: </span></span><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">(Source: Left-Navigation on the Antaeus Software).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Create Cube </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Select Cube</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Functions</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Subsets</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Single Quantile Plot</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Q Separation Array</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Q Measure Array</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Quantile-Scatter Plot</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Single Scatter Plot</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Double Scatter Plot</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Scatter Plot Array</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Scatter Plot Matrix</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Partitioning</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Brushing</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Magnification</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Separation</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Dimension Array</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Separation Array</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Z-Space Exploration</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Z-Space Slice Array</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Single Sunflower Plot</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Sunflower Plot Matrix</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Docking of windows </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">User Forum</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\">Slides / Creation of Slide Show presentation of windows</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Alternatives:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">There  are many potential alternatives to Antaeus including SAS, SPSS, R, and  other statistical packages that support scatter plot visualizations. The  R statistical language is free and includes free packages such as RGL (</span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://rgl.neoscientists.org/\"><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://rgl.neoscientists.org/</span></span></a></span></span><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">)  that provide similar ability to create scatter plots and 3D scatter  plots that might be an alternative to Antaeus. It is important to note  that Antaeus is a codeless scatter plot visualization environment and  has the advantage of no code associated with building the visualizations  but the disadvantage of no ability to customize the scatter plots.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Recommendation:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">While  the Antaeus could have potential use-cases within public health, it is  unclear that there is any track record of success with this tool within  the public health domain and the tool itself appears to be somewhat  young / new in terms of overall maturity and functionality. The tool is  free and provides basic scatter plot visualizations for the purpose of  exploratory data analyses within a codeless graphic user interface. </span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Another  down-side of the tool is that the scatter plots are not customizable  and they do not provide metrics such as R-squared values, regression  lines, or other metrics. Antaeus does make use of a sunflower scatter  plot which is a rather unique plot that allows a scatterplot to  visualize large datasets with many points and still provides an  interpretable scatter. Public health could make use of sunflower  scatterplots and this is worth study and review.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Although  the Antaeus tool allows users to publish data cubes, public health  could not utilize this function with protected health information and  data.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">It  is not likely that this tool would receive wide adoption until it has  an easier mechanism to import data from various sources such as DBF,  SAS, EXCEL, CSV, TXT. It also seems that although the tool provides  visualization it does not provide statistical metrics and measures or  quantification of the visualizations. </span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Conclusion:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The  Antaeus tool is very interesting but may not be ready for prime-time  use within public health. The Antaeus tool provides a mechanism for  exploratory data analyses and uses a set of scatter plot tools to  visualize data. The Antaeus tool is not as robust as R or SAS but does  provide some unique tools such as the sunflower scatter plot that are  not widely used within commercial statistical software packages. The  Antaeus tool lacks some of the other scatter plot metrics that would  accompany scatter plots within commercial software and is not a  statistical tool as much as it is a visual and exploratory tool. The  Antaeus tool makes some interesting arguments in a similar manner to Dr.  John Tukey in terms of the importance of exploratory data analyses and  visualizations of the data to provoke new questions about existing data.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>REFERENCES: </strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Tukey, J. 1977. Exploratory Data Analysis. ISBN 0-201-07616-0.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">R: </span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.r-project.org/\"><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://www.r-project.org/</span></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">RGL: </span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://rgl.neoscientists.org/\"><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://rgl.neoscientists.org/</span></span></a></span></span><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"> and </span></span><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://rgl.neoscientists.org/gallery.shtml\"><span style=\"font-family: ArialMT,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">http://rgl.neoscientists.org/gallery.shtml</span></span></a></span></span></p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 19:36:19',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',4,0,12,'','',0,2,'robots=\nauthor='),(63,'GGobi and Rggobi','ggobi-','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=63:ggobi-&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">GGobi and Rggobi</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 8/12/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/12/2010<br /> <strong>Platform:</strong> Desktop | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">An Exploratory Data Analysis Tool</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong>Source:¬† (<a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/\">http://www.ggobi.org/</a> )</p>\r\n<p><strong>Executive Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The GGobi tool is an exploratory data analysis tool that extends the  work of Dr. John Tukey and his famous text and work on exploratory data  analyses (Tukey, 1977).</p>\r\n<p>The GGobi tool is a second or third generation tool that has evolved  from XGobi and S language to GGobi and working with the R statistical  programming language.</p>\r\n<p>It is also important to note that GGobi has a track record of success  with visualizing disease progression (Lazic et al, 2009) and  visualization for genomic studies (Rasko et. al, 2005).¬†¬† It should also  be noted that the epidemiology literature has many more examples of  successful use of GGobi and XGobi over the last decade.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>GGobi is an open source visualization program for exploring high-dimensional data.</p>\r\n<p>It provides highly dynamic and interactive graphics such as ‚Äútours‚Äù,  as well as familiar graphics such as the scatterplot, barchart, and  parallel coordinates plots.¬† Plots are interactive and linked with  brushing and identification.</p>\r\n<p>(Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/\">http://www.ggobi.org/</a> ).</p>\r\n<p>It is also worth noting that GGobi is a descendent of XGobi (Swayne  et. al, 1992 and 1998).¬†¬† It is also worth noting that GGobi researchers  have a long history with S and R languages and extending the work of  Dr. John Tukey and his text on exploratory data analyses (Tukey,  1977).¬†¬† Much of this work involves¬† the Bell laboratories.</p>\r\n<p>Rggobi is an extension package for the R statistical programming language.</p>\r\n<p>The rggobi package provides a command-line interface to GGobi.</p>\r\n<p>Rggobi complements GGobi‚Äôs graphical user interface, providing a way to fluidly</p>\r\n<p>transition between analysis and exploration, as well as automating common tasks.</p>\r\n<p>(Source:¬† <a href=\"http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rggobi/index.html\">http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rggobi/index.html</a> ).</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Results</strong><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p>This summary report presents our finding from three perspectives: <em>general information,</em></p>\r\n<p><em>system features, and functionality.</em></p>\r\n<p><em> </em></p>\r\n<p><strong>General Information</strong>:¬†¬† (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/docs/\">http://www.ggobi.org/docs/</a> )<strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>The GGobi website includes a Learning section which provides links to  GGobi books, courses, sample lectures, video demos, and tours:</p>\r\n<p>Parallel Coordinate Plots:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/docs/parallel-coordinates/\">http://www.ggobi.org/docs/parallel-coordinates/</a></p>\r\n<p>Teaching with GGobi:¬†¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/demos/teaching-with-ggobi.html\">http://www.ggobi.org/demos/teaching-with-ggobi.html</a></p>\r\n<p>Simple Brushing:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/demos/brushing-simple.html\">http://www.ggobi.org/demos/brushing-simple.html</a></p>\r\n<p>Point-Line Brushing:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/demos/brushing-biotin.html\">http://www.ggobi.org/demos/brushing-biotin.html</a></p>\r\n<p>Tours:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/demos/tours.html\">http://www.ggobi.org/demos/tours.html</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>System Features</strong>:¬† (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/\">http://www.ggobi.org/</a> and¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/features.html\">http://www.ggobi.org/features.html</a> ).</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Linked Brushing (if you click on dot in scatter plot that record is highlighted in all plots).</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Easily transfer results of R analyses with rggobi package for R.</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† ‚ÄúTours‚Äù of your data including a ‚Äúhelicopter tour in high dimension‚Äù.</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Graphically display / layout network data and link to other plots</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Create high quality publication graphics with display plugin</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Draw dotplots and scatterplots, barcharts, spineplots and histograms, parallel coordinate plots, scatterplot matrices</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Link data points and lines between plots using persistent or transient brushing, and identification</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Pan and zoom</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Rotate data in 3D, and tour high-dimension data using  sequences of 1D, 2D, and 2x1D projections augmented by manual control  and automatic projection pursuit guidance</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Acts as a high-dimensional drawing tool, by adding, moving, and drawing lines between points</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Connects with R to perform statistical analyses</p>\r\n<p>-¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Can be extended using modular plugins</p>\r\n<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The GGobi website suggests alternatives such as Mondrian and Manet  from the RoSuDa group at the University of Augsburg.¬†¬† They mention that  these tools have much stronger categorical features and if you have  categorical analyses these tools may be better than GGobi for these  purposes.¬† (Source:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/\">http://www.ggobi.org/</a>)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The GGobi tool has a strong statistical foundation and history in  connection with the R and S programming languages and the extension of  exploratory data analyses.¬† The scientific literature is packed with  examples of successful use of this tool within epidemiology and  bioinformatics contexts.¬†¬† The researchers behind GGobi (Swayne et. al)  have continued to revise and evolve the GGobi tool for scientific use.</p>\r\n<p>The recommendation to use GGobi for public health studies is not difficult.<strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>GGobi can enable scientists to visualize their data and explore their  data in ways that integrate with statistical analyses from the R  programming language.¬†¬† These methodologies extend the important  concepts outlined by Dr. John Tukey in his text on</p>\r\n<p>Exploratory data analyses (Tukey, 1977).¬† The inventor of the box  plot wanted us to visualize our data and use these visualizations to ask  new questions about existing data.¬†¬† GGobi is a logical extension of  these ideas and it is no surprise that scientists around the globe agree  and have been using this tool for these purposes.<strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>REFERENCES: </strong></p>\r\n<p>Cook, D. and Swayne, D.F.¬† 2007.¬† Interactive and Dynamic Graphics for Data Analysis.</p>\r\n<p>Springer.¬† ISBN 978-0-387-71761-6.¬†¬† Softcover.¬† 190 pages.</p>\r\n<p>URL: <a href=\"http://www.springer.com/statistics/statistical+theory+and+method/book/978-0-387-71761-6\">http://www.springer.com/statistics/statistical+theory+and+method/book/978-0-387-71761-6</a></p>\r\n<p>Lang, D.T. and Swayne, D.F.¬† 2001.¬† GGobi meets R:¬† an extensible  environment for interactive dynamic data visualization.¬† DSC 2001  Proceedings of the 2<sup>nd</sup> International Workshop on Distributed Statistical Computing.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-dsc.pdf\">http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-dsc.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Lang, D.T., Swayne, D., Wickham, H., and Lawrence, M.¬† 2009.¬† Package ‚Äòrggobi‚Äô.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rggobi/rggobi.pdf/\">http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rggobi/rggobi.pdf/</a></p>\r\n<p>Lazic, S.E., Mason, S.L., Michell, A.W., and Barker, R.A.¬† 2009.¬†  Visualizing disease progression on multiple variables with vector plots  and path plots.¬† BMC Medical Research Methodology 2009, 9:32¬† URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-228-9/32\">http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-228-9/32</a></p>\r\n<p>Rasko, D.A., Myers, GSA, and Ravel, J.¬† 2005.¬† Visualization of  comparative genomic analyses by BLAST score ratio. BMC Bioinformatics  2005, 6:2</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2105/6/2\">http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2105/6/2</a></p>\r\n<p>Swayne, D.F.,¬† Buja, A., and Lang, D.T.¬† 2004.¬† Exploratory Visual  Analysis of Graphs in GGobi. (PDF 300k).¬† CompStat:¬† Proceedings in  Computational Statistics, 16<sup>th</sup> Symp.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2003-dsc.pdf\">http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2003-dsc.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Swayne, D.F., Lang, D.T., Buja, A., and Cook, D.¬† 2006.¬† GGobi:¬†  evolving from XGobi into an extensible framework for interactive data  visualization (PDF, 1meg).¬† Computational Statistics &amp; Data  Analysis, 2003, 43:423-44.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-dataviz.pdf\">http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-dataviz.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Swayne, D.F., Lang, D.T., Buja, A, and Cook, D.¬† 2001.¬† GGobi:¬† XGobi  Redesigned and Extended.¬†¬† Proceedings paper for Interface conference,  summer 2001.</p>\r\n<p>URL: <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-interface.pdf\">http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-interface.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Swayne, D.F., Cook, D., and Buja, A.¬† 1992.¬† XGobi:¬† Interactive  dynamic graphics in the X Window System with a link to S.¬† American  Statistical Association 1991 Proceedings of the Section on Statistical  Graphics, pg 1-8.</p>\r\n<p>Swayne D.F., Cook, D., and Buja, A. ¬†1998.¬† XGobi:¬† Interactive  dynamic data visualization in the X Window System.¬† Journal of  Computational and Graphical Statistics, 7(1): 113-130.</p>\r\n<p>Swayne, D.F., Lang, D.T., Buja, A., and Cook, D.¬† 2001.¬† GGobi.</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-newsletter.pdf\">http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2001-newsletter.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p>Symanzik, J., Swayne, D.F., Lang, D.T., and Cook, D.¬† 2002.¬† Software  Integration for Multivariate Exploratory Data Analysis.¬† Proceedings  paper for workhop on tools for exploring spatial data (Spring 2002).</p>\r\n<p>URL:¬† <a href=\"http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2002-spatial-tools.pdf/\">http://www.ggobi.org/publications/2002-spatial-tools.pdf/</a></p>\r\n<p>Tukey, J.¬† 1977.¬†¬† Exploratory Data Analysis.¬† ISBN¬† 0-201-07616-0.</p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 19:42:31',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',3,0,10,'','',0,4,'robots=\nauthor='),(65,'Flot for Public Health Data','flot','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=65:flot&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Flot for Public Health Data</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/05/2010 | <strong>Version: </strong>Prelim</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Flot JavaScript Library</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>The PHGrid project had a <a href=\"http://sites.google.com/site/phgrid/Home/service-registry/quicksilver-service-registry-entry\">component</a> that used the <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/flot/\">Flot </a>JavaScript  library to visualize aggregate syndromic surveillance data and perform a  C2 algorithm to detect outliers and abnormal events. This demonstration  will extract the JavaScript library and demonstrate using it as a web  widget or embeddable gadget. The JavaScript library is extremely  lightweight and was received well by users. The Flot library</p>\r\n<p>The potential impact of using Flot will allow programs to easily embed basic visualization and analysis into web applications.</p>\r\n<p>Flot is a pure Javascript plotting library for <a href=\"http://jquery.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">jQuery</a>. It produces graphical <strong>plots</strong> of arbitrary datasets on-the-fly client-side. The focus is on <strong>simple</strong> usage (all settings are optional), <strong>attractive</strong> looks and <strong>interactive</strong> features like zooming and mouse tracking. The plugin works with  Internet Explorer 6/7/8, Firefox 2.x+, Safari 3.0+, Opera 9.5+ and  Konqueror 4.x+ with the HTML canvas tag (the <a href=\"http://excanvas.sourceforge.net/\" rel=\"nofollow\">excanvas</a> Javascript emulation helper is used for IE).</p>\r\n<p>¬†</p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 20:19:17',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',5,0,8,'','',0,7,'robots=\nauthor='),(66,'Mobile Development for Public Health','mobile','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=66:mobile&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Mobile Development for Public Health Data</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/13/2010 | <strong>Version: </strong>Prelim</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Recommendation: How to Develop Mobile Applications for Public Health Practitioners</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>An open question within the lab and with the groups we‚Äôve met with  within CDC and external to CDC is ‚ÄúWhat is CDC‚Äôs strategy for developing  on mobile platforms?‚Äù Initially the research and development unit has  targeted iOS applications for the iPhone and iPad based on market  penetration, level of vendor support, developer tools and public  perception; but as the mobile application marketplaces mature our group  needs a position on how we target and develop for mobile platforms.  Specifically, the Android, Blackberry and WindowsMobile marketplaces are  maturing and available for use by public health practicioners and the  consumers they work with.</p>\r\n<p>This recommendation will examine the mobile environment and create a  recommendation for how the research and development unit-and CDC as a  whole- can develop applications that are used by public health  praticioners to perform public health surveillance, interventions and  other activities as well as how the public consumes information from CDC  and other public health data sources. With the HHS and CDC iniatives to  better engage citizens with publicly-available data sets like those  available on <a href=\"http://www.data.gov/\">data.gov</a> and <a href=\"http://wonder.cdc.gov/\">WONDER</a>,  we need to know how citizens can use their mobile devices to view and  work with public health data released to the public by CDC programs.</p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 20:30:21',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',3,0,7,'','',0,3,'robots=\nauthor='),(64,'Google Maps for Public Health Data','googlemaps','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" title=\"OpenJUMP GIS icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=64:googlemaps&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Google Maps for Public Health Data</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/13/2010 | <strong>Version: </strong>Prelim</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Google Maps Demonstration</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p>Porting the google maps functionality from PHGrid‚Äôs <a href=\"http://sites.google.com/site/phgrid/Home/service-registry/gridviewer\">GridViewer </a>and <a href=\"http://sites.google.com/site/phgrid/Home/service-registry/quicksilver-service-registry-entry\">Quicksilver </a>projects.</p>','',0,1,0,3,'2010-12-08 15:22:02',62,'','2011-04-25 20:08:43',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:22:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',2,0,9,'','',0,2,'robots=\nauthor='),(67,'Structured Evaluation Tool','eval-tool','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Structured Evaluation Tool icon\" title=\"Structured Evaluation Tool icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=67:-epi-collect-&amp;catid=2:structuredevaluations&amp;Itemid=4\">Structured Evaluation Tool</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Structured Evaluation | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/01/2010 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 4/01/2011 <br /><strong>Platform:</strong> Evaluation | <strong>Version: </strong>Draft</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">Public Health Informatics Technology Evaluation Tool</p>\r\n<p>CDC Informatics Research and Development Unit (IRDU) Guide to Public Health Informatics Structured Technology Evaluations.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />This document serves as a guide for completing a structured technology evaluation – for the public health community. Each section of the outline describes how specific portions of the evaluation should be performed. The scope of this tool is to examine specific technology-based tools or resources that have the capacity to provide specific value to the public health community. The tool is not designed to evaluate public health programs. Though suboptimal, it can be used to evaluate public health surveillance systems. There are, however much more specific tools to achieve this task.1 This tool is best used to evaluate the component technologies within a larger system (e.g., a surveillance system).</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Resources icon\" title=\"Resources icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> Resources\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/irdu-guide-to-public-health-informatics-structured-evaluation-release.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Structured Evaluation Tool [PDF]</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/irdu-guide-to-public-health-informatics-structured-evaluation-release.doc\" target=\"_blank\">Structured Evaluation Tool [Word]</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/irdu-guide-to-public-health-informatics-structured-evaluation-release-template.doc\" target=\"_blank\">Structured Evaluation Blank Template [Word]</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/irdu-guide-to-public-health-informatics-structured-evaluation-release-aides.xls\" target=\"_blank\">Structured Evaluation Figure Aides [Excel]</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,2,'2011-05-23 23:54:00',63,'BAL','2011-12-01 17:20:39',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-05-23 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',7,0,1,'','',0,66,'robots=\nauthor='),(68,'MMWR for the iPad','wwmr-ipad','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/mmwr_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"MMWR iPad icon\" title=\"MMWR iPad icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=68:-mmwr-ipad-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">MMWR for the iPad</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Prototype | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 12/10/2010 | <strong>Platform:</strong> iOS | <strong>Version:</strong> 1.0</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">MMWR Reading App for the iPad</p>\r\n<p>The goal of this prototype has been to examine existing MMWR content, and structure the content to best fit the iOS iPad platform.   You can see from the screenshots that two prototypes were created- one that focuses on a standard method for displaying content - while the other prototype leverages a novel map-based navigation interface.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\"> (view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5px\" height=\"1px\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/mmwr1.jpg\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"MMWR Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/mmwr1.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"WWMR Screenshot\" title=\"WWMR Screenshot\" width=\"120\" height=\"100\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5px\" height=\"1px\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/mmwr2.jpg\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"MMWR Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/mmwr2.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"WWMR Screenshot\" title=\"WWMR Screensh