'0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',11,0,6,'','',0,79,'robots=\nauthor='),(76,'Centers of Excellence','coe-link','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/generic_icon_80x53.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"default logo\" title=\"default logo\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><span style=\"position: relative; top: 10px;\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=76:coe-link&amp;catid=4:news&amp;Itemid=6\">Centers of Excellence (CoE) in Public Health Informatics</a></span></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The Centers of Excellence (CoE) in Public Health Informatics was established to support a broadly based research program to share knowledge and common resources with a few selected research partners. The program was initiated by a funding opportunity announcement that was released on February 9, 2009.</p>\r\n<p>The Centers support research that will develop, translate, and disseminate informatics knowledge and expertise to public health professionals that is essential to maximizing the potential of information systems to improve the health of the nation. The research supported should be innovative and supportive of programs linking recent advances in evidence-based public health intervention, systems development, information processes, and computer science to advance and improve the public\'s health.</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"smallish\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/osels/ph_informatics_technology/coe.html\">More information is available at the CDC PHITPO hosted Centers of Excellence web site...</a></p>','',1,2,0,4,'2011-08-09 18:42:00',62,'TGS','2011-12-01 17:22:14',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-08-09 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',13,0,4,'','',0,22,'robots=\nauthor='),(77,'An example of the use of Public Health Grid (PHGrid) technology during the 2009 H1N1 influenza pandemic','phgrid-2009-h1n1','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/grid_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Public\" title=\"Public Health Grid icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=77:-phgrid-2009-h1n1-&amp;catid=5:publications&amp;Itemid=7\">An example of the use of Public Health Grid (PHGrid) technology during the 2009 H1N1 influenza pandemic</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Grid Computing</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\"><br />Boyd T, Lee B, Savel T, Stinn J, Kesarinath G</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Atlanta, GA 30333, USA.</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\">Int J Grid and Utility Computing 2011 - Vol.2, No.2 pp. 148-155</p>\r\n<p><br />ABSTRACT:</p>\r\n<p>Historically, public health surveillance systems in the USA have been designed as registries targeting specific public health issues that collect data from certain population groups to answer particular questions.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p>This resulted in disparate public health information systems that can rarely address new needs without extensive redesign. Such a design limits the ability of public health professionals to address emerging public health threats when data need to be collected from different areas of public health practice; the 2009 H1N1 influenza pandemic posed such a challenge. The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention\'s Public Health Informatics and Technology Program Office (CDC/PHITPO) and its partners explored a decentralised information architecture using the Public Health Grid (PHGrid). Through the exploration of PHGrid capabilities, CDC/PHITPO developed a pilot project to demonstrate a method for secure and timely data exchange using simulated data in aggregate format.</p>\r\n<p><br />KEYWORDS:</p>\r\n<p>grid computing; opportunistic networks; distributed databases; service-oriented framework; middleware; security; privacy; trust; public health surveillance; United States; USA; H1N1 influenza pandemic; decentralised information; public health grid; network security; timely data exchange; flu pandemic.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Resources icon\" title=\"Resources icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> Resources\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.inderscience.com/search/index.php?action=record&amp;rec_id=40602&amp;prevQuery=&amp;ps=10&amp;m=or\" target=\"_blank\">Article Abstract</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,3,0,5,'2011-09-22 19:42:00',62,'','2011-12-01 17:22:30',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-09-22 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',11,0,2,'','',0,40,'robots=\nauthor='),(78,'Yahoo Pipes','yahoo-pipes','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoo_pipes.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Yahoo Pipes icon\" title=\"Yahoo Pipes icon\" width=\"80\" height=\"53\" align=\"left\" style=\"float: left; border: 0;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=78:yahoo-pipes&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Yahoo Pipes</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 9/19/2011 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 9/22/2011 <br /><strong>Platform:</strong> Web/HTML5 | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">Data Mashup Tool</p>\r\n<p>Yahoo Pipes is a free web tool that can allow public health programs to pull together existing data feeds into a combined, transformed and processed RSS feed.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h2>Introduction:</h2>\r\n<p><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://pipes.yahoo.com/pipes/\">Yahoo Pipes</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference1\">[1]</a> is a free tool that has been designed to combine multiple, disparate data feeds and allows for rules processing, transformation and combination of data into a new feed (called a “pipe”) that is accessible by a unique URL. Each pipe is developed using Yahoo’s graphical editor and can be either private or available to the public. <br /><br />Pipes is a free tool released and maintained by Yahoo that allows for the mashup, transformation and re-publication of data feeds- primarily RSS, but multiple feed types are supported. It was released to public beta on 2/7/2007 where is has been maintained without any service level agreement (SLA) by Yahoo. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference2\">[2]</a> <br /><br />Pipes was built by Pasha Sadri, Ed Ho, Jonathan Trevor, Kevin Cheng and Daniel Raffel (all Yahoo employees) who describe the tool as \"…a hosted service that lets you remix feeds and create new data mashups in a visual programming environment. The name of the service pays tribute to Unix pipes, which make it easy to chain simple utilities together on the command line.\" <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference3\">[3]</a> Although not available as open source, the tool is available free of charge. Although no support options exist, Yahoo maintains an <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://blog.pipes.yahoo.net/\">active blog</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference4\">[4]</a> and <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://discuss.pipes.yahoo.com/\">discussion forum</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference5\">[5]</a> where Yahoo has consistently updated the tool based on community feedback with 5,608 posts since 2007.</p>\r\n<h2>Description:</h2>\r\n<p>Yahoo Pipes was created as a general purpose tool, not specifically for use within public health or health. In spite of this, there are existing public health related public pipes such as the 34 feeds created by the user <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://pipes.yahoo.com/pipes/person.info?guid=QNVHIZBA2IB7CX6KEVL4TNWCQM\">\"Public Health\"</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference6\">[6]</a> that monitor health publications for articles related to specific public health related terms such as Women’s Health and Neurology. <br /><br />Pipes allows input from a variety of structured and unstructured web data sources: RSS, RDF, iCal, basic HTML, CSV; as well as web site specific inputs from Yahoo sites such as Flickr. Pipes parses these data feeds and allows an analyst or developer to perform basic operations on the content of the feed based on the direct contents of the feed or based on specific metadata associated with the feed. Although these operations are text based and may seem basic to informaticians they allow powerful text manipulation without the need to create independent systems or new web services. These operations include the ability to filter by regular expression, filter by text (either inclusive or exclusive), count, substring, sort, union/join/combine, loop, split and more. All of these processing rules can be combined together graphically to create and output a new feed in a variety of formats, including: RSS, CSV. JSON, and custom formats. <br /><br />Analysts or developers create work-flows within the Pipes web site using an HTML5 graphical user interface that allows users to drag components into the design pane and connect work-flow steps together using predefined operations and relationships <a class=\"reg\" href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot1-fullworkflow.png\">[see Screenshot 1]</a>. The Pipes designer provides a basic set of components that allow users to manipulate data by source <a class=\"reg\" href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot2-sourcescomponents.png\">[see Screenshot 2]</a>, user input <a class=\"reg\" href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot3-userinputcomponents.png\">[see Screenshot 3]</a>, programmatic operators <a class=\"reg\" href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot4-operatorscomponents.png\">[see Screenshot 4]</a> or with string manipulation <a class=\"reg\" href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot5-stringmanipulationcomponents.png\">[see Screenshot 5]</a>. <br /><br />While the designer tool does not require a knowledge of programming, our evaluator found his knowledge of basic programming principles useful for working with pipe work-flows; specifically: variables, flow control, string manipulation and regular expressions. The designer also provides a debugger and debugging tools that help to develop work-flows and work-flow steps. While familiar to a developer, the debugger may be initially confusing to a non-developer as they gain familiarity with the tool. There is limited formal training available, there are many explanatory videos, tutorials and self-paced training pages available through Yahoo’s <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://blog.pipes.yahoo.net/category/how-tos/\">how-to blog</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference7\">[7]</a>. <br /><br />Although the performance of the processing for a particular work-flow will depend on the availability of the input feeds and complexity of the processing rules, our experience is that run-time is extremely quick. In our example pipe processing/run time was .008 seconds to read in an RSS feed, filter it by regular expression and output a new, modified RSS feed. <br /><br />Yahoo makes no claim for availability, nor integrity of data. Although access to pipes can be restricted by Yahoo or Google userid, no claim is made for the NIST-compatibility of the authentication and authorization mechanisms. This makes Pipes inappropriate for use with PHI/PII or other sensitive data. Additionally, Pipes cannot be a dependency of systems or system components where availability is a critical characteristic.</p>\r\n<h2>Lab testing:</h2>\r\n<p>The lab, in collaboration with the Situation Awareness team of CDC’s Emergency Operations Center (EOC), created a test pipe to 1) explore the learning curve necessary to create a pipe, and 2) test the extent of Pipes’ text filtering. The Situation Awareness team monitors USGS for earthquakes that register over 6.0 on the Richter scale. USGS provides an <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/catalogs/eqs7day-M5.xml\">RSS feed</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference8\">[8]</a> of all earthquakes that register 5.0 or higher. The SA team monitors this feed manually and investigates only earthquakes over 6.0. We thought this simple scenario would be appropriate for testing Pipes’ ability to automate simple human review to allow SA to focus their resources on more complex aspects of situation awareness and emergency response. Our architect had no prior experience with Yahoo Pipes, yet within 1 hour was able to register for an account, create a pipe using a USGS’s feed, filtering for any earthquake above 6.0 and outputing the results in <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://pipes.yahoo.com/pipes/pipe.run?_id=7ab28fc2bcb60ac4264747598f2f5646&amp;_render=rss\">GeoRSS enabled RSS</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference9\">[9]</a>. Since the output of this new pipe was in GeoRSS, the feed could be easily sent through another web service like Google Maps to plot the earthquakes on a global map without any additional development effort, nor specialized GIS expertise. Although a simple example of a mashup using Pipes’ capabilities, this test showed that Pipes can be useful to extend the investigative capability of public health while respecting the availability, integrity and confidentiality requirements of public health.</p>\r\n<h2>Conclusion:</h2>\r\n<p>While severely limited by Pipes’ lack of security controls (no CDC compliant authentication/authorization, no FIPS-compliant data integrity controls), lack of SLA and lack of commercial support; this tool is useful for public health programs that:</p>\r\n<ol class=\"sum33\">\r\n<li>Deal with public data from public data sources (i.e., publicly available and addressable RSS feeds),</li>\r\n<li>Do not have critical dependencies or require a specific level of availability.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>If programs can work with these restrictions then Yahoo Pipes is an inexpensive, rapid method to automate routine tasks or prototype approaches that depend on internet-based data feeds.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\">(view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot1-fullworkflow.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Yahoo Pipes Screenshot #1\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot1-fullworkflow.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Yahoo Pipes Screenshot #1\" title=\"Yahoo Pipes Screenshot #1\" width=\"91\" height=\"91\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot2-sourcescomponents.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Yahoo Pipes Screenshot #2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot2-sourcescomponents.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Yahoo Pipes Screenshot #2\" title=\"Yahoo Pipes Screenshot #2\" width=\"60\" height=\"91\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/brief_reviews/yahoopipesscreenshot3-userinputcomponents.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Yahoo Pipes Scre