09.19 </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Yahoo Pipes Blog, <a name=\"reference4\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://blog.pipes.yahoo.net/\">http://blog.pipes.yahoo.net/</a> Accessed 2011.09.19 </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Yahoo Pipes Forum, <a name=\"reference5\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://discuss.pipes.yahoo.com/\">http://discuss.pipes.yahoo.com/</a> Accessed 2011.09.19 </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">\"Public Health\" user Yahoo Pipes Profile Page, <a name=\"reference6\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://pipes.yahoo.com/pipes/person.info?guid=QNVHIZBA2IB7CX6KEVL4TNWCQM\">http://pipes.yahoo.com/pipes/person.info?guid=QNVHIZBA2IB7CX6KEVL4TNWCQM</a> Accessed 2011.09.19 </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Yahoo Pipes Developer How-To, <a name=\"reference7\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://blog.pipes.yahoo.net/category/how-tos/\">http://blog.pipes.yahoo.net/category/how-tos/</a> Accessed 2011.09.19 </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">USGS 5+ Earthquake RSS Feed, <a name=\"reference8\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/catalogs/eqs7day-M5.xml\">http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/catalogs/eqs7day-M5.xml</a> Accessed 2011.09.19 </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Custom IRDU developed 6+ Earthquake GeoRSS Feed, <a name=\"reference9\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://pipes.yahoo.com/pipes/pipe.run?_id=7ab28fc2bcb60ac4264747598f2f5646&amp;_render=rss\">http://pipes.yahoo.com/pipes/pipe.run?_id=7ab28fc2bcb60ac4264747598f2f5646&amp;_render=rss</a> Accessed 2011.09.19 </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p> </p>',1,1,0,3,'2011-09-19 22:42:00',62,'BAL','2011-12-01 17:21:37',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-09-22 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',29,0,6,'','',0,76,'robots=\nauthor='),(79,'Biosurveillance Registry Alternatives Analysis for Selecting an Integrated Software Solution','biosurveillance-aa','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/nphsb_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Biosurveillance Alternatives Analysis icon\" title=\"Biosurveillance Alternatives Analysis icon\" width=\"80\" height=\"70\" align=\"left\" style=\"float: left; border: 0;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=79:biosurveillance-aa&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Biosurveillance Alternatives Analysis for Selecting an Integrated Software Solution</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 3/1/2011 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 8/31/2011 <br /><strong>Platform:</strong> Web/Enterprise Architecture | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">R&amp;D Lab Engagement Report: Alternatives Analysis for Data Collection, Analysis and Reporting</p>\r\n<p><em>Guest authors Drs. Prachi Mehta and Christine Bradshaw from Biosurveillance Coordination, Office of Surveillance, Epidemiology and Laboratory Services and Jay Govindan from Deloitte Consulting share their experience within the R&amp;D Lab in this first engagement summary post.</em></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Conducting an Alternatives Analysis for Selecting an Integrated Solution to Support the National Public Health Surveillance and Biosurveillance (NPHSB) Registry for Human Health.</strong></p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />The National Public Health Surveillance and Biosurveillance Registry for Human Health (NPHSB Registry) is a new electronic resource available at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) that provides essential high-level information on 285 identified human health surveillance assets operating within the agency. The Registry enables surveillance experts at CDC to find and connect with each other in order to foster collaboration and harness the power of their collective knowledge to detect, characterize, and monitor population health threats and trends.<br /><br />The current technology is not optimal to support the Registry’s long term data collection, analysis and reporting needs. To ensure the selection of an appropriate integrated solution, we conducted a thorough and systematic alternatives analysis. This analysis was based on a methodology that was aligned to the Software Engineering Institute (Carnegie Mellon – Capability Maturity Model) COTS Software Product Evaluation framework. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference1\">[1]</a> In addition, we accounted for HHS IRM Policy for Conducting Information Technology Alternative Analysis requirements. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference2\">[2]</a> We developed evaluation criteria and reviewed them against “Gartner’s critical capabilities for Business Intelligence tools.” <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference3\">[3]</a> Finally, we evaluated our approach against “Keil, Tiwana, “Beyond Cost: The Drivers of COTS Application Value.” IEEE Software May/June (2005). <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference4\">[4]</a> <br /><br />Our analysis illustrates a detailed methodological approach for assessing a large suite of technological options against objective, qualitative and quantitative criteria. As part of the analysis, we evaluated over 30 different products based on a wide range of characteristics including usability, security, scalability and value vs. cost. We narrowed our selection pool to 4 potential integrated solutions based on a product score that was a composite of the characteristic weight, importance and whether or not the criteria were met. These options are further evaluated in the “Proof of Concept” phase, ultimately leading to the selection of a final integrated solution.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<div><strong>Product Score = ∑ [Characteristic Weight * ((Criteria Importance * Criteria Met) / # of criteria)]</strong></div>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\nThe elements of the methodological approach include:\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><strong>Characteristic Weight</strong> – Assign weights to the criteria</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><strong>Criteria Importance</strong> – Assign importance to established criteria (must have=2, nice to have=1, not needed=0).</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><strong>Criteria Met</strong> – Assess degree to which each product meets each criteria (meets criteria=2, partially meets criteria=1, does not meet criteria=0) – Conducted by Systems Architect based on extensive product research with vendors, demos, literature, SMEs.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><strong>Assign Importance</strong> - To established criteria (must have=2, nice to have=1, not needed=0).</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><strong>Criteria Met</strong> - Assess degree to which each product meets each criteria (meets criteria=2, partially meets criteria=1, does not meet criteria=0).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The four short-listed solution options were prototyped in the CDC/ OSELS R&amp;D laboratory. Based on the prototype evaluation findings coupled with a Strengths, Weaknesses, Opportunities and Threats (SWOT) analysis and review by an expert informatics panel, we selected one integrated solution to support the next generation of the NPHSB Registry. The R&amp;D lab’s support was instrumental in the successful completion of this analysis. They provided remote access to virtual machines (VMs) to build and test these prototypes and in addition, provided server administration and hosting services to support development efforts. The R&amp;D lab provides an excellent option for CDC Programs that want to conduct a prototype evaluation prior to making significant monetary investments in a final product.<br /><br />We presented our alternatives analysis methodology at the American Medical Informatics Spring Conference in May 2011 and at the Public Health Informatics Conference in August 2011. For more information regarding our approach, and to view our poster presentation please click on the attachment below.<br /><br />For more information about this analysis or the NPHSB Registry, please contact the NPHSB Registry Helpdesk at {emailcloak=off} <a class=\"reg\" href=\"mailto:NPHSBRegistry@CDC.gov\">NPHSBRegistry@CDC.gov</a> or call 404-498-0600.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Resources icon\" title=\"Resources icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> Resources\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/nphsb-alternatives-analysis-poster.pdf\" title=\"Alternatives Analysis Poster\">NPHSB Alternatives Analysis Poster</a> </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"Referencesicon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference1\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?Location=U2&amp;doc=GetTRDoc.pdf&amp;AD=ADA443491\">http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?Location=U2&amp;doc=GetTRDoc.pdf&amp;AD=ADA443491</a> </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference2\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.hhs.gov/ocio/policy/2003-0002.html\">http://www.hhs.gov/ocio/policy/2003-0002.html</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Sallam R, Richardson J, Gartner Report Critical Capabilities for Business Intelligence Platform Integration, 29 December 2009<a name=\"reference3\"></a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference4\"></a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cs.helsinki.fi/u/przybils/courses/CBD06/papers/01438331.pdf\">http://www.cs.helsinki.fi/u/przybils/courses/CBD06/papers/01438331.pdf</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p> </p>',1,1,0,3,'2011-11-22 09:56:23',62,'BAL','2011-12-06 21:51:28',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-11-22 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlan