/bit.ly/sFuqHv</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Norman, Donald. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Design-Everyday-Things-Donald-Norman/dp/0465067107/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1322678358&amp;sr=1-1\" target=\"_blank\">The Design of Everyday Things</a>. Basic Books, 2002.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Norman, Donald. 2003. Don Norman on 3 ways good design makes you happy. TED: Ideas Worth Spreading. <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://bit.ly/rSbNxg\" target=\"_blank\">http://bit.ly/rSbNxg</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">O’Connor, Kevin. 2011. Personas: The Foundation of a Great User Experience. UX Magazine. <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://bit.ly/uKrgLL\" target=\"_blank\">http://bit.ly/uKrgLL</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Reiber, Terry. 2004. Requirements Trace-ability and Use Cases. Managing Requirements. Ludwig Consulting Services, LLC. <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://bit.ly/uKy5AA\" target=\"_blank\">http://bit.ly/uKy5AA</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">U.S. Department of Health and Human Services. Card Sorting. Usability.gov: Your Guide for Developing Useful &amp; Usable Web Sites. <br />URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://1.usa.gov/w0F4r1\" target=\"_blank\">http://1.usa.gov/w0F4r1</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">User Experience.UX Design. 8/16/2010. UX Design Defined. <br /> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://bit.ly/rXSp3q\" target=\"_blank\">http://bit.ly/rXSp3q</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Weinschenk, Susan. 2011. HFI Animate — The ROI of User Experience with Dr. Susan Weinschenk. Human Factors International Video. <br /> URL: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://bit.ly/sXaxdP\" target=\"_blank\">http://bit.ly/sXaxdP</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,3,'2011-11-29 19:28:04',62,'','2011-11-30 21:14:13',62,62,'2012-03-27 16:27:09','2011-11-29 19:28:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',89,0,4,'','',0,181,'robots=\nauthor='),(82,'PHIX','phix-prototype','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/phix_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHIX Prototype icon\" title=\"PHIX Prototype icon\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 80px; float: left; height: 53px; border: 0px none;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=82:-phix-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">Public Health Information eXchange (PHIX)</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Pilot Prototype | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 11/17/2011 | <strong>Platform:</strong> Web | <strong>Version:</strong> 1.2.0.1</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Public Health Information eXchange (PHIX) Pilot Project</p>\r\n<p>The CDC PHITPO sponsored Public Health Information eXchange pilot project provides access to an information exchange solution designed to assist clinical care and public health partners with preparing and communicating quality, standards based electronic messages as defined by the applicable laboratory, surveillance and immunization use case and messaging standards.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To make the PHIX solution readily available to public health organizations and health care providers and to further expand the capabilities of the PHIX, the team has launched an open source community portal as part of the CDC Informatics Research and Development portal. The web portal includes components for Showcase and local message validation, downloads of software and support documentation, and a Community User component for user collaboration designed to support tasks to further development and deployment of PHIX.<br /><br /> The PHIX has been designed to perform a full range of functions and features to support interoperable data exchange including message transformation, vocabulary validation and translation, component routing based on appropriate business rules and organizational requirements, and message component analysis of incoming data streams for specific conditions of interest. As a new solution for interoperable data exchange, PHIX features will be added incrementally based on input from development partners and participants.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Launch Application:</strong> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://phix.phiresearchlab.org\">http://phix.phiresearchlab.org</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\">(view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/phix_screenshot.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"PHIX Screenshot #1\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/phix_screenshot.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHIX Screenshot #1\" title=\"PHIX Screenshot #1\" width=\"91\" height=\"91\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a></p>',1,1,0,1,'2011-12-01 11:57:11',62,'','2011-12-01 20:29:08',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-12-01 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',13,0,5,'','',0,107,'robots=\nauthor='),(83,'RSS Feeds','rssfeeds','','<h3><img src=\"images/stories/rss_feeds.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\" />RSS Feeds</h3>\r\n<p><br />Stay up-to-date with the lab\'s projects, news, and resources. Choose from our RSS feeds below.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top:15px; margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px;\"><img src=\"images/stories/all_rss.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"float:left;\" /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_ninjarsssyndicator&amp;feed_id=3&amp;format=raw\"><strong>All Content</strong></a>: a comprehensive feed that covers all the content provided on our website. You can stay current with any updates to the site.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top:10px; margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px;\"><img src=\"images/stories/projects_rss.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"float:left;\" /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_ninjarsssyndicator&amp;feed_id=1&amp;format=raw\"><strong>Projects</strong></a>: covers all projects within the R&amp;D lab. The lab has 3 major types of projects: prototypes, structured evaluations, and brief reviews. All types are listed together, by the most recently created project.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top:15px; margin-left:55px; margin-right:45px;\"><img src=\"images/stories/rss_arrow.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"float:left;\" /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_ninjarsssyndicator&amp;feed_id=2&amp;format=raw\"><strong>Prototypes</strong></a>: investigations or experiments that build software, data and/or hardware devices.<br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/rss_arrow.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"float:left;\" /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_ninjarsssyndicator&amp;feed_id=5&amp;format=raw\"><strong>Structured Evaluations</strong></a>: systematized quantitative &amp; qualitative technology evaluations for public health.<br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/rss_arrow.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"float:left;\" /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_ninjarsssyndicator&amp;feed_id=4&amp;format=raw\"><strong>Brief Reviews</strong></a>: short reports on technologies that have the potential to benefit public health.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top:9px; margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px;\"><img src=\"images/stories/news_rss.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"float:left;\" /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_ninjarsssyndicator&amp;feed_id=6&amp;format=raw\"><strong>News</strong></a>: all news related to the R&amp;D lab.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top:10px; margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px;\"><img src=\"images/stories/downloads_rss.png\" border=\"0\" style=\"float:left;\" /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_ninjarsssyndicator&amp;feed_id=7&amp;format=raw\"><strong>Downloads &amp; Tools</strong></a>: useful downloads and tools created by the R&amp;D lab to assist the public health community with its research.</p>\r\n<p> </p>','',1,0,0,0,'2011-12-06 15:05:28',62,'','2011-12-06 20:38:07',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-12-06 15:05:28','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=0\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',73,0,2,'','',0,253,'robots=\nauthor='),(84,'PHTweet','phtweet-prototype','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/phix_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHIX Prototype icon\" title=\"PHIX Prototype icon\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 80px; float: left; height: 53px; border: 0px none;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;sectionid=1&amp;task=edit&amp;cid[]=84\">PHTweet</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Pilot Prototype | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 11/17/2011 | <strong>Platform:</strong> Web | <strong>Version:</strong> 1.2.0.1</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Public Health Information eXchange (PHIX) Pilot Project</p>\r\n<p>The CDC PHITPO sponsored Public Health Information eXchange pilot project provides access to an information exchange solution designed to assist clinical care and public health partners with preparing and communicating quality, standards based electronic messages as defined by the applicable laboratory, surveillance and immunization use case and messaging standards.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To make the PHIX solution readily available to public health organizations and health care providers and to further expand the capabilities of the PHIX, the team has launched an open source community portal as part of the CDC Informatics Research and Development portal. The web portal includes components for Showcase and local message validation, downloads of software and support documentation, and a Community User component for user collaboration designed to support tasks to further development and deployment of PHIX.<br /><br /> The PHIX has been designed to perform a full range of functions and features to support interoperable data exchange including message transformation, vocabulary validation and translation, component routing based on appropriate business rules and organizational requirements, and message component analysis of incoming data streams for specific conditions of interest. As a new solution for interoperable data exchange, PHIX features will be added incrementally based on input from development partners and participants.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Launch Application:</strong> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://phix.phiresearchlab.org\">http://phix.phiresearchlab.org</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\">(view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/phix_screenshot.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"PHIX Screenshot #1\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/phix_screenshot.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHIX Screenshot #1\" title=\"PHIX Screenshot #1\" width=\"91\" height=\"91\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a></p>',-2,1,0,1,'2011-12-01 11:57:11',62,'','2012-01-25 20:00:37',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2011-12-01 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',4,0,0,'','',0,0,'robots=\nauthor='),(85,'PHTweet','phtweet-prototype','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/phtweet_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHTweet Prototype icon\" title=\"PHTweet Prototype icon\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 80px; float: left; height: 53px; border: 0px none;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=85:phtweet-prototype&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">PHTweet</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Prototype | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/07/2011 | <strong>Platform:</strong> Web | <strong>Version:</strong> 1.0</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Social Media and Situational Awareness: Monitoring the Twitter Stream for Public Health-Related Trends.</p>\r\n<p>PHTweet is a web application prototype created by the Informatics R&amp;D Lab team to monitor the Twitter stream for a specified set of public health terms. This project helps with situational awareness needs by leveraging the ubiquity of this social medium to survey public health-related trends. The user has several options for how he/she would like to view the Twitter data: Bubble View, Graph View, or Relationship View. Additionally, there are temporal options for displaying the data: daily, hourly, or in 2-week periods (the temporal options depend upon the selected view).</p>\r\n','\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Goals:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">This application was designed for obtaining high-level information at a glance, as well as drilling down to detailed information when needed. The context of use was a strong design consideration because it is unique to a Situation Awareness setting. The application has the potential of being displayed on a large screen for viewing by CDC Emergency Operations staff, where dramatic changes to a term’s tweet frequency should be prominent and easily noticed by the user(s).</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Because it is important to provide access to any quantitative data collected from the Twitter streams, users may delve into a Detailed View which displays specific information for each tweet. Such granular information includes: user name, message, exact date &amp; time, location, number of retweets, hash tags, and more. Please see the top-right screenshot below for an example of the Detailed View.  Please note that in our prototype, this \"deep dive\" Detailed View feature has not been activated.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">In keeping with our mission as the CDC’s Informatics Research and Development lab, we pursued a modern approach to the application’s data visualizations. We want to demonstrate that data can be represented in a manner that is clean, elegant, descriptive, and visually engaging. Design considerations such as color, form, ease of interaction, and negative space were applied. We also created a unique visualization for the Relationship View that properly fits its data variants: the relationships of the key terms to each other (i.e., how often multiple key terms are tweeted together), and the strength of the relationships based on tweet frequency (e.g., strong, medium, and weak). Please see the bottom-right screenshot below for an example of the Relationship View.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Design Philosophy:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To present the Twitter stream data efficiently, we embraced an important tenet of Information Design, as advocated by Edward Tufte and other experts in the field: the use of multifunctioning graphical elements. Multifunctioning graphical elements make the most of their space by displaying multivariate data. However, the graphical elements must still be clean and clearly understandable. Otherwise, their intent has been undermined.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">We also felt the design should feature different perspectives for viewing the information so users can obtain a complete picture of the data’s relevance. Each of the major views, Bubble, Graph, and Relationship, illustrates the data in a distinctive way.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The Bubble View displays a bubble chart which correlates the tweet frequency for each specified term with the size of a bubble graphic. The bubbles change sizes dynamically in real time, and can also be viewed for specific past hours or days. Each bubble is color-assigned and labeled with its corresponding term. The number of tweets for the term is displayed directly on the bubble, so the quantifiable data is easily viewable. The Bubble View provides a high-level and concise perspective, but each bubble is also a link leading further into detail about the term’s tweet stream — all the way to the very granular Detail View. The bubble graphical elements display multivariate data, and allow for interaction. Yet, the Bubble View maintains a clean, minimal look. To see the Bubble View, please refer to the top-left and top-center screenshots below.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The Graph View (as pictured in the bottom-left screenshot below) allows users to view the tweet frequency for selected terms over a period of time — either over a 12-hour period, or a 2-week period. All terms in the specified set may be viewed at once so they can be compared to each other. Or, the user can eliminate particular terms from the view to focus in on a smaller set. This time-series plot gives the tweet frequency analysis a historical context, which allows trends to be clearly spotted and assessed.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The Relationship View (bottom-right screenshot below) illustrates the selected public health terms in the context of <em>co-occurrences</em> — when two terms exist within the same tweet. The user can quickly see the relationships that exist, and the strength of those relationships. The block graphics correlate to the term, and the size of the corresponding blocks indicates the strength of the relationships to other terms. Through a few easy interactions, the user can remove particular terms from view, or fade out the graphic transparency of certain terms. This helps the user hone in on the analysis of specific data. The result is a concise, interactive infographic which makes a large amount of data easy to digest.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Social Media clearly has the potential to have significant impact on many aspects of public health practice. Without a doubt, there is much work to be done to best use this new source of data.  Of the many challenges, PHTweet focused its examination on the user experience/user interface aspects.  Work by other institutions has been taking place, examining issues around data quality.<sup>1</sup> We look forward to feedback and collaboration with the public health community.  The code for PHTweet is available from the R&amp;D Lab\'s code repository.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Code Repository:</strong> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/viewvc/informaticslab/PHTweet/\">http://code.phiresearchlab.org/viewvc/informaticslab/PHTweet/</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Launch Application:</strong> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://edemo.phiresearchlab.org/PHTweet2/\" target=\"_blank\">http://edemo.phiresearchlab.org/PHTweet2/</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\">(view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/phtweet1.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"PHTweet Bubble View Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/phtweet1.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHTweet Bubble View Screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"PHTweet Bubble View Screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/phtweet2.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"PHTweet Bubble View Screenshot Terms\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/phtweet2.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHTweet Bubble View Screenshot thumbnail Terms\" title=\"PHTweet Bubble View Screenshot thumbnail Terms\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /> </a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/phtweet2b.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"PHTweet Detail View Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/phtweet2b.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHTweet Detail View Screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"PHTweet Detail View Screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/phtweet3.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"PHTweet Graph View Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/phtweet3.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHTweet Graph View Screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"PHTweet Graph View Screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/phtweet4.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"PHTweet Relationship View Screenshot\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/phtweet4.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHTweet Relationship View Screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"PHTweet Relationship View Screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a></p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"Referencesicon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> Reference\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"> You are what you tweet: Tracking public health trends by Twitter. Phil Sneiderman. July 5, 2011. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://gazette.jhu.edu/2011/07/05/you-are-what-you-tweet-tracking-public-health-trends-by-twitter/\">http://gazette.jhu.edu/2011/07/05/you-are-what-you-tweet-tracking-public-health-trends-by-twitter/</a> Accessed January 26, 2012. </li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,1,'2012-01-25 20:04:15',62,'','2012-01-26 22:03:55',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-01-25 20:04:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',57,0,4,'','',0,134,'robots=\nauthor='),(86,'Situation Awareness Dashboard','situation-awareness-dashboard','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/sa_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Situation Awareness Dashboard Prototype icon\" title=\"Situation Awareness Dashboard Prototype icon\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 80px; float: left; height: 53px; border: 0px none;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=86:situation-awareness-dashboard&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">Situation Awareness Dashboard</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Prototype | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 7/14/2011 | <strong>Platform:</strong> Web | <strong>Version:</strong> Pre-alpha</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Interactive Dashboard Supporting Situational Awareness Requirements</p>\r\n<p>The Situation Awareness Dashboard prototype has been designed by the Informatics R&amp;D Lab team as a comprehensive tool which can provide critical information to the Situation Awareness Section within the CDC. The Situation Awareness Dashboard is designed to be a scalable, modular, and customizable web application. Its dashboard interface supplies a variety of high-level information at a glance, and allows the user to drill down into more detail. The current visual prototype consists of a series of non-functional, full resolution screen mockups. Subsequent phases will include the development of a functional prototype.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Goals and Methods:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Our main goal for the Situation Awareness Dashboard has been to support CDC\'s Emergency Preparedness and Response activities by providing actionable information that helps users make efficient, timely, and appropriate decisions. We designed this decision management dashboard by applying the concept of <em>business intelligence</em> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference1\">[1]</a>. Business intelligence (BI) applications allow organizations to gather, store, and analyze their raw data efficiently so they may quickly gain insights into their critical operations, such as revenues, expenditures, etc. Such insights help organizations act in an informed and expedient manner. We felt this general concept could be leveraged to assist CDC in its Situation Awareness activities.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The information presented by the dashboard is determined by the user’s role (based on log-in credentials). This allows users at various levels and positions within the organization to see information that is tailored to their job responsibilities.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The dashboard is organized into several tabs, and the user can specify which tab he/she wants to be the <em>Home</em> tab. We included many customizable features in the application so users can maximize their productivity.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">On the <em>My Apps</em> tab, various widgets provide summary information by topic, and each widget can launch a full application — thus allowing the user to dive deeper into the data. This tool is very scalable; as applications are developed and added, they can be launched by widgets on the dashboard. The user customizes which apps (applications) he/she sees on his/her <em>My Apps</em> tab (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\">screenshot #1</a> below). The user can also organize related apps into collections, and drag &amp; drop them into view from the <em>Collections</em> panel.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">An <em>App Library</em> tab (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\">screenshot #2</a> below) lists the applications available to the user (availability is based on user role), and the user can add applications as desired. For example, a data entry application could be available for users who need to submit entries for a daily report. A different application might be designed to aggregate and display critical information for executive leadership. The App Library is conceptually similar to the Apple App Store or the Android Market, and it gives users the freedom of selecting applications for his/her particular needs. Such customization options have the potential to streamline and optimize workflows.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">On the <em>Alerts</em> tab (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\">screenshot #3</a> below), alerts are listed based on urgency, date &amp; time, alert type, status, and reporting period. There is also a persistent <em>Alerts</em> panel on the right side of the screen — to reduce the chances of a user missing any important alerts.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The <em>Events</em> tab provides a wealth of information about events in both a map and a tabular format (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\">screenshots #4 and #5</a>). As with the overall structure of the design, a high-level picture is presented (e.g., the map with events indicated worldwide), as well as the option of drilling down into detailed information about each event (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\">screenshot #6</a>). Events can be filtered by the level of CDC involvement, event type, and reporting period.  Leveraging user-provided content for collaboration and knowledge-sharing, the notes area, provided with each event, allow users to share and comment on critical information.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Verified and validated RSS feeds related to situational awareness activities can be \"subscribed to,\" and then aggregated and displayed on the <em>Feeds</em> tab (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\">screenshot #7</a> below). The user can add, manage (i.e., configure), and read feeds in this central location. The ability to share and print articles is also built into the interface (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\">screenshot #8</a>).</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">An intuitive global search tool is provided to allow the user to quickly look for specific words - segregated by content type (e.g., Alerts, Events, Feeds).</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Essentially, the dashboard brings all relevant situational awareness data to the user in a centralized user interface — making the information easy to access and digest.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Design Philosophy:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Most design challenges associated with a dashboard user interface relate to the fact that a lot of information needs to be displayed, and it must be displayed clearly and succinctly. When bringing together this amount of information, it’s important to apply the <em>prägnanz</em> law of Gestalt psychology. The law of <em>prägnanz</em> (a German term translating to <em>conciseness</em> or <em>pithiness</em>) says that the human brain tends to group things together in a way that is consistent, simple, orderly, and symmetrical <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference2\">[2]</a>. Of course, this is important any time you’re visualizing data, but it is imperative when large amounts of data are brought together in a dashboard interface. For example, a designer’s careful attention to the similarity and proximity of onscreen elements can greatly expedite the user’s ability to differentiate groups of data. When a user is viewing a dashboard, it is crucial that he/she is able to decipher and comprehend the information quickly. A glance should provide the user with a snapshot of the information, and he/she can then probe into the details if needed.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">With a dashboard interface, it is also important to consider the urgency and priority of the data being presented. A plethora of data is made available, but where should the user place his/her primary focus, or focus first? We confronted this challenge in several situations. For example, the list of alerts on the <em>Alerts</em> tab provides a way to see any alert and explore its details, but what about the alerts that are occurring in real time while viewing a different tab within the application? Notification about those alerts in a timely manner could be critical. So we designed a persistent panel on the right side of the screen that displays alerts as they occur, and lists them in sequential order from top to bottom. The level of urgency is indicated, and users can dismiss any alert from the panel, if desired, when it is not important to his/her role. The user can also click into more information about an alert directly from the panel.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The Situation Awareness Section provides a critical function within CDC, and applying the appropriate technology to support that mission is essential. Organizing and presenting information effectively is a key component of applied technology, for it augments the interaction between user and computer. Our team explored a dashboard user interface because a well-designed dashboard is an effective antidote to information overload, and having the right information at the right time can greatly improve public health response.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Launch Interactive Demonstration:</strong> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"sa_dashboard_demo/1.html\" target=\"_blank\">Start demo</a> <br /><em>(NOTE: you must click the cursor icon on each screenshot to move forward)</em></p>\r\n<p><a class=\"reg\" href=\"sa_dashboard_demo/1.html\"> </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"sa_dashboard_demo/1.html\"></a><a name=\"screens\"></a><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\">(view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #1 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/1_my_apps.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, My Apps tab\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/1_my_apps.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, My Apps tab screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, My Apps tab screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #2 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/5_app_library.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, App Library tab\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/5_app_library.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, My Apps tab screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, App Library tab screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #3 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/7_alerts.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, Alerts tab\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/7_alerts.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, Alerts tab screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, Alerts tab screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a><br /><br /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #4 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/8_events_map.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, Events map\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/8_events_map.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, Events map screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, Events map screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #5 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/12_events_table.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, Events table\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/12_events_table.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, Events table screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, Events table screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #6 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/9_events_map_drilldown.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, Events map drilldown\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/9_events_map_drilldown.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, Events map drilldown screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, Events map drilldown screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <br /><br /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #7 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/13_feeds.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, Feeds tab\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/13_feeds.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, Feeds tab screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, Feeds tab screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #8 <a href=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/16_feeds_article_dd.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SA Dashboard Screenshot, Feeds article\"> <img src=\"images/prototypes/SAdashboard/16_feeds_article_dd.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SA Dashboard, Feeds article screenshot thumbnail\" title=\"SA Dashboard, Feeds article screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a></p>\r\n<ol class=\"sum2\"> <img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"Referencesicon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"> <a name=\"reference1\">Business Intelligence Definition and Solutions. Compiled by Ryan Mulcahy. </a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cio.com/article/40296/Business_Intelligence_Definition_and_Solutions\">http://www.cio.com/article/40296/Business_Intelligence_Definition_and_Solutions</a> <br />Accessed February 8, 2012. </li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference2\">Dashboard UIs: An Introduction. By Max Steenbergen. February 23, 2010. Article 494. </a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://uxmag.com/articles/dashboard-uis-an-introduction\">http://uxmag.com/articles/dashboard-uis-an-introduction</a></li>\r\n</ol>',1,1,0,1,'2012-02-07 18:58:55',62,'','2012-02-13 19:45:53',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-02-07 18:58:55','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',54,0,3,'','',0,6151,'robots=\nauthor='),(87,'Situation Awareness Dashboard Demo','situation-awareness-dashboard-demo','','<p>Situation Awareness Dashboard, Interactive Demo</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><em>Please click the cursor icon on each screenshot to move forward to the next screen.</em></p>','',-2,0,0,0,'2012-02-10 19:40:02',62,'','2012-02-10 19:43:53',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-02-10 19:40:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',2,0,0,'','',0,5,'robots=\nauthor='),(88,'Open Source Development','oss','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/open_source_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Open Source Development icon\" title=\"Open Source Development icon\" width=\"80\" height=\"53\" align=\"left\" style=\"float: left; border: 0;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=88:oss&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Open Source Development for Public Health Informatics</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 09/01/2011 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 03/01/2012 <br /><strong>Platform:</strong> Any | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">The Lab\'s experience using open source licenses for software development</p>\r\n<p>Open Source development is a viable option for public health informatics software development. While specific open source licenses should be selected based on individual project requirements, the R&amp;D Lab uses the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Apache Software License\">Apache Public License v2</a> (ASL) for many of its projects.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Overview:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The R&amp;D Lab, as a CDC government system within the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/osels/phsipo/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Public Health Surveillance &amp; Informatics Program Office\">Public Health Surveillance &amp; Informatics Program Office</a> (PHSIPO), is frequently asked how to use open source development in collaboration with partners both internal and external to the agency. Specifically, we are asked how we selected an open source license that includes the necessary protections for the R&amp;D Lab as a project sponsor as well as the Lab\'s partners as peer contributors and committers. While specific projects will evaluate and select a development methodology and software license based on the needs of their stakeholders, the Lab consulted with CDC\'s legal counsel to review and select a software license that allows us to share source code with as wide an audience as possible.<br /><br />This brief review shares our experiences in the hope that this may be helpful to other organizations within the public health informatics community interesting in using open source to improve transparency and increase software reuse.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>Although some large projects and government entities do have specific \"Open Source Policies\" [<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference1\">1</a>], this review does not speak for the CDC and certainly does not establish any requirements.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Open source projects are increasingly common at the Office of the National Coordinator for Health IT (ONC)(e.g., <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.connectopensource.org/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"CONNECT Open Source\">CONNECT</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://wiki.directproject.org/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Direct Project Wiki\">Direct Project</a>), Veteran’s Administration &amp; Department of Defense (e.g., <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.osehra.org/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Open Source Electronic Health Record Agent\">OSEHRA</a>) and the National Cancer Institute (NCI) of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) (e.g., <a class=\"reg\" href=\"https://cabig.nci.nih.gov/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Cancer Biomedical Informatics Grid\">caBIG</a>) and others. Projects within PHITPO and its public health partners also seek to develop and release software projects under an open source license. These programs seek to use open source licenses for many positive reasons including, but not limited to: greater community involvement, increased scope of features, greater user adoption, reduced cost of development and increased reuse and interoperability across federal and partner agencies.<br /><br />The <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://opensource.org/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Open Source Initiative\">Open Source Initiative</a> (OSI) defines open source software as complying with 10 criteria [<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference2\">2</a>]: free redistribution of software programs, free availability of source code, allowing derived works, integrity of source code, no discrimination against groups, no discrimination against fields of endeavor, distribution of license, license must not be specific to a product, license must not restrict other software, and that the license must be technology neutral. Although OSI recognizes over 75 licenses, these licenses generally fall into three categories:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Permissive licenses - provide few, if any, restrictions on modifications and extensions to software (e.g., <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/Apache-2.0\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Apache Software License\">ASL</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/BSD-3-Clause\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"BSD\">BSD</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/MIT\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"MIT\">MIT</a>)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Viral licenses - require that modifications, extensions and linkages be covered and distributed under a compatible license (e.g., <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/GPL-3.0\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"GNU General Public License\">GPL</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/LGPL-3.0\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"GNU Lesser General Public License\">LGPL</a>)</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Hybrid licenses - combination of permissive and viral licenses that provides limited restrictions on how modifications and extensions to software are distributed back to the community (e.g., <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/MPL-2.0\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Mozilla Public License\">MPL</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/EPL-1.0\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Eclipse Public License\">EPL</a>).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Licenses are historically chosen by the community and sponsoring organization based on the specific requirements of the project with permissive licenses allowing for greater reuse and viral or hybrid licenses providing greater control over a project.<br /><br />CDC has a history of using permissive licenses, beginning in 2008, to develop and share projects with the open source community through projects sponsored by the R&amp;D Lab and Epi-Info program. Additional programs have expressed interest in developing software in an open source manner so it is efficient to provide a single guidance document that answers the common question of: which license is appropriate for use.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Experiences:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Based on the use of permissive licenses with existing projects within the federal government (ONC CONNECT, VA/DoD OSEHRA, NCI caBIG) and the availability of government produced source code under the Freedom of Information Act, a permissive license is typically, pragmatically selected for use by Lab projects. A viral or hybrid license may place restrictions that would be difficult by the government to enforce and would limit reuse of software with the public health community.<br /><br />Given that the Lab\'s key requirements for software projects are collaboration, sharing, reuse and transparency the default license used by a project should be the ASL, although individual projects may have specific needs that lead them to select an alternative license, including non-open source licenses, for use within their project (e.g., sensitive data contained within the source code; security configuration within the source code; intellectual property used within the source code, etc.).<br /><br />The ASL is selected as guidance based primarily on its permissive nature and on its extensive use within the federal government at ONC and VA/DoD. This license explicitly provides protections for liability as it clearly states that all software is provided without warranty or support. Issues such as security, privacy, quality and stewardship of federal resources, are not negatively impacted solely by the specific selection of the ASL.<br /><br />Our projects explicitly note their use of the ASL by including a LICENSE.TXT file within the root of the source code repository that contains the text of the license (see Appendix A) and by including a header within each source file that is included within the project.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"References icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">OSEHRA Licensing Terms - v1.0 <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.osehra.org/sites/default/files/osehra_licensing_terms_v.1.0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"OSERA Licensing Terms\">http://www.osehra.org/sites/default/files/osehra_licensing_terms_v.1.0.pdf </a>Accessed 2011.11.08<a name=\"reference1\"></a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">OSI Open Source Definition, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://opensource.org/docs/osd\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"OSI Open Source Definition\">http://opensource.org/docs/osd</a> Accessed 2011.10.04<a name=\"reference2\"></a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,3,'2012-03-27 04:26:00',62,'BAL','2012-08-08 18:09:13',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-03-27 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',25,0,3,'','',0,76,'robots=\nauthor='),(89,'PHIN Partner Presentation','phin-partner-presentation','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/news/phin_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PHIN icon\" title=\"PHIN icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><span style=\"position: relative; top: 10px;\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=89:phin-partner-presentation&amp;catid=4:news&amp;Itemid=6\">Public Health Information Network (PHIN) Partner Presentation</a></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">IRDA Presents Resources Available to CDC and the Public Health Community</p>\r\n<p>At the monthly PHIN Partner Call on March 7, 2012, the Informatics Research &amp; Development Activity (IRDA) described the resources and services it provides to CDC and the public health community. 70 people were in attendance. The presentation walked through the architecture, history, and processes used in IRDA\'s research cloud. Several of the IRDA’s partner engagements were described, and a selection of prototype engagements were demonstrated and discussed. The presentation illustrated how IRDA collaborates with CDC programs and the public health community to fulfill its mission — advancing the field of public health informatics through applied research and innovation.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The PowerPoint slides from the presentation are available here: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/PHINPartnerPres-IRDA-20120307-v2.ppt\">PHIN Partner Presentation, 03/07/2012</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>','',1,2,0,4,'2012-04-12 19:42:48',62,'','2012-04-18 17:42:11',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-04-12 19:42:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',22,0,3,'','',0,36,'robots=\nauthor='),(90,'Mobile Virtual Reality Mine Safety Training iPad Prototype','niosh-mine-safety-training-ipad-application','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/mine_safety_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Mine Safety Training application icon\" title=\"Mine Safety Training application icon\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 80px; float: left; height: 53px; border: 0px;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=90:niosh-mine-safety-training-ipad-application&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">Mobile Virtual Reality Mine Safety Training iPad Prototype</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Prototype | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 10/05/2011 | <strong>Platform:</strong> iOS | <strong>Version:</strong> 1.0</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Tablet-based Immersive Mine Safety Training</p>\r\n<p>The CDC Informatics R&amp;D Lab has collaborated with NIOSH (CDC’s National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health) in areas related to mobile applications that support the Institute’s Occupational Health objectives. For example, one such effort yielded a prototype that is a mobile device interface to the NIOSH Personal Protection Technology Laboratory’s Certified Equipment List data collection. More information on this prototype can be found <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=75:-niosh-facepiece-respirator-guide-for-iphone-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">here</a>. In addition, the application can be directly downloaded to an iOS-based device from our App Lab <a class=\"reg\" href=\"applab/facepiece.php\">here</a>.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />In October, 2011 the Informatics R&amp;D Lab pursued an alternative approach to an existing NIOSH area that is a large-scale virtual reality laboratory for mining safety training. The R&amp;D effort resulted in a prototype to demonstrate how a mobile device solution would be deployed as a portable, convenient, high-quality and engaging training experience. The prototype development took place on Apple’s iOS, which provides cost benefits derived from using the features of a commodity multi-purpose software and hardware platform when compared to a highly specialized single-purpose platform. The prototype is optimized to run on Apple’s iPad.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Current Prototype:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The virtual environment is created by leveraging sophisticated capabilities embedded in today\'s mobile devices. In the R&amp;D Lab’s prototype, cutting-edge gaming technology (Epic Game’s Unreal Engine) as well as the iPad\'s built-in accelerometer and gyroscope create an engaging, immersive, life-like environment with geo-spatial characteristics that can be tailored to individual trainee instruction. Only a few years ago, an experience such as this would have been impossible on a mobile platform.<br /><br />In the current prototype, the user (trainee) is able to explore sights and sounds of a virtual mine shaft where the screen of the iPad or iPhone is a window into the mine (i.e., to look up at the ceiling of the shaft, the device is directed toward the ceiling), and interact with the environment via the touchscreen. Based on their activities, the trainee is sent messages and questions, and the mine shaft environment changes to match the response criteria. A demonstration of the prototype is available to download from our App Lab <a class=\"reg\" href=\"applab/minesafety.php\">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Future Steps:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Acknowledging the limited scope of the initial prototype, future enhancements could include interactivity / collaboration among multiple users (e.g., awareness of relative positions of users) and allowing a trainer to configure and adjust the mining environment dynamically. Further software development could enable the trainer to be able to obtain data from the students, both actively during training via pop-up alerts which require a voice or touch-response — or passively by using information derived from the positional movement of the devices. This information could also be collected and analyzed post training to improve the training delivery as well as the detail of the content.<br /><br />In summary, the prototype is a realistic demonstration of the capabilities of mobile devices as well as the ability to use those features through software development to create a rich interactive training environment.</p>\r\n<!--\r\n<p><b>Goals and Methods:</b></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">A primary goal for this prototype was to provide an immersive training experience for the user. Immersive media engage the senses in a variety of ways to make the user feel integrated into the alternate reality that is presented. Many 3D video gaming environments do this quite well, and the boundary between the user and the fictional world starts to evaporate. The user feels that he/she<i> is</i> the character represented onscreen, rather than simply controlling the character onscreen. Many organizations, including NOAA (The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration), have found immersive training to be a lower-cost training solution that’s safe because it allows people to practice their skills while circumventing physical harm <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference1\" mce_href=\"#reference1\">[1]</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To create this immersive training experience, we leveraged the iPad mobile tablet device and the immersive gaming platform, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.unrealengine.com\" mce_href=\"http://www.unrealengine.com\">Unreal Engine</a> — a tool used by many game developers with a core written in C++ <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference2\" mce_href=\"#reference2\">[2]</a>. The mine shaft depicted in the application has realistic, animated 3D graphics (which can be created in <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://usa.autodesk.com/maya\" mce_href=\"http://usa.autodesk.com/maya\">Autodesk\'s Maya</a> or <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.newtek.com/lightwave.html\" mce_href=\"http://www.newtek.com/lightwave.html\">NewTek\'s LightWave</a>). See <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\" mce_href=\"#screens\">screenshot #1</a> below. The application takes advantage of the iPad’s built-in accelerometer, gyroscope, compass, and GPS capabilities. These allow the user to navigate within the application by touching the screen, and to change the field of vision by moving the actual device. In a sense, the device becomes the user’s <i>eye</i> within the mine shaft.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To train the students, emergency events occur when a student reaches a specific location within the mine. The training experience is enhanced by sound. For example, when liquid starts to drip from the ceiling of the mine shaft, the student can hear it. Once the student moves closer to the emergency event, he/she is presented with a set of choices regarding how to resolve the situation (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\" mce_href=\"#screens\">screenshot #2</a> below). The scene provides instant feedback based on the student’s decision. For instance, cones immediately appear on the ground if the student decides to clean up the dripping liquid (see <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\" mce_href=\"#screens\">screenshot #3</a> below).</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To create a more seamless experience, user assistance is integrated within the interface. So rather than touching a Help button, context-sensitive information appears on the screen when the user appears to be having difficulty.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><b>Future Enhancements:</b></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Since this is an early proof-of-concept prototype, there are several design enhancements that we hope to implement in the future.</p>\r\n<ul style=\"padding-top:6px; margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:6px; margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px;\" type=\"disc\">\r\n<li><i>Multiple users:</i> allow for interactivity and collaboration among multiple users. Users could be aware of the relative positions of other users within the mining environment.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li><i>Trainer-specific features:</i> \r\n<ul style=\"margin-right:10px; margin-left:10px;\" mce_style=\"margin-right:10px; margin-left:10px;\" type=\"circle\">\r\n<li>The trainer could configure and adjust the mining environment. For example, the trainer could turn an emergency event on or off (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"#screens\" mce_href=\"#screens\">screenshot #4</a> below shows this as a Settings option).</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding-top:8px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:8px;\">The trainer could obtain data from the students, both actively (e.g., via alerts which require a voice or touch response) and passively (e.g., from sensing the positional movement of the devices).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding-top:11px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:11px;\"><i>Further enhance the immersive experience:</i> make feedback more immersive (e.g., better integration of the information that is currently presented by dialog boxes).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><b>Design Philosophy:</b></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Immersive training has been implemented in a variety of fields: medicine, military, law enforcement, aviation, and others. When designing immersive training systems, it is important to create an experience that leads to what is known as the <i>Sense of Presence (SoP)</i>. According to Dr. Mel Slater, Professor of Virtual Environments, University College London, the SoP has three main aspects:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"padding-top:6px; margin-right:20px; margin-left:20px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:6px; margin-right:20px; margin-left:20px;\">\r\n<li>a sense of <i>being there</i></li>\r\n<li style=\"padding-top:5px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:5px;\">an extent to which the virtual environment becomes dominant</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding-top:5px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:5px;\">remembering the virtual environment as <i>having visited the place</i> rather than <i>having seen images of the place</i>. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference3\" mce_href=\"#reference3\">[3]</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To create an SoP, technologies that enable the virtual environment should be hidden from the user so they do not distract from the student’s immersive learning experience. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference3\" mce_href=\"#reference3\">[3]</a> This is where the notion of <i>diegetic</i> interfaces come in.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">With <i>diegetic</i> interfaces, everything takes place within the virtual environment. For example, if the user needs to see a map, the onscreen character actually gets out a map and views it. In a non-diegetic experience, the user would press a key, for example, and the virtual environment would pause. Then a map would come to the foreground of the screen — temporarily hiding the virtual environment. In this latter case, the user is aware of the map, but the character in the environment is not. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference4\" mce_href=\"#reference4\">[4]</a> In film, a diegetic sound is one that both the character and the viewer hear, like a line said to the character. A non-diegetic sound is one that only the viewer hears, like director commentary or mood music. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference5\" mce_href=\"#reference5\">[5]</a> Diegetic experiences make anything that the user/viewer needs to know part of the storyline itself. Therefore, with diegetic interfaces, the user feels more fully immersed into the virtual environment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">In virtual environments, non-diegetic interface elements are often <i>HUD (Heads-up Display)</i> interface elements. A HUD is a collection of persistent onscreen elements that indicate the status of the character within the virtual environment. They might show, for example, how healthy the character is, which direction the character is going, or the character’s ranking within the task. HUD elements are a barrier to a totally immersive experience because they remind the user that <i>this is just a game</i> or <i>this is just an interface</i>. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"#reference6\" mce_href=\"#reference6\">[6]</a> Therefore, more immersive UIs try to reduce the intrusiveness of HUD elements by putting this needed information directly within the users’ virtual environment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">To create a more immersive training experience, the Mine Safety Training prototype employs the following interactions and elements:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px; padding-top:6px;\" mce_style=\"margin-left:20px; margin-right:20px; padding-top:6px;\" type=\"disc\">\r\n<li>touch-screen interface, which allows direct manipulation</li>\r\n<li>intuitive navigation within the scene (no separate controller, no HUD map)</li>\r\n<li>diegetic sound heard by both the character and user</li>\r\n<li>using the device as the <i>eye</i> into the field of view; an example of technology that supports the environment starting to <i>disappear</i></li>\r\n<li>context-sensitive user assistance</li>\r\n<li>immediate feedback within the scene based on the user’s reaction to an emergency event</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><b>Conclusion:</b></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\" mce_style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Immersive virtual applications open new doors for training and education, providing benefits for both the organization and the student. Cost, safety, and convenience are important factors when assessing an immersive training system, and tablet devices are an attractive option. Occupational safety training is an important aspect of public health, and we learned much during this collaboration with NIOSH. Immersive training presents many interesting possibilities, and we look forward to more collaboration and feedback from the public health community. The code for this prototype is available from the lab’s code repository.</p>\r\n-->\r\n<p><br /><strong>Code Repository:</strong> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/viewvc/informaticslab/VRMineSIm/\">http://code.phiresearchlab.org/viewvc/informaticslab/VRMineSIm/</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><a name=\"screens\"></a><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\">(view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #1 <a href=\"images/prototypes/mine1.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Mine shaft\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/mine1.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Mine shaft, thumbnail\" title=\"Mine shaft screenshot thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #2 <a href=\"images/prototypes/mine2.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Decision point\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/mine2.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Decision point, thumbnail\" title=\"Decision point, thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #3 <a href=\"images/prototypes/mine3.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Cones appear in response to decision\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/mine3.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Cones appear in response to decision, thumbnail\" title=\"Cones appear in response to decision, thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a><br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> #4 <a href=\"images/prototypes/mine4.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Settings\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/mine4.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Settings, thumbnail\" title=\"Settings, thumbnail\" width=\"150\" height=\"101\" style=\"border:1px solid black\" /></a></p>\r\n<ol class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"Referencesicon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference1\">Immersive Training Spaces. Imagination: Creating the Future of Education and Work.</a> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://creatingthefuturetoday.com/pages/8\">http://creatingthefuturetoday.com/pages/8</a><br />Accessed April 19, 2012.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference2\">Unreal Engine. Wikipedia. </a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unreal_Engine\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unreal_Engine</a> <br />Accessed April 19, 2012.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference3\">Immersive VR Decision Training: Telling Interactive Stories Featuring Advanced Virtual Human Simulation Technologies. Ponder, Herbelin, Molet et al. 2003. Virtual Reality Lab (VRlab), Swiss Federal Institute of Technology (EPFL), Lausanne, Switzerland. MIRALab, University of Geneva, Switzerland. </a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.miralab.ch/repository/papers/127.pdf\">http://www.miralab.ch/repository/papers/127.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference4\">Game UI Analysis. Virtual Learning Worlds. February 26th, 2010. </a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://virtuallearningworlds.com/?cat=10\">http://virtuallearningworlds.com/?cat=10</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference5\">FilmSound.org: Learning Space dedicated to the Art and Analyses of Film Sound Design. </a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://filmsound.org/terminology/diegetic.htm\">http://filmsound.org/terminology/diegetic.htm</a> <br />Accessed April 20, 2012.</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a name=\"reference6\">Off With Their HUDs!: Rethinking the Heads-Up Display in Console Game Design. by Greg Wilson. February 3, 2006. Gamasutra. </a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/2538/off_with_their_huds_rethinking_.php\">http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/2538/off_with_their_huds_rethinking_.php</a></li>\r\n</ol>',1,1,0,1,'2012-08-08 11:14:23',62,'','2012-08-14 21:16:51',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-08-08 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',85,0,2,'','',0,158,'robots=\nauthor='),(91,'Official Launch of iOS App Lab for R&D Prototypes','official-launch-of-ios-app-lab-for-rad-prototypes','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/news/labapp_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"App Lab icon\" title=\"App Lab icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><span style=\"position: relative; top: 10px;\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=91:official-launch-of-ios-app-lab-for-rad-prototypes&amp;catid=4:news&amp;Itemid=6\">Official Launch of iOS App Lab for R&amp;D Prototypes</a></span></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">IRDA launches App Lab for Public Health R&amp;D mobile prototype apps for iOS-based devices (iPhone, iPad, etc.)</p>\r\n<p>On June 14, 2012, CDC’s Informatics Research &amp; Development Activity (IRDA) team launched its app lab of prototype mobile applications (currently iPhone &amp; iPad only, but soon to include Android and other mobile OSes). This app lab (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.phiresearchlab.org/applab/\">http://www.phiresearchlab.org/applab/</a>) is a tool for the Lab, CDC, &amp; its public health partners to test and collaborate on innovative mobile apps. These prototypes serve a wide variety of purposes – but ultimately are efficient and effective tools for gaining knowledge and decision making. Along with the launch of the app lab, the R&amp;D Lab is making available 5 iPhone prototypes and 4 iPad prototypes. The lab provides an easy-to-use environment to learn about and experience these prototypes. Valuable information about each app in the lab includes a description, screenshots, iOS version requirements, and links to source code. When the app lab is viewed on a mobile iOS-based device, by simply clicking on the <em>Download</em> button, users can easily install an app on that device. When it is viewed on a laptop or desktop PC, users can install an app via the use of iTunes. New features, including high-resolution graphics and user feedback, are in final stages of testing, and will be launched soon.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Please note that this app lab does NOT contain production apps, but prototype / proof-of-concept apps. If and/or when a prototype app <em>graduates</em> to production, the R&amp;D Lab’s app lab will provide links to <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/mobile/applications/cdcgeneral/promos/ipad_promo.html\">CDC’s mobile site</a> as well as Apple’s official App Store. For more information or questions, please contact the R&amp;D team at <a class=\"reg\" href=\"mailto:informaticslab@cdc.gov\">informaticslab@cdc.gov</a>.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The App Lab can be found at <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.phiresearchlab.org/applab/\">http://www.phiresearchlab.org/applab/</a>.</p>\r\n<p> </p>','',1,2,0,4,'2012-06-14 13:39:27',62,'','2012-06-14 14:35:07',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-06-14 13:39:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',8,0,2,'','',0,17,'robots=\nauthor='),(92,'iPhone App Development','iphone-app-dev','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/iphone_dev_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"iPhone App Development icon\" title=\"iPhone App Development icon\" width=\"80\" height=\"53\" align=\"left\" style=\"float: left; border: 0;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=92:iphone-app-dev&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">iPhone App Development Lessons Learned</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 05/01/2012 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 07/06/2012 <br /><strong>Platform:</strong> iOS | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">The Lab\'s experience developing mobile applications for the iPhone platform using existing and new processes within CDC.</p>\r\n<p>Mobile computing is a growing component of CDC\'s interaction with the public. This review shares the lessons learned by the Lab and its partners in designing, developing, testing and releasing a clinical guidance app for use by physicians. Although the processes followed are specific to CDC, the lessons learned may be useful to any group working within a public health organization.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Overview:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The R&amp;D Lab, in cooperation with <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/osels/lspppo/index.html\">LSPPPO</a> developed an iPhone app, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=74:-prolonged-ptt-advisor-for-iphone-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">PTT Advisor</a>, to assist clinical providers with management of patients requiring complex coagulation testing. The functionality of the app can be experienced by <a class=\"reg\" href=\"applab/ptt.php\">downloading the app from the R&amp;D App Lab</a> and the specific functionality of the app will be described in a forthcoming manuscript. This article seeks to capture the lessons learned by the project team to develop a process that can be reused by other public health programs, both within and outside CDC, to develop new smartphone applications for use by the public health community.<br /><br />This review is not meant to be exhaustive and please email or comment with any questions that are not answered within this article. Specifically, we will cover the following areas:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum3\">\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Software development process</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Legal review</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Security and privacy review</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">Scientific review</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">User review and beta testing</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum2\">App Store publication</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/ptt-process-drawing.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Process Diagram\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Software development process:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Lab and its partners used an iterative, agile approach to developing the iPhone app. We used this approach as this was a fairly unknown development area with our group so we wanted to use a method that allowed for flexibility yet still met the needs of the CDC program sponsoring the app. The application was written in Objective C (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/viewvc/informaticslab/ptt-advisor/\">source code available here</a>) following Apple\'s <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.apple.com/library/ios/#DOCUMENTATION/UserExperience/Conceptual/MobileHIG/Introduction/Introduction.html\">Human Interface Guidelines for iOS</a> <br /><br />The LSPPPO team worked with its clinical SME stakeholders to identify the algorithms and decision trees that were to be used by the app to provide guidance. The Lab team then took these paper algorithms and developed a set of rules that were then implemented within the app to allow for intuitive and rapid algorithm navigation, as well as rapid modification to accommodate revisions and changes to the algorithm during the development lifecycle.<br /><br />Many iterations were shared with stakeholders within CDC, and once the app was deemed to be ready (i.e., stable, and easy to use),  it was released to a small set of beta testers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>User review and beta testing:</strong></p>\r\n<p>LSPPPO gathered a set of 22 volunteer beta testers including 8 practicing physicians. These beta testers received a link to download the app on their personal devices to test functionality. Based on feedback collected from this beta test, the developers made minor revisions to prepare it for release to the Apple iTunes App Store.<br /><br />Although the number of beta testers was smaller than we would have preferred, the project team was able to determine that the app was suitable for general release through the app store so that further feedback could be collected from users.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Legal review:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Prior to release to the App Store, legal counsel within CDC\'s Office of the General Counsel (OGC) reviewed the app from a legal perspective to make sure that the terms of the App Store as well as the expectations of users was properly met. After multiple discussions with OGC and program staff, an <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/viewvc/informaticslab/ptt-advisor/trunk/anticoagmon/anticoagmon/neweula.html?revision=531&amp;view=co\">end user license agreement (EULA)</a> was developed for the application using similar language from other mobile apps created by the federal government. <br /><br />In addition to the EULA development, the Lab worked with OGC to determine what license should be used for the development and distribution of the app. The R&amp;D Lab selected the Apache Software License 2.0 so that other groups could reuse the code written for the app. Further details on the process of evaluating and selecting a license can be found in the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=88:oss&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">\"Open Source Development for Public Health Informatics\" brief review</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Security and privacy review:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Security was a prime requirement for the app design, especially since this was the first app developed for release by the Lab and its partners. To protect the privacy of the app users, the app does not store any data nor does it use any sensitive data. The algorithms themselves are currently in the process of being published in the peer-reviewed literature and do not contain sensitive information. In the application, the user does not store any settings, nor does the app access any patient data. Because the app does not use any sensitive data, the security design was limited to developing an incident response plan, in the case that the Apple iTunes Store became compromised.  In addition, a required <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.hhs.gov/pia/\">privacy impact assessment (PIA)</a> was completed. Please email InformaticsLab@cdc.gov for examples of how we developed these documents.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Scientific review:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our final review, prior to publishing the app was to use CDC\'s scientific clearance process to assure the quality and integrity of the science involved in the mobile app. As is standard at CDC, communication and policy review was also included in this overall clearance process.  Because the app was clinical guidance issued by CDC, scientific review was performed by not only the two C/I/Os involved in the process (PHSIPO and LSPPPO), but also by OSELS\' and CDC\'s associate directors for science.  Since CDC\'s e-clearance system, at the time of submission, did not have a preset configuration for clearing mobile phone apps, the Lab team created a document containing all material used within the app: screenshots, language, license agreements and metadata. This document was then reviewed and revised to achieve clearance by the associate directors for science and the associate directors for communication.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>App Store publication</strong>:</p>\r\n<p>Once we achieved all reviews and had made the appropriate modifications, the app was ready for publication to Apple\'s iTunes App Store. CDC\'s Office of the Associate Director for Communication (OADC) has an established iTunes account for CDC and manages the team that packages and submits all iPhone apps on behalf of the agency. The Lab coordinated with this team to prepare our app according to the metadata requirements set by Apple (<a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.apple.com/library/ios/#qa/qa1686/_index.html\">working with Icons</a> and <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.apple.com/library/ios/#documentation/iPhone/Conceptual/iPhoneOSProgrammingGuide/Introduction/Introduction.html\">iOS Developer Library</a>).<br /><br />The app was released for free to the public for download and can be viewed in the iTunes store: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/ptt-advisor/id537989131?mt=8&amp;ls=1\">PTT Advisor app</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>While the development of the Lab\'s first production iPhone app may seem arduous, many of the policy and scientific pieces can now be reused by other programs. The Lab and LSPPPO have a repeatable process where the legal, security, policy and scientific review process can now be \"templated\" and reused for future programs. Other programs can now develop additional apps for the iPhone and other mobile platforms- either independently or in collaboration with CDC\'s Informatics R&amp;D Lab.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"References icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Apple iOS Development Guidelines - <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.apple.com/library/ios/#documentation/iPhone/Conceptual/iPhoneOSProgrammingGuide/Introduction/Introduction.html\">http://bit.ly/dy9I0e</a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.osehra.org/sites/default/files/osehra_licensing_terms_v.1.0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Apple iOS Programming Guide\"> </a><br />Accessed 2012.07.06<a name=\"reference1\"></a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Apache Software License v2 - <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\">http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0</a> <br />Accessed 2012.07.06</li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,3,'2012-07-06 06:15:00',62,'BAL','2012-08-08 18:08:58',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-07-06 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',61,0,2,'','',0,133,'robots=\nauthor='),(93,'\"PTT Advisor\" Graduates to Apple App Store','qptt-advisorq-graduates-to-apple-app-store','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/news/ptt_advisor_news_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"PTT Advisor app icon\" title=\"PTT Advisor app\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><span style=\"position: relative; top: 10px;\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=93:qptt-advisorq-graduates-to-apple-app-store&amp;catid=4:news&amp;Itemid=6\">\"PTT Advisor\" Graduates to Apple App Store</a></span></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">The mobile prototype app for iPhone, \"PTT Advisor,\" graduates to Apple App Store</p>\r\n<p>On July 6, 2012, the R&amp;D Lab\'s prototype mobile clinical decision support app, \"PTT Advisor,\" became available in the Apple App Store: <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/ptt-advisor/id537989131?mt=8&amp;ls=1\">see PTT Advisor in the Apple App Store</a>. This app, based on a close collaboration between the R&amp;D Lab and CDC\'s <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/osels/lspppo/index.html\"> Laboratory Science, Policy and Practice Program Office</a>, began its development in the summer of 2011 — supported through CDC\'s 2011 iFund Challenge award. <br /><br /> The app assists clinical providers in their evaluation of patients with an abnormal clinical laboratory blood test, specifically an abnormal PTT (Partial Thromboplastin Time). The application has been created to easily navigate through the detailed laboratory testing algorithms. The algorithms may help to reduce inappropriate coagulation testing as well as possible adverse patient outcomes from, for example, a delay in diagnosis. <br /><br /> This application leverages coagulation testing algorithms, which were developed by a group of volunteer laboratory experts working together on a CDC-sponsored team as part of the Clinical Laboratory Integration into Healthcare Collaborative (CLIHC)™ project. The prototype leverages the algorithms as documented in flow charts and turns them into electronic, interactive, decision support tools for clinical provider use. <br /><br /> The algorithms are organized digitally to allow the user to easily walk through a complicated flow diagram by answering one question at a time in an interactive format.<br /><br /> To download the free app, simply search the Apple App Store for \"PTT Advisor\" on your mobile device. <br /><br /> To learn more about the app, feel free to read the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=74:-prolonged-ptt-advisor-for-iphone-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">R&amp;D Lab’s posting from June 2011</a>, or contact the R&amp;D Lab staff at <a class=\"reg\" href=\"mailto:informaticslab@cdc.gov\">informaticslab@cdc.gov</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>','',1,2,0,4,'2012-07-11 14:13:31',62,'','2012-07-11 16:22:46',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-07-11 14:13:31','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',14,0,1,'','',0,50,'robots=\nauthor='),(94,'z_OLD_CDC\'s Vision for Public Health Surveillance in the 21st Century','-using-secure-web-services-to-visualize-poison-center-data-for-nationwide-biosurveillance-a-case-study-','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/stories/graph_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Graph icon\" title=\"Graph icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=12:-using-secure-web-services-to-visualize-poison-center-data-for-nationwide-biosurveillance-a-case-study-&amp;catid=5:publications&amp;Itemid=7\">CDC\'s Vision for Public Health Surveillance in the 21st Century</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Specific Report:  The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\"><br />Thomas G. Savel, MD,  Seth Foldy, MD</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\">CDC\'s Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR) Supplement  July 27, 2012 / 61(03);20-24</p>\r\n<p><br />OVERVIEW:</p>\r\n<p>This 44 page MMWR supplement summarizes the deliberations of CDC/ATSDR scientists and managers who met in September 2009 in Atlanta as part of the 2009 Consultation on CDC/ATSDR’s Vision for Public Health Surveillance in the 21st Century. The meeting was convened to reflect on domestic and global public health surveillance practice and to recommend a strategic framework to advance public health surveillance to meet continuing and new challenges. The first report is an adaptation of the keynote address for the meeting, which summarized the history of public health surveillance, the need to reassess its usefulness, the rationale for topics selected for  discussion, and the charge to participants. Subsequent reports summarize the discussions of workgroups that addressed specific topics in surveillance science and practices.  The specific report on The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance was co-authored by a member of the R&amp;D Lab team.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The specific report on The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance proposes a vision for informatics in enhancing public health  surveillance, identifies challenges and opportunities, and suggests  approaches to attain the vision. This topic was identified by CDC  leadership as one of six major concerns that must be addressed by the  public health community to advance public health surveillance in the 21<span class=\"superscript\">st </span>century.  The six topics were discussed by CDC workgroups that were convened as  part of the 2009 Surveillance Consultation to advance public health  surveillance to meet continuing and new challenges (<em><a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/su6103a1.htm?s_cid=su6103a1_w\">2</a></em>).  Although this report is not based on workgroup discussions, it is  intended to continue the conversations with the public health community  for a shared vision for public health surveillance in the 21<span class=\"superscript\">st</span> century.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>View MMWR Supplements on CDC website</p>\r\n<p>http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/ind2012_su.html</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>View specific section on The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance</p>\r\n<p>http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/su6103a5.htm?s_cid=su6103a5_w</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>View PDF of full supplement</p>\r\n<p>http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/pdf/other/su6103.pdf</p>',-2,3,0,5,'2010-12-08 15:36:11',62,'','2012-08-01 17:42:30',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2010-12-08 15:36:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',6,0,0,'','',0,0,'robots=\nauthor='),(95,'CDC\'s Vision for Public Health Surveillance in the 21st Century','cdcs-vision-for-public-health-surveillance-in-the-21st-century','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/publications/mmwr_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"MMWR icon\" title=\"MMWR icon\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><span style=\"position: relative; top: 10px;\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=95:cdcs-vision-for-public-health-surveillance-in-the-21st-century&amp;catid=5:publications&amp;Itemid=7\">CDC\'s Vision for Public Health Surveillance in the 21st Century</a></span></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">Specific Report: The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\"><br />Thomas G. Savel, MD,  Seth Foldy, MD</p>\r\n<p class=\"small_type\">CDC\'s Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR) Supplement  July 27, 2012 / 61(03);20-24</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>OVERVIEW:</p>\r\n<p>This 44 page MMWR supplement summarizes the deliberations of CDC/ATSDR scientists and managers who met in September 2009 in Atlanta as part of the 2009 Consultation on CDC/ATSDR’s Vision for Public Health Surveillance in the 21st Century. The meeting was convened to reflect on domestic and global public health surveillance practice, and to recommend a strategic framework to advance public health surveillance to meet continuing and new challenges. The first report is an adaptation of the keynote address for the meeting, which summarized the history of public health surveillance, the need to reassess its usefulness, the rationale for topics selected for  discussion, and the charge to participants. Subsequent reports summarize the discussions of workgroups that addressed specific topics in surveillance science and practices. The specific report on <em>The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance</em> was co-authored by a member of the R&amp;D Lab team.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br />The specific report on <em>The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance</em> proposes a vision for informatics in enhancing public health surveillance, identifies challenges and opportunities, and suggests approaches to attain the vision. This topic was identified by CDC leadership as one of six major concerns that must be addressed by the public health community to advance public health surveillance in the 21<span class=\"superscript\">st </span>century. The six topics were discussed by CDC workgroups that were convened as part of the 2009 Surveillance Consultation, with the goal of advancing public health surveillance to meet continuing and new challenges. Although this report is not based on workgroup discussions, it is  intended to continue the conversations with the public health community for a shared vision for public health surveillance in the 21<span class=\"superscript\">st</span> century.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>View MMWR Supplements on CDC website:<br /> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/ind2012_su.html\">http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/ind2012_su.html</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>View specific section on <em>The Role of Public Health Informatics in Enhancing Public Health Surveillance</em>:<br /> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/su6103a5.htm?s_cid=su6103a5_w\">http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/su6103a5.htm?s_cid=su6103a5_w</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>View PDF of full supplement:<br /> <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/pdf/other/su6103.pdf\">http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/pdf/other/su6103.pdf</a></p>',1,3,0,5,'2012-08-01 17:43:58',62,'','2012-08-01 20:15:24',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-08-01 17:43:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',17,0,1,'','',0,51,'robots=\nauthor='),(96,'Cross-Platform Mobile Development Tool Selection','shirly-tool','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/limited_prototype_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Cross-Platform Mobile Development Tool Selection icon\" title=\"Cross-Platform Mobile Development Tool Selection icon\" width=\"80\" height=\"53\" align=\"left\" style=\"float: left; border: 0;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=96:shirly-tool&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Cross-Platform Mobile Development Tool Selection</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Brief Review | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 07/01/2012 | <strong>End Date:</strong> 08/06/2012 <br /><strong>Platform:</strong> iOS / Android | <strong>Version: </strong>Complete</p>\r\n<p class=\"tagdouble\">The Lab\'s experience in evaluating and selecting a tool for cross-platform mobile development.</p>\r\n<p>The Lab is developing a new version of our <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=69:-2010-std-iphone-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">STD prototype</a> that will be released within the Apple iTunes App Store and the Google Play Marketplace. To reduce the level of effort to develop and maintain the app on multiple mobile platforms, we had to select a development tool. The Lab designed a brief tool selection evaluation project, conducted an environmental scan of existing tools, and developed four limited prototypes to test tool functionality. We share the process and results of this evaluation and selection process as our results may be helpful to other informatics groups.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Background:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Multiple CDC programs have asked the Lab how to easily publish existing health communication content that they have developed for the web, print or digital document for use on mobile devices. The bulk of CDC\'s mobile users accessing <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov\">CDC.gov</a> use either iOS or Android so a complete mobile communication plan must address audiences on both mobile platforms as well as planning for the future uncertainty of what mobile devices may be popular in the mid-term future. In addition to this practical request from programs, there is a strategic driver for easy mobile development: The White House\'s May 23 memorandum <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/omb/egov/digital-government/digital-government-strategy.pdf\">\"Digital Government: Building a 21st Century Platform To Better Service The American People\"</a> calls for Federal programs to provide digital information across \"a variety of platforms, devices and delivery mechanisms (e.g., websites, mobile applications, and social media.)\" (p19)<br /><br />The straightforward approach would be for a program to develop apps for major platforms and add this development effort into their existing communication plan. However, different platforms can require vastly different development skillsets (e.g., ObjectiveC for iOS and Java for Android) and the new nature of mobile applications means that skillsets can shift rapidly depending on new device release and adoption. If programs can develop apps in a single method that can then be released on multiple platforms, this will reduce the direct cost of development as well as the time required to release and update mobile apps.<br /><br />The Lab has selected <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=69:-2010-std-iphone-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">2010 STD Treatment Guidelines for iPhone</a> prototype. STD is an existing mobile app prototype that the Lab developed in 2010 to test concepts around developing smartphone apps. We will publish a prototype page in the near future describing the results from this prototype, but real-time progress can be viewed on the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/Shirly\">Lab\'s wiki</a>. Before we can build the 3rd version of the STD Guidelines app, code-named \"Shirly\", we need to evaluate the many available cross-platform development tools and either select one to use during development or determine that we cannot use a cross-platform development tool.<br /><br />We documented the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/ToolSelection\">Tool Selection subproject on the Lab\'s wiki</a> and this brief review will cover the major aspects of the tool selection project as well as our conclusion: that we will use jQueryMobile and Cordova to develop the Shirly prototype.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Design of Evaluation:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Tool Selection task was broken down into a few steps:</p>\r\n<ol class=\"sum2b\">\r\n<li>Identify Assumptions</li>\r\n<li>Environmental Scan &amp; Lightweight Scoring</li>\r\n<li>Develop limited prototypes using 3-4 tools</li>\r\n<li>Evaluate</li>\r\n<li>Select</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">The Design of the evaluation process recognizes that we had a limited amount of time for tool selection so we admitted that we may not properly identify a cross-platform tool, but will select a tool to develop the Shirly prototype. Only after we complete the Shirly prototype will we have enough data to perform a full evaluation of the tool selected. Based on the time constraints of the overall project, we found it more valuable to spend a limited amount of time testing tools that will reduce the risk of choosing blindly, but not eliminate the risk of selecting the wrong tool.<br /><br />Our evaluation team was limited by available resources and time. We had a full time developer for 5 weeks, 20% of an architect for 5 weeks, 20% of a User Experience (UX) Designer and the development time to create Shirly was limited to 3 months. Our developer has direct experience with ObjectC and Java, but no experience with JavaScript nor HTML development. Our UX Designer has extensive experience in HTML but limited experience with JavaScript. As a result, many assumptions and shortcuts were knowingly taken in order to meet these time restrictions. While another project would be more focused on app feature completeness, the Lab limits its prototypes to serve as proofs of concept and only dedicates additional time if warranted. We welcome feedback from others who have selected and used similar or different tools.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Requirements &amp; Assumptions:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Before conducting an environmental scan of available tools, we developed a list of assumptions and validated them with the app product owner and subject matter experts. These assumptions, in order of priority, are:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2b\">\r\n<li>Learning Curve — our goal is to reuse existing skill sets within CDC. CDC has a diverse development community with existing skills in Java, C#/.Net and HTML web development.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li>Android and iOS support — the tool must, at a minimum, support Android 4.0 (Ice Cream Sandwich) and iOS 5.x. Many tools support other platforms (Windows Phone, WebOS, BlackBerryOS, HTML5), but our prototype focuses solely on Android and iOS. Future versions of the prototype may eventually need to support more diverse platforms, but program interest is currently on Android and iOS.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li>Price — a low price will make it easier for programs to adopt. Free/open source is optimal.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li>Native-like Functionality — the tool needs to have a reasonable user experience so that the performance is similar to that of a native-developed app for a particular platform.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li>Maintainability — the code and project structure used by the tool should be easy to modify and maintain over time.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li>Stability — the tool has to be supported by a vendor and/or community that updates and supports the tool in a timely manner.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li>Single Code Base — the tool should have the editable code of the project in a single location and source code project. A developer needing to modify platform-specific projects and files is suboptimal.</li>\r\n<br />\r\n<li>Tablet Support — although not required, support for tablet devices is a useful criteria as future versions of Shirly will be expanded to use specific functionality available to tablets.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Environmental Scan:</strong></p>\r\n<p>After establishing our set of assumptions for the tool, the project\'s Architect and Developer conducted an environmental scan of available tools and frameworks that may be worth further investigation by developing a limited prototype. <br /><br /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/ToolSelection#ToolSelection-EnvironmentalScan\">A full table of tools and identified characteristics is on the project wiki</a>. While there are dozens of available tools and sites to aid in developing mobile apps, our team focused on a smaller subset of tools based on our previous readings, participation in developer groups, participation in HHS\' <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.hdiforum.org/\">2012 HDI Data Forum</a>, <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=10:appcelerator-titanium&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">previous Lab reviews</a>, and available industry news. We were able to focus on a smaller set of 13 tools:</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2b\">\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://incubator.apache.org/cordova/\">Apache Cordova</a> (née <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://phonegap.com/\">PhoneGap</a>) with <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://jquerymobile.com/\">jQueryMobile 1.1.1</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.sencha.com/products/touch/\">SenchaTouch2</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.appcelerator.com/platform/titanium-sdk\">Appcelerator Titanium</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/flex.html\">Adobe Flex</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://xamarin.com/monotouch/\">MonoTouch</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.motorola.com/Business/US-EN/Business+Product+and+Services/Software+and+Applications/RhoMobile+Suite\">Mototole RhoMobile</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.coronalabs.com/products/corona-sdk/\">Corona SDK</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.kendoui.com/mobile.aspx\">KendoUI</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.appmobi.com/\">AppMobi</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.mosync.com/sdk\">MoSync SDK</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://mobileroadie.com/\">MobileRoadie</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.appmakr.com/\">AppMakr</a></li>\r\n<li><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.icenium.com/\">Icenium</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Since the team did not have time to perform detailed evaluations of all 13 tools, we used a lightweight scoring and evaluation to select final candidates that warranted dedicating a week of time developing a limited prototype for evaluation. The developer and architect narrowed the tools based on the assumptions above. While each tool had certain strong areas, we selected the final four based on maturity, feature set, cost and ease of use.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:10px;\">Initially we planned on selecting 3 tools to explore further by developing limited prototypes, but we found 4 tools very close: Sencha, Cordova/JQuery, MonoTouch and Appcelerator. We made the decision to spend 1 week testing each tool for a total of 1 month spent testing the tools directly. We understand that there is no way to explore all the functionality and capability of a tool in 1 week, but our goal was to use this time to learn as much as possible. If at the end of the 1 month of testing, we needed more time to decide we would revise the overall Shirly timeline. In our case, we were able to learn enough to decide on a tool that we could use to develop Shirly.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Development:</strong></p>\r\n<p>We spent one week on each limited prototype and worked toward testing a set of app features likely to be required by Shirly. Features were ranked by priority. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/ToolSelection#ToolSelection-Features\">You can view the full feature table on our project wiki</a>, and the specific feature functionality of each tool will be described below. The results of each limited prototype will be posted to our <a class=\"reg\" href=\"applab/\">AppLab</a> and the source code will be made available for others wishing to see specific development details. These \"KitchenSink\" or \"HelloWorld\" limited prototypes specifically allowed us to test the claims made by the tool communities as well as gain hands-on experience with the responsiveness, look and feel, and learning curve of each tool.<br /><br /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/Sencha+Touch%2C+Architect%2C+and+SDK+Tools+Notes\">Sencha</a> was the first tool evaluated. Sencha is a JavaScript library as well as a set of IDE-like tools that give developers a <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://catb.org/jargon/html/W/WYSIWYG.html\">WSYIWYG</a> style design editor called Sencha Architect. The Sencha JavaScript library can be used in any text editor, but Sencha Architect allows direct graphical editing. While our developer was able to test many of the features within the Sencha Architect tool and Sencha was able to meet our feature requirements, we were not able to properly package the app for deployment to Android devices. We extended the evaluation time from one week to two weeks for additional testing of the JavaScript API and Sencha Architect tool. We were never able to successfully deploy the app onto an Android device.<br /><br /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/JQuery+Mobile+with+Dreamweaver+and+PhoneGap+Evaluation+Notes\">jQueryMobile/Cordova</a> was evaluated next. While the jQueryMobile JavaScript API can be used in any text editor, our Developer chose to use DreamWeaver CS6 due to its tight integration with Cordova and DreamWeaver\'s use within the CDC development community. Cordova tools can be used to package any HTML/JavaScript web site as a native app, but we used it specifically with jQueryMobile as part of our test. It is quite possible to use other JavaScript libraries if desired, but due to the limited time of our prototype we only used jQueryMobile with Cordova. We were able to meet most of the feature functions using jQueryMobile and although the native app runs HTML and JavaScript through the mobile OS\' built-in browser the app responsiveness was acceptable. A single code base is edited as JavaScript, CSS and HTML and then the Cordova tools are used to generate an iOS and Android package. The packages are then built using xCode for iOS and the Android SDK. Build still requires a Macintosh computer as this is the only operating system that will run the Apple xCode tools. In addition to this local build procedure, Adobe offers a cloud service called <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://build.phonegap.com\">build.phonegap.com</a> that builds projects for multiple devices within Adobe\'s cloud and this allows developers to build and package apps without the necessary build tools. Although build.phonegap.com is a useful time saver, CDC policy does not yet allow use of these external build tools. The Lab will work with CDC security officers to explore how to use cloud build services, but until then will only use the local build tools provided by Cordova. While DreamWeaver is not a free tool (~$400/seat is purchased outside of the CS6 bundle) it is a common development tool and many developers within CDC already have a valid license.<br /><br /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/MonoTouch+and+Mono+for+Android+Evaluation+Notes\">MonoTouch</a> provides a stand-alone SDK and plug-in for Microsoft VisualStudio that allows developers to write code using an existing .Net language and then design the user interface using xCode for iOS or the Android SDK. This is a large benefit for programs that need to reuse existing codesets written in C#, but requires additional work to design a separate UI for each target platform. Deploying an app to a device requires a full license and were unable to deploy as we were using Mono\'s evaluation license<br /><br /><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/Appcelerator+Titanium+Studio+and+SDK+Evaluation+Notes\">Appcelerator</a>\'s SDK provides a JavaScript API and tools that can generate native apps for Android and iOS. While the JavaScript API is robust, there is no visual designer so in order for a developer to test his changes he must perform a project generation and then a build for each platform. This process can be time consuming when developing as a full build may take up to 5 minutes and a developer may need to make numerous builds to visualize each change made during development or debugging. The strength of Appcelerator is that it uses a single JavaScript code-base, yet outputs native apps for each platform. The Appcelerator app had the best performance and closest look and feel match to iOS and Android (as the apps used the exact native controls provided by the OS), but this performance was not deemed significant by the product owner.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-top:25px;\"><strong>Tool Selection &amp; Conclusion:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Each of the tools evaluated had strengths and were appropriate in certain organizations. Sencha Architect provided a good graphical editor, but it is still a new product and it was not as polished as the other tools. MonoTouch is the best if an organization has a large code base in a non-mobile language (e.g., C#) but it requires additional development time and maintenance to maintain separate UI projects for each platform. In the end our decision was down to jQueryMobile/Cordova and Appcelerator and we chose jQueryMobile due to the integration with DreamWeaver and our developer efficiency. jQueryMobile does not have the performance of Appcelerator, but the performance was deemed acceptable by the product owner. Specifically, our UX Designer has experience using DreamWeaver and can design functional mockups using JavaScript, CSS and HTML that our developer then adds additional JavaScript programming and builds directly to the device. Due to the time constraints of the Shirly project, we chose lowered development time over tool performance.<br /><br />Progress will be recorded on the project wiki and we will update this review based on our detailed experience with jQueryMobile. While each organization\'s needs are different, our experience in performing this tool evaluation should be helpful to other groups asking similar questions. Please share your experiences with the Lab through email or Twitter.</p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"References icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=97:shirly-app&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">STD Treatment Guidelines App for iOS and Android Prototype</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Apple iOS Development Guidelines - <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://developer.apple.com/library/ios/#documentation/iPhone/Conceptual/iPhoneOSProgrammingGuide/Introduction/Introduction.html\">http://bit.ly/dy9I0e</a><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.osehra.org/sites/default/files/osehra_licensing_terms_v.1.0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Apple iOS Programming Guide\"> </a><br />Accessed 2012.07.06<a name=\"reference1\"></a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Shirly Project Wiki <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/Shirly\">http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/Shirly</a> <br />Accessed 2012.08.08</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Gartner Cross-Platform Mobile Development Frameworks <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.gartner.com/id=1848214\">http://www.gartner.com/id=1848214</a> <br />11/14/2011</li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\">Informatics Structured Evaluation Tool <a class=\"reg\" href=\"downloads/irdu-guide-to-public-health-informatics-structured-evaluation-release.pdf\">http://www.phiresearchlab.org/downloads/irdu-guide-to-public-health-informatics-structured-evaluation-release.pdf</a> <br />Accessed 2012.08.08 </li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,3,'2012-08-08 14:08:00',62,'BAL','2012-09-06 15:00:33',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-08-08 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',53,0,1,'','',0,66,'robots=\nauthor='),(97,'STD Treatment Guidelines App for iOS and Android','shirly-app','','<p class=\"icon\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/std_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Shirly Prototype icon\" title=\"Shirly Prototype icon\" align=\"left\" style=\"float: left; border: 0;\" /></p>\r\n<p class=\"art_title\"><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=97:shirly-app&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">STD Treatment Guidelines App for iOS and Android</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"info\"><strong>Project Type: </strong>Prototype | <strong>Start Date:</strong> 6/20/2012 | <strong>Platform:</strong> iOS/Android/HTML5 | <strong>Version:</strong> 3.0</p>\r\n<p class=\"tag\">STD Treatment Guidelines Cross-Platform Mobile App for the iPhone and Android</p>\r\n<p>The prototype application(s) serve as a reference for doctors and related parties on the identification of and treatment regimen for STDs.   The applications are being created in collaboration with CDC\'s STD team to design mobile apps for the iOS and Android operating systems (OS) based on the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/std/treatment/2010/\">2010 STD Treatment Guidelines</a>.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p><br /> These guidelines for the treatment of persons who have or are at risk for sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) were updated by CDC after consultation with a group of professionals knowledgeable in the field of STDs who met in Atlanta on April 18–30, 2009. The information in this report updates the 2006 Guidelines for Treatment of Sexually Transmitted Diseases (MMWR 2006;55[No. RR–11]).  The prototype builds upon our knowledge gained from the earlier prototypes developed by the lab: version 1 and <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=69:-2010-std-iphone-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">version 2</a>.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>There are multiple goals of this prototype:</p>\r\n<p>1.  Gain knowledge around selecting the most appropriate software development tools to create these two applications in the most efficient and effective way.   The lab has learned a significant amount from this investigation.   Specifically, the lab conducted an environmental scan of existing tools, and developed four limited prototypes to test tool functionality. We have shared the process and results of this evaluation and selection process as our results may be helpful to other informatics groups. <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=96:shirly-tool&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\"> You can read about our insights here</a>.</p>\r\n<p>2.  Gain knowledge in using a multi-platform development tool.  As this information becomes available, we will update this document.  Our notes are always available <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/Shirly\">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p>3.  Complete the prototypes for both iOS and Android OSs.  Once thoroughly tested and evaluated by CDC\'s STD team and its partners, IRDA will collaborate with CDC staff throughout the agency to assist in transitioning the prototypes into production-quality applications, suitable for the Apple iTunes App Store and Google Play (Android App Store).</p>\r\n<p>4.  In the process of transitioning from prototype to production, IRDA hopes to gain 1st-hand experience in the processes required to publish a CDC-developed app in <a class=\"reg\" href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps\">Google Play</a> (Android app store).  This information will be parallel to what was learned in publishing to the <a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=92:iphone-app-dev&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Apple iTunes AppStore</a>, but for a different platform.</p>\r\n<p>5.  To share our experiences with other CDC programs and public health partners so that they can extend their health communications material onto mobile devices in a cost and time effective way. This prototype seeks to establish reusable patterns, tools and resources that others can take and accelerate their cross-platform mobile development needs.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The current features that are functional in this version of the prototype include:</p>\r\n<p>•    Condition Quick Pick: allows doctors and clinicians to quickly look up conditions and their treatments. Easy access to condition descriptions is also provided.</p>\r\n<p>•    Slide-in Main Menu: provides the main options of the application in a highly accessible slide-in menu. No matter where the user is within the application, the main menu is only one tap away.</p>\r\n<p>•    Full STD Guidelines: the full STD guidelines presented in an easily navigable format. The user may drill down to any section of the 2010 STD Treatment Guidelines.</p>\r\n<p>•    PDF of STD Guidelines: the user may access the PDF document via his/her mobile Safari browser.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>As new features become available, we will update this document to the reflect the changes.  If you would like to test out the applications for yourself, please feel free to contact <a class=\"reg\" href=\"mailto:informaticslab@cdc.gov\">InformaticsLab@cdc.gov</a> to obtain the passphrase to access the R&amp;D Lab’s <a class=\"reg\" href=\"applab/\">AppLab</a>. We welcome any feedback. Please email <a class=\"reg\" href=\"mailto:informaticslab@cdc.gov\">InformaticsLab@cdc.gov</a> directly or <a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/jira/secure/CreateIssue.jspa?pid=10400&amp;issuetype=7\">submit a user story with an idea directly to our project.</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=\"sum2\"><img src=\"images/brief_reviews/screenshot_icon.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"screenshots icon\" title=\"screenshots icon\" align=\"middle\" /> Screenshots <span style=\"font-size:10px; color:#777575; padding-left:3px;\">(view screenshots by clicking the thumbnails below)</span> <br /><br /><img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <a href=\"images/prototypes/std3_row1.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"test\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/std3_row1.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"test\" title=\"PTT Screenshot #1\" width=\"270\" height=\"207\" style=\"border: 1px solid black;\" /></a> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /> <img src=\"images/stories/pixel_shim.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"spacer\" width=\"5\" height=\"1\" /><a href=\"images/prototypes/std3_row1.png\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"test\"><img src=\"images/prototypes/std3_row2.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"STD condition quick pick\" title=\"PTT Screenshot #1\" width=\"270\" height=\"207\" style=\"border: 1px solid black;\" /></a></p>\r\n<ul class=\"sum2\">\r\n<img src=\"images/stories/project_resources.png\" border=\"0\" alt=\"References icon\" title=\"References icon\" align=\"absMiddle\" /> References\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/std/treatment/2010/\">2010 CDC Treatment Guidelines</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=69:-2010-std-iphone-&amp;catid=1:prototypes&amp;Itemid=3\">Overview of previous STD Guidelines prototype (versions 1 and 2)</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=92:iphone-app-dev&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">iPhone Application Development Lessons Learned Brief Review</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=96:shirly-tool&amp;catid=3:brief-reviews&amp;Itemid=5\">Cross-Platform Mobile Development Tool Selection Brief Review</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"applab/std_guide3.php\">Direct download of current STD prototypes from AppLab</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/viewvc/informaticslab/shirly/\">Source code for current prototype (for developers)</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/confluence/display/LAB/Shirly\">Collaboration wiki for current prototype (for developers)</a></li>\r\n<li class=\"sum3\"><a class=\"reg\" href=\"http://code.phiresearchlab.org/jira/browse/SHIRLY\">User Story Issue Tracker for current prototype (for developers)</a></li>\r\n</ul>',1,1,0,1,'2012-09-04 05:16:11',62,'TGS','2012-09-06 14:57:05',62,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2012-09-05 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','','show_title=0\nlink_titles=0\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=0\nshow_print_icon=0\nshow_email_icon=0\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=',47,0,1,'','',0,54,'robots=\nauthor=');
